<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DeBartolos Negotiate Over 49ers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Despite a slow and sometimes bumpy  
negotiating process, Eddie DeBartolo's spokesman said an agreement 
is still likely between DeBartolo and his sister over who will 
control the San Francisco 49ers. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, DeBartolo reportedly said he would return to the  
49ers if he and his sister, Denise DeBartolo York, could not reach 
a deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``They still haven't reached a final agreement. I'm still  
hopeful this will be resolved soon,'' spokesman Rick Rice told the 
San Francisco Examiner in an interview published Wednesday. 
``Whatever resolution there is, we know it's going to be a 
decoupling of the assets. Eddie and Denise are going to have 
separate businesses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rice said the July announcement of a deal that would end  
DeBartolo's control of the team was premature. Talks between 
DeBartolo and Denise DeBartolo York are ongoing, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	DeBartolo York's spokesman, Sam Singer, also said both sides  
were continuing to talk. 
</P>
<P>
	The slow pace of talks does not mean a final accord is unlikely,  
Rice said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sportscaster Al Michaels said during ABC's ``Monday Night  
Football'' broadcast that DeBartolo told him he expected to return 
to the team if there was no deal by Feb. 1, the date the National 
Football League lifts its suspension of him. 
</P>
<P>
	In late July, the team owner, Edward J. DeBartolo Corp. said an  
agreement had been reached between DeBartolo and his sister, giving 
DeBartolo York control of the club. Rice immediately called news of 
a deal ``premature.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DeBartolo was suspended from the NFL earlier this year after he  
pleaded guilty to a federal felony in a Louisiana 
gambling-and-bribery case involving that state's ex-Gov. Edwin 
Edwards. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
