<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Judge Chosen for Soliah Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A former federal judge has been picked to  
preside over the trial of the Midwestern housewife accused of 
trying to bomb police cars two decades ago when she was a member of 
a radical group. 
</P>
<P>
	Superior Court Judge James M. Ideman was appointed Tuesday to  
the case after the defense vetoed the first choice, Superior Court 
Judge J.D. Smith, who is a former police officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the defendant, formerly known as Kathleen Ann Soliah,  
officially became Sara Jane Olson in court records -- the name she 
adopted as a fugitive and has lived under as a doctor's wife and 
mother of three in St. Paul, Minn. 
</P>
<P>
	``This case was formerly the People vs. Kathleen Ann Soliah,''  
said Superior Court Judge Larry P. Fidler, who presided at the 
hearing. ``Now it will be the People vs. Sara Jane Olson, a.k.a. 
Kathleen Ann Soliah.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the name she was married under, the name her children  
know her by,'' said her attorney, Susan Jordan. ``It is the name 
she has lived under for 23 years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota granted Ms. Olson's petition for a name change this  
month. 
</P>
<P>
	A pretrial hearing was set for Sept. 13. Ms. Olson, 52, will be  
entitled to a trial within 60 days after that date. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Olson, who is free on $1 million bail, is charged with  
planting bombs under two Los Angeles police cars in 1975. Neither 
bomb went off. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors contend the effort was retaliation for a shootout  
with police that killed six of her fellow members of the Symbionese 
Liberation Army, the radical leftist group best known for 
kidnapping newspaper heiress Patricia Hearst in 1974. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's innocent and that will be her defense,'' Jordan said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
