<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Want To Pay Down Debt? But How? / On the Money  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The news that more Americans are paying down  
their credit card debt might make other consumers think about doing 
the same. And financial advisers say lowering debt should be the 
first step in a household budget program. 
</P>
<P>
	But anyone thinking about attacking their debts should go about  
it carefully. What may look like a great deal on credit may not be 
so hot after all. And taking out a home equity loan or selling 
stock may not be the answer, either. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers who want to cut their debt ``need to come up with a  
plan, to sit and figure out all their options,'' said Howard 
Dvorkin, president of Consolidated Credit Counseling Services Inc., 
a not-for-profit group based in Fort Lauderdale, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	Dvorkin and other advisers warn consumers against the temptation  
of low introductory interest rates that credit card issuers have 
offered for some time. Issuers market these rates -- some as low as 
2.9 percent -- as a great way to pay off debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Some people think they'll grab a low rate, transfer balances  
from other accounts and, as the introductory rate expires, transfer 
to another issuer with a similar deal. And switch again after that. 
</P>
<P>
	In reality, few people card-hop, according to Dvorkin. ``A lot  
of people have the intention, but I don't think it happens a lot,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	One reason is many customers just go ahead and pay a higher rate  
after the introductory, or teaser, rate expires. Others call up the 
card issuer and try to negotiate a better deal. 
</P>
<P>
	But consumers can't count on that happening. Issuers are  
rethinking their strategy, and it may become harder to get lower 
rates. 
</P>
<P>
	``Over the next six months, banks will have pressure to maintain  
significant earnings growth,'' Dvorkin said. ``I question if these 
companies will be as flexible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Late August brought word from Bank One, one of the nation's  
biggest banking companies, that its earnings would fall because of 
weakness in its credit card business. Bank One and other issuers 
are finding that more Americans are paying down their debt, and at 
a faster pace. 
</P>
<P>
	But there is still more than $1.3 trillion in consumer credit  
outstanding, and for the time being, low-interest offers are still 
arriving in the mail. Consumers shouldn't sign up unless they've 
considered how much it will cost. 
</P>
<P>
	If you're not a mathematical whiz, the Internet has resources to  
help you figure out how expensive credit cards are. (Some are 
provided by financial services companies hoping you'll do business 
with them). 
</P>
<P>
	SmartMoney magazine has a calculator in its Web site  
(www.smartmoney.com) to compare deals from different issuers. It 
can show that a rate that looks good for the first six months may 
in the long run not be worth it. 
</P>
<P>
	Let's say you have an average balance of $3,000. You get a card  
with a six-month rate of 4.9 percent, which becomes 15 percent when 
the teaser expires. Over the first year, you'll pay $298 in 
interest, and your rate will really work out to about 9.94 percent. 
If the rate becomes 18 percent, your interest is $344 and the rate 
works out to 11.46 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	After that first year, the rate goes to a solid 15 percent or 18  
percent, or whatever the offer's terms stipulate. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Stephen Brobeck, executive director of the Consumer  
Federation of America, ``the first strategy that should be 
considered is reducing one's expenditures'' and diverting that 
money to debt payment. 
</P>
<P>
	Start by looking at what you buy and asking if you really need  
it. Not just a new car or big-screen TV, but smaller items. Do you 
buy a $1 cup of coffee or $3 latte? Buy lunch or brown-bag it? Just 
a few dollars spent every day can turn into $1,000 over the course 
of a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Many people, including financial advisers, believe a home equity  
loan is a good way to pay off expensive debt. Dvorkin disagrees. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're turning unsecured debt into secured debt, which is not  
a very wise choice in case something happens down the road ... they 
can go after your house,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Another possibility is to sell mutual funds or stocks. But  
selling securities means capital gains taxes, and, if you're 
thinking about taking money out of a retirement account, big 
penalties and a possible move into a higher tax bracket. 
</P>
<P>
	The best thing to do may be to go get some help. Ask a  
professional adviser or credit counseling service about the best 
way to pay down your debts. 
</P>
<P>
	Counseling services are found in the Yellow Pages and on the  
Internet. Even if there isn't one located right near you, many 
offer their services nationwide. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
