<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Head Seeks Buchanan Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican Party chairman Jim Nicholson,  
hoping to avoid a high-profile defection, has requested to meet 
privately with Pat Buchanan before the GOP presidential candidate 
decides whether to bolt to the Reform Party. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan has agreed to the session, which is being scheduled for  
later this month, his top strategist and sister, Bay Buchanan said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jim Nicholson has personally contacted me and asked to set up  
a meeting with Pat, which we're attempting to do,'' Bay Buchanan 
said in a telephone interview. Nicholson did not say why he wanted 
to talk to Buchanan, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, had  
said Nicholson wants to personally urge Buchanan to remain 
Republican. However, Nicholson's aides said they didn't know 
anything about the meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``He talks with the presidential candidates all the time,'' said  
spokesman Mike Collins. The chairman was on vacation and 
unavailable, Collins said. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan, a political commentator and former Nixon White House  
aide, is a harsh critic of the GOP establishment, which he says has 
forsaken its conservative roots. 
</P>
<P>
	Though he lags in polls and would not be assured the Reform  
Party nomination, Buchanan could siphon social conservative votes 
from the eventual Republican nominee if he ran as a third-party 
candidate. He won the New Hampshire primary in 1996 and gave 
President Bush a scare in the 1992 primaries with his potent blend 
of social conservatism and populist, anti-trade rhetoric. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican Party officials privately question whether Buchanan's  
departure would have a major impact. Some argue that his trade 
views would attract a fair share of hard-hat Democrats hurt by the 
Clinton administration's free-trade policies. Others say his 
showing so far in the 2000 campaign proves that Buchanan has lost 
his political muscle. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that Nicholson is smart to reach out and try to keep  
all Republican moving in the same direction,'' said GOP strategist 
Ed Gillespie. ``You don't want to have someone who's been a 
Republican staffer, a Republican candidate and who's spoken at 
Republican conventions in past cycles leave the party in anger.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``But the fact is Buchanan has not had the run he did the first  
two times,'' Gillespie said. ``I don't think you'd see droves of 
Republicans turning in their registration cards saying, `Cancel me. 
I'm going Reform Party.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholson placed the call Tuesday, the same day that officials  
close to Buchanan revealed that he had intensified discussions 
about bolting. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pat will listen to what he has to say and will take it under  
consideration,'' said Bay Buchanan, who confirmed Nicholson's 
request after GOP officials circulated word of the meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	A top Buchanan adviser, speaking on condition of anonymity, said  
the candidate is proceeding as if he will bolt the party -- even 
though a final decision has not been made. The only thing that 
would stop him, the adviser said, ``is if the wall suddenly went 
up'' and Buchanan decided at the last minute he couldn't abandon 
the GOP. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the signs:  
</P>
<P>
	--Bay Buchanan is calling fund-raisers and state chairman to  
gauge their reaction to a possible Reform Party race. 
</P>
<P>
	--The campaign's Internet site had been touting news stories  
about a Reform Party bid, a practice Bay Buchanan said she ended. 
</P>
<P>
	-- In a staff meeting this week, advisers discussed how they  
would organize an announcement rally if he bolted. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Both Buchanans are also studying the arcane Reform Party  
rules. 
</P>
<P>
	His decision is expected to be announced in October, though  
Buchanan will tantalize the party throughout a September publicity 
tour to promote his upcoming book, ``A Republic, Not an Empire: 
Reclaiming America's Destiny.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement released by his publisher, a headline reads,  
``Why would Pat Buchanan break ranks with the Republican Party?'' 
</P>
<P>
	If he does leave, Buchanan would not be assured of the  
presidential nomination in the fractious Reform Party. Backers of 
Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura have wrested the party leadership from 
associates of party founder Ross Perot. 
</P>
<P>
	While Perot allies are urging Buchanan to run, Ventura has been  
cool to the idea. Perot backers have quietly suggested to Buchanan 
that the Texas millionaire would not stand in his way if he sought 
the nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reform Party nominee will have access to more than $12  
million in federal funding, millions more than Buchanan is expected 
to raise as a GOP candidate. His GOP campaign is in debt, 
marginalized by a poor showing at the Aug. 14 Iowa straw poll. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
