<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Rise; Dow Gains 55.09 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks moved higher today, reviving after four  
straight declines in the Dow Jones industrials sent some investors 
on a search for bargains. 
</P>
<P>
	In late afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow was up 55.09  
at 10,884.37. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's  
500 index was up 4.70 at 1,325.11, and the Nasdaq composite index 
was up 11.78 at 2,751.13. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow began the day nearly 500 points below its record close  
of 11,326.04 reached just last Wednesday. While traders expected 
the big decline to lure some buyers, few market analysts expect a 
major rally any time soon. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market has likely set the table for a rocky month of  
September,'' said Brian Belski, chief investment strategist at 
George K. Baum &AMP; Co., citing a lack of market leadership and the 
persistent worries about higher interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, some strength today came from technology issues. Intel  
rose 2 5/16 to 84 3/8 after unveiling a new microprocessor chip 
intended for use in devices that route information across the 
Internet. Analysts said the development raised expectations that 
the boom of the Internet will feed continued growth at computer 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	In a similar vein, IBM was up 3 at 127 9/16. IBM and Cisco said  
Tuesday they will jointly provide networking equipment and services 
to companies looking to do business on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	International Paper also contributed to the Dow's strength,  
gaining 1 11/16 to 48 3/4 after PaineWebber raised its rating on the 
stock. 
</P>
<P>
	Promus Hotel Corp. rose 2 7/8 to 31 15/16 amid reports that Hilton  
Hotels is negotiating a deal to acquire it. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board today provided the latest sign that the  
U.S. economy continues to grow at a brisk pace. The research 
group's Index of Leading Economic Indicators, a key barometer of 
future economic activity, rose 0.3 percent in July. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Conference Board's report was counterbalanced by a  
Commerce Department report that showed home building and other 
construction spending was surprisingly weak in July. 
</P>
<P>
	Fears that robust economic growth will encourage the Federal  
Reserve to raise interest rates for a third time this year have 
shadowed the market in the past few sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks rose sharply after the Fed's second rate increase as  
investors temporarily raised their hopes that the central bank may 
leave rates untouched for the rest of the year. But as fear 
returned to Wall Street, prices turned lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 7-to-6 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 556.2 million shares, 
slightly behind Tuesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index was up 2.53 at 430.36.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
