<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MIT Student Dies From Laughing Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- An MIT junior found dead in his dorm  
room apparently died while trying to get high by inhaling laughing 
gas from a plastic bag, officials said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The body of Richard Guy, a 22-year-old from Mission Viejo,  
Calif., was found early Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The medical examiner said the physics major died of asphyxiation  
as a result of nitrous oxide intoxication. Nitrous oxide displaces 
oxygen in the blood, and when used as a recreational drug it can 
cause dizziness, light-headedness and euphoria. 
</P>
<P>
	Police were trying to determine where Guy obtained the nitrous  
oxide, which is not a controlled substance and is often used as a 
painkiller by dentists. 
</P>
<P>
	Guy was alone at the time of his death, and school officials  
believe he was inhaling the gas to get high, said Ken Campbell, a 
spokesman for the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're treating it like an accident and that's because we have  
no evidence of a suicide,'' he said this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Classes aren't scheduled to begin at MIT until Sept. 7, but  
freshmen and some upperclassmen had already moved into their rooms. 
</P>
<P>
	In September 1997, 18-year-old freshman Scott Krueger died three  
days after he was found in an alcohol-induced coma on a fraternity 
floor. No one was prosecuted, but in July the school revoked the 
diploma of a man who bought alcohol consumed by Krueger and other 
pledges. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just a shame,'' said Chris Johnson, 19, an MIT sophomore  
from Columbia, Tenn. ``Some of the smartest kids in the world are 
here. Maybe they think they're too smart to suffer the 
consequences.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
