<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arkansas' Hall Pleads Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FAYETTEVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- Arkansas defensive end Carlos Hall  
pleaded guilty today to charges in two counties, including an 
accusation that he stole checks from the university. He drew 
probation on all charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall pleaded guilty in Washington County to theft of property  
after being accused of stealing $220 worth of checks made out to 
the University of Arkansas. In Pope County, he pleaded guilty to 
charges related to a July 10 traffic accident in which a woman was 
injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Clearing up his legal problems could lead to his being  
reinstated to the Razorbacks' football team. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are relieved it has been settled,'' coach Houston Nutt said  
in a statement made to the Jacksonville Patriot newspaper . 
``Carlos has been under in-house discipline for over a month. He's 
been doing everything he can to do it the right way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Any decision on Hall's returning to the team would be made  
later, the university said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall, who initially was accused with stealing three checks from  
a university mailroom and forging them, was ordered to make $220 in 
restitution and perform 200 hours of community service in the 
Fayetteville case. 
</P>
<P>
	He also was ordered to pay $150 in court costs.  
</P>
<P>
	Hall was suspended from the Razorbacks after being charged this  
summer. He faced a Sept. 20 hearing in Pope County, but a clerk 
there said Hall's case had been settled today. Hall was sentenced 
to probation, which Hall lawyer Bob White said would be 
administered out of Washington County, where the university is 
based. 
</P>
<P>
	White said Hall would be sentenced to 3 1/2 years' probation in the  
Pope County case, 168 hours of community service and ordered to pay 
$1,600 in fines and court costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Washington County Circuit Court said prosecutors today  
presented only a theft of property charge -- a misdemeanor -- before 
Judge William Storey. Hall initially had been accused of forgery. 
</P>
<P>
	The charges, made July 20, said Hall stole three checks totaling  
$220 from a university mailroom, then endorsed and cashed them. The 
checks had been made out to the university. 
</P>
<P>
	At Russellville, he was accused of leaving the scene of an  
accident in which a person was injured and with driving under the 
influence of alcohol. The accident on Interstate 40 near 
Russellville and Hall was charged in Conway, 40 miles away, after 
stopping to fix a flat tire. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall, 6-foot-4 and 260 pounds, is a third-year sophomore. Last  
year, he had 45 tackles, 23 by himself and 11 for losses. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
