<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clintons Tour Central New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SENECA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) -- There wasn't much the rangers at the  
Women's Rights National Historical Park could tell their prominent 
guest that he didn't already know. ``When you're looking for 
work,'' one said, ``you can give us a call.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, I can work for cheap,'' President Clinton said with a  
smile. ``I've got a good pension.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president, who can count on an annual $151,800 presidential  
pension when he leaves the White House in 2001, and first lady 
Hillary Rodham Clinton took a tour Wednesday of historic sites in 
central New York, including a house where abolitionist Harriet 
Tubman lived. 
</P>
<P>
	They also visited the birthplace of the women's rights movement  
-- the Wesleyan Chapel -- where in 1848 a group of women and male 
supporters issued the Declaration of Sentiments, a tract based on 
the Declaration of Independence calling for equal rights for women. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons walked along a wall that had the declaration  
chiseled into its face and was covered by a falling sheen of water, 
discussing fine points of the women's rights movement with rangers 
Maryellen Snyder and Leroy Renninger. 
</P>
<P>
	Having recently read a biography of abolitionist William Lloyd  
Garrison, an early supporter of women's rights, Clinton was 
familiar with much of the history behind the declaration. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope our coming here will raise the visibility so more  
Americans will come,'' Clinton told reporters traveling with him. 
``There are things here that every American should know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In full vacation mode, the president declined to answer  
questions about a new investigation of the Branch Davidians 
incident in Waco, Texas, or the attack on the U.N. compound in 
Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons were enjoying sunny skies, the shimmering blue  
Skaneateles Lake by the borrowed estate where they were staying in 
the town of the same name, and excited crowds wherever they went. 
Daughter Chelsea stayed behind. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm having a great time,'' said Mrs. Clinton. ``It reminds me  
so much of where I spent my childhood because I spent every summer 
at the little lake in Northeast Pennsylvania. The nights were cool, 
and the mornings were cool.... It's so nostalgic, I called my 
mother last night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons began the day with a stop at a specialty foods shop  
in downtown Skaneateles that featured chocolates made by Albert 
Kumin, who was White House pastry chef for President Carter. 
</P>
<P>
	A crowd of some 70 people gathered outside and the Clintons  
lingered to shake hands and sign autographs. The president obliged 
a woman on the other side of the police tape by placing a letter in 
the mailbox for her. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're off on an excursion,'' the president told the crowd.  
</P>
<P>
	The crowd scene and visits to historical sites may not seem very  
relaxing for a vacationing couple. But they did seem like good 
politics. Mrs. Clinton is building up for a campaign for Senate 
from New York next year. 
</P>
<P>
	All of the historic sites were on the America's Treasures tour  
Mrs. Clinton took last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons spent more than one-half hour in the home of  
William H. Seward, secretary of state under presidents Lincoln and 
Johnson and the prime mover behind the purchase of Alaska, which 
was called ``Seward's Folly'' at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	Before heading to scenic Seneca Falls, the Clintons stopped at  
the site of a home Tubman moved to after the Civil War. Tubman 
helped conduct 300 slaves to freedom along the underground railroad 
and spied for the North. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons also visited the McClintock House, where the  
Declaration of Sentiments was drafted, in nearby Waterloo. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
