<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Intel Introduces New Internet Chip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Intel Corp. is making a big move into the  
fast-growing Internet networking business, signaling trouble for 
some smaller rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel unveiled a new chip on Wednesday to power the equipment  
that routes information across the Internet. The move is an 
ambitious bid by the world's largest maker of microprocessors to 
expand beyond its core business of making chips for personal 
computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel's new ``network processor'' is intended to replace more  
expensive chips as the brains of switches and routers that shepherd 
data through corporate networks and the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The move prompted Wall Street investors to reconsider some  
smaller companies that compete in the space. Shares of network 
chips supplier MMC Networks Inc. dropped 13 percent, down $4.12 1/2 at 
$26.75, in trading on the Nasdaq Stock Market. MMC also was hit by 
a decision Tuesday by IBM, a major customer, to stop selling 
networking equipment and focus on selling chips and other parts. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel, meanwhile, rose 2 percent Wednesday, up $1.25 at $83.43 3/4.  
</P>
<P>
	IBM, for its part, is aggressively defending its sales of  
networking chips. The company plans to announce Thursday a new 
family of networking chips that it will start selling to makers of 
communications equipment, including Nortel Networks Corp. and 
Alcatel, of France. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM also formed a new research and development unit devoted to  
improving its chips. And the company is spending $100 million on a 
new unit to boost sales to communications equipment makers, 
according to a source close to IBM. An IBM spokesman declined to 
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel has good reason to want to expand its chip business. While  
sales of desktop PCs continue to rise, demand is slowing. Intel's 
unit sales of chips are increasing only about 10 percent a year, 
less than half the growth rate of just four years ago. At the same 
time, the average price Intel charges for computer chips has 
dropped sharply as a result of industry price wars. 
</P>
<P>
	To help buoy the company's profits and sales, Intel is pushing  
to sell more lucrative chips, such as those used in powerful 
business machines at the hub of computer networks. Wednesday's move 
into networking chips is the latest such foray to augment its PC 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is simply further evidence of Intel's scramble to  
diversify,'' said Drew Peck, a financial analyst with Boston-based 
Cowen &AMP; Co. ``It's just one relatively small element of a much 
bigger effort at Intel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Intel, by far the largest chip maker with $26 billion in sales  
last year, is seeking to exploit its size. Intel can keep prices 
low because of its large-scale manufacturing operations, a strategy 
that has helped the company get its microprocessors into 90 percent 
of the world's personal computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel said it already has lined up several major customers of  
its Internet chips, including network equipment makers Cisco 
Systems Inc., Newbridge Networks Corp. and Cabletron Systems Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel also said it would invest $200 million in small companies  
that are developing products using the chips. 
</P>
<P>
	The company stressed that its new ``IX Architecture'' system  
would help makers of networking equipment easily add new features. 
Intel's new chip design ``will help customers deliver faster and 
smarter networks on Internet time,'' Mark Christensen, head of 
Intel's Network Communications unit, said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The unveiling was part of a flurry of announcements by Intel at  
its annual conference for developers this week in Palm Springs, 
Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Intel unmasked its Coppermine Pentium III processor,  
an enhanced version of its high-end PC chip, to be released in 
October. It will operate at a speed of at least 700 megahertz. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel also demonstrated its much-touted Merced chip for powerful  
business machines, which the company has been developing with 
Hewlett-Packard Corp. and intends to start shipping in volume by 
the middle of next year. 





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
