<DOCNO> APW19990901.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 06:40:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Denver Post Names New Editor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Glenn Guzzo, managing editor of the Akron (Ohio)  
Beacon Journal, is taking over as editor of The Denver Post, 
replacing Dennis A. Britton, who has been editor and executive vice 
president for 3 1/2 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Post Publisher Gerald E. Grilly said Tuesday that Guzzo will  
start around Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Grilly did not explain Britton's departure in detail.  
</P>
<P>
	``I thought a change was appropriate,'' Grilly said. ``Dennis  
has been a valued member of the Post's management team and we wish 
him well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Guzzo, 48, a Detroit native, has been managing editor of the  
Beacon Journal since 1993. The Knight Ridder newspaper won a 
Pulitzer Prize for public service in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	He was vice president/news for Knight Ridder from 1989 to 1993,  
an editor at The Philadelphia Inquirer for eight years and an 
editor at the Fort Worth (Texas) Star-Telegram for three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Britton, 58, came to The Denver Post in March 1996 after rising  
through the San Jose (Calif.) Mercury News, the Los Angeles Times 
and the Chicago Sun-Times, where he was editor and executive vice 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	Britton also worked at the John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur  
Foundation in Chicago, and co-authored two books on congressional 
and presidential dealings with the media. 
</P>
<P>
	The Denver Post, a Media News Group newspaper controlled by Dean  
Singleton, has been locked in a bitter, years-long newspaper war 
with the Denver Rocky Mountain News, a Scripps Howard newspaper. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
