<HEADLINE> Dennis Washes Away Sea Turtle Nests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KURE BEACH, N.C. (AP) -- The high surf kicked up by Hurricane  
Dennis washed away dozens of sea turtle nests during what had been 
one of the state's best nesting seasons on record. 
</P>
<P>
	The state's primary nesting turtles are loggerheads, which the  
government classifies as a threatened species. 
</P>
<P>
	The size of the loss was still unclear as the state's network of  
volunteer turtle trackers fanned out along the coast to assess the 
toll. Damage found so far varies greatly from beach to beach, with 
Oak Island losing 61 of its 105 turtle nests and Wrightsville Beach 
losing none. 
</P>
<P>
	Susi Clontz, the sea turtle coordinator for Kure Beach and  
Carolina Beach, said the first few nests she checked this week were 
gone without even a trace of the wooden stakes and yellow ribbon 
she had used to mark them. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of her nests did survive. ``I was so happy to see one I  
did a little dance,'' she said. ``Last year, I lost them all during 
Bonnie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before Dennis, almost every beach in the state had reported  
above-average nest totals this year, said Ruth Boettcher, 
coordinator of the N.C. Sea Turtle Project, the network of 
volunteers. 
</P>
<P>
	Fewer than half of them had hatched before Dennis sent its  
heaviest surf ashore Saturday through Monday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Turtle nests also are washed away during high tides that  
correspond with a new moon, Boettcher said, but Dennis struck a 
population struggling to recover. 
</P>
<P>
	``The main objective to recovering a species, getting them back  
to healthy enough numbers, so they can recover from these kinds of 
catastrophic events,'' she said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
