<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Magazine Lists Mom-Friendly Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- IBM helps employees screen new nannies. Texas  
Instruments sends mobile toy stores around its offices to help 
workers save on holiday shopping time. 
</P>
<P>
	More and more companies are going the extra mile to help their  
workers, according to Working Mother magazine's 14th annual list of 
the best 100 companies for working moms. 
</P>
<P>
	``Companies are really listening to what their employees have to  
say,'' said Deborah Wilburn, executive editor of the magazine. 
``It's not so much, 'What are the hours that you're in the office', 
but 'Are you getting the job done','' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The magazine is published its annual list -- seen as a badge of  
honor in Corporate America -- Wednesday in its October issue. It can 
also be seen on the company's Web site, www.workingmother.com. 
</P>
<P>
	The magazine does not rank the 100 companies, but names 10  
companies as exceptionally progressive: Bank of America, Cigna, 
Deutsche Bank, Fannie Mae, First Tennessee Bank, IBM, Eli Lilly, 
Lincoln Financial Group, Lotus Development and Prudential Financial 
Services. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM has been among the top 10 for 12 years -- longer than any  
other company. 
</P>
<P>
	The computer manufacturer believes its secret to success is  
really not a secret at all, just logic, creativity and 
responsiveness to workers' changing needs. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, when the company realized some parents preferred to  
have at-home child care, it launched a pilot program in New York 
and North Carolina that helps screen nannies for their employees. 
The program began last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you have a workplace that is still reflective of what it  
looked like in the '50s and '60s, with the same kinds of rules in 
place, you're not going to be very appealing a place for women to 
come to work,'' said Ted Childs, vice president of global work 
force diversity. 
</P>
<P>
	Other companies on the list are also using creative solutions.  
</P>
<P>
	At Bristol-Myers Squibb, employees can receive free baby  
formula, mailed to them in installments, for their baby's first 
year of life. 
</P>
<P>
	At Chase Manhattan Bank, a backup child care service provides a  
safety net for parents whose baby-sitter may call in sick or fail 
to show up on time. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, nearly 3,000 children were cared for in the care  
center, the largest such corporate facility in the country. The 
center has also won prestigious accreditation by the National 
Association for the Education of Young Children. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, companies are beginning to wake up to the need for  
elder care services, said Ellen Galinsky, president of the Families 
and Work Institute. 
</P>
<P>
	``As our employee base continues to age, we learn from our  
employees,'' explained Mary Anne Detmer, diversity and work-life 
manager at Rochester-based Eastman Kodak, which offers backup elder 
care as well as free in-home assessments of elderly dependents. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the struggle to balance work-life issues is far from  
over. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 90 percent of companies allow workers to take time off to  
attend school events, and half let workers stay home with mildly 
ill children without using vacations or sick days, according to a 
1998 study by the Families and Work Institute. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet only 9 percent of companies offer child care at or near the  
workplace, 33 percent offer maternity leaves more than 13 weeks 
long, and 23 percent offer elder care resource and referral 
services. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 08:21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Machinists Prepare To Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Even as Machinists union leaders touted the  
Boeing Co.'s contract proposal as the best in the aerospace 
industry, the company was engaging in a large-scale ad campaign to 
persuade workers to vote today. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just not taking this for granted,'' Boeing chairman Phil  
Condit said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Machinists accept the contract, it could encourage other  
unions to make similar demands when they negotiate future 
agreements, because the issues at stake mirror battles occurring 
throughout the U.S. manufacturing and aerospace industries. 
</P>
<P>
	The company ran double full-page ads -- outlining contract basics  
and urging union members to vote -- in Seattle's two daily 
newspapers on Tuesday. The ads also ran today in the Seattle 
Post-Intelligencer and others were scheduled for newspapers serving 
cities with substantial Boeing work forces, including Spokane, 
Everett, Tacoma, Bellevue and Kent in Washington; Portland, Ore.; 
and Wichita, Kan. 
</P>
<P>
	Condit appeared in TV ads Tuesday, telling workers that ``after  
intense and thoughtful negotiations, we have a contract that we're 
proud to present to employees for ratification. It offers 
unprecedented job security, the best wages and retirement plan in 
the industry, and world-class benefits. It's the right thing for 
employees and the company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Condit wasn't getting any argument from the union.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'll say it again: That's the best contract in aerospace,  
period. By far. Talk to anyone around the country,'' said Bill 
Johnson, president of International Association of Machinists 
District Lodge 751. 
</P>
<P>
	The 44,000 Machinists union members will vote at union halls  
today on the 44-month contract. 
</P>
<P>
	There was some grumbling on the eve of the ratification vote --  
concerns about job-security provisions and pension benefits for 
those already retired. But union leaders remained convinced that 
the contract was a good one. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've negotiated what we feel is a very good contract,'' said  
Dick Schneider, who led the union's bargaining effort. ``We 
recommended the tentative agreement to our members and it will be 
up to them whether to accept or reject it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If the membership turns the offer down, ``then we strike and try  
to go back to the table,'' Schneider said. 
</P>
<P>
	A walkout by Machinists in the Seattle area, Spokane, Wichita  
and Portland, Ore., ``would greatly harm'' the company, Schneider 
said. ``I can tell you that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing spokesman Peter Conte said Boeing is optimistic about the  
vote. 
</P>
<P>
	The current contract expires at 12:01 a.m. Thursday. The  
Machinists have struck over two of the last three contracts, most 
recently for 69 days in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed contract would continue Boeing's traditional  
five-day work week, with workers paid overtime for weekend shifts, 
and it makes no increases in member costs for medical benefits. It 
offers a 25 percent increase in pension benefits. The deal provides 
a 10 percent signing bonus worth $4,400 to the average worker, and 
annual wage increases of 4 percent, 4 percent and 3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	It also strengthens union oversight of proposals for  
subcontracting work to outside companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Job security is the key issue for the union. Boeing plans to  
deliver a record 620 planes in 1999, but -- under pressure from 
rival European consortium Airbus Industrie -- has been working for 
over a year to streamline its operation. 
</P>
<P>
	Union naysayers shrug off a provision that guarantees ``no  
layoffs as the direct result of subcontracting or offloading,'' 
noting other language that exempts ``commercial airplane strategic 
work placement requirements.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We tried to get a total ban on outsourcing, but obviously that  
wasn't there,'' Schneider said. ``We feel the language we have 
attained affords us protection.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another concern was pension benefits for more than 8,000  
already-retired members. The goal was a tripling of benefits -- from 
$40 a month per year of service to $120 -- but negotiators settled 
for a 25 percent increase to $50 per year of service. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
