<HEADLINE> North Face CEO Steps Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARBONDALE, Colo. (AP) -- Jim Fifield, president and CEO of The  
North Face Inc. has resigned after an agreement to sell the alpine 
sporting goods company fell through. 
</P>
<P>
	The company announced today that its agreement to be purchased  
by TNF Acquisition LLC, an affiliate of Leonard Green &AMP; partners, 
L.P., had been terminated. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was actively involved with the proposed Leonard Green  
transaction and I am disappointed with the termination of the 
agreement,'' Fifield said. ``I continue to believe the company 
enjoys an outstanding brand name and products and I look forward to 
remaining a member of the company's board of directors and a major 
shareholder.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leonard Green had agreed to acquire North Face for $17 a share,  
or about $212 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The board of directors appointed William Simon as interim chief  
executive officer to oversee the day-to-day operation of the 
company, effective immediately. Simon had been serving as the 
company's vice chairman and previously served as its CEO. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of North Face, which makes outerwear and sports-related  
equipment, were trading Wednesday down 68 3/4 cents to $8.06 1/4 on the 
Nasdaq Stock Market. 




  	   	
