<HEADLINE> Grizzlies Reunite 2 Old Teammates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- While he'll miss Houston,  
Michael Dickerson is excited about rekindling the magic with his 
college backcourt mate Mike Bibby in Vancouver. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is great. Mike and I have some great chemistry. Mike  
knows what I'm going to do before I even do it. That's what makes 
him such a great point guard,'' Dickerson said Wednesday during his 
first visit to Vancouver, five days after the Grizzlies acquired 
the second-year guard from the Houston Rockets in a blockbuster 
11-player trade that also involved the Orlando Magic. 
</P>
<P>
	Dickerson, at shooting guard, and Bibby, at point, formed the  
Arizona backcourt for two years, including 1997 when the Wildcats 
won the NCAA title. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had something really special. Winning the championship,  
that just united us even more. Mike is a great point guard. I'm 
just excited to be here,'' Dickerson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dickerson, fourth in the NBA in 3-point shooting accuracy last  
year, was acquired to address the Grizzlies' needs at shooting 
guard, and is expected to win the starting job. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year he gained valuable experience starting for the  
Rockets, while also playing alongside all-stars like Hakeem 
Olajuwon, Charles Barkley and Scottie Pippen. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the one thing I'm going to miss, our veteran players.  
That's the only thing I don't like about leaving there. They gave 
me a lot of confidence,'' Dickerson said. 
</P>
<P>
	But he's looking forward to playing in Vancouver, a two-hour  
drive north of his hometown of Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to take this opportunity and run with it,''  
Dickerson said. ``I'm looking on the bright side, this is a great 
team with great players and I think I'm going to compliment them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Along with Dickerson, the Grizzlies acquired Othella Harrington,  
Brent Price, Antoine Carr and a first-round draft pick from the 
Rockets, in exchange for Steve Francis, the second player taken in 
last June's draft, and Tony Massenburg. 
</P>
<P>
	Orlando sent Don MacLean and a future first-round pick to  
Houston in exchange for the Grizzlies' Michael Smith, Lee Mayberry, 
Rodrick Rhodes and Makhtar Ndiaye. The Magic also dealt their 2002 
second-round pick to Vancouver. 
  	   	
</P>
