<HEADLINE> BP Amoco Stockholders OK Arco Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- BP Amoco PLC shareholders voted overwhelmingly  
Wednesday to approve the company's acquisition of Atlantic 
Richfield Co., which will create one of the world's largest energy 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The 99.3 percent vote in favor at a special shareholders'  
meeting in London's Royal Festival Hall followed 99.3 percent 
approval by Atlantic Richfield shareholders that was announced in 
Los Angeles on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	BP Amoco shareholders also approved a split of BP Amoco shares  
which will have the effect of doubling the shares on issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Executives of Arco and BP Amoco agreed last April to the merger,  
which still must be approved by the Federal Trade Commission and 
the European Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger will make BP Amoco ``an even more significant player  
on the international stage,'' said co-chairman Peter Sutherland. 
</P>
<P>
	``We shall become the largest non-state owned oil producer in  
the world, as well as the largest oil and gas producer in both the 
United States and the United Kingdom,'' said Sutherland. 
</P>
<P>
	Ahead of the merger, the company has been shedding jobs as part  
of a cost-cutting plan or because of sales of assets. 
</P>
<P>
	BP Amoco chief executive Sir John Browne said last month that  
12,500 jobs have been shed so far this year, and another 2,000 
layoffs were expected by year's end. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
