<HEADLINE> Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn Moves World HQ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PEAPACK, N.J. (AP) -- Drug maker Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn, best known  
for its Rogaine baldness treatment and Nicorette and Nicotrol 
smoking cessation products, relocated its world headquarters to 
Peapack on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The move comes 15 months after P&AMP;U consolidated the London and  
Kalamazoo, Mich., headquarters of its predecessor companies to a 
temporary base in Bridgewater, several miles south of here in 
central New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	Company spokesman Paul Fitzhenry said the new facility can  
accommodate about 1,000 employees. 
</P>
<P>
	The new campus comprises 550,000 square feet of office space  
spread among 10 buildings on 70 acres. The leafy, college-like 
setting includes aboveground and underground walkways connecting 
the buildings and a clock tower and fountain in the center. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn posted sales of $6.76 billion and  
profits of $691 million, successfully completing a turnaround 
engineered after struggles following its 1995 formation from 
Swedish and Michigan companies. On Tuesday, the company completed 
its acquisition of Sugen Inc., a South San Francisco biotechnology 
company developing several promising cancer treatments. 
</P>
<P>
	Fitzhenry said the company will continue operating the  
Bridgewater facility, with about 360 employees, at least through 
2007. It will house the sales and marketing staffs for U.S. 
consumer health care products, such as Rogaine and Nasalcrom, a 
nonprescription nasal spray for allergies. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
