<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Govt., Tribes Negotiate on Casinos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Tribal leaders want Gov. Gray Davis to  
rewrite his plan for expanded Indian gambling. His initial 
response: no dice. 
</P>
<P>
	Californians had approved a voter initiative to expand Indian  
gambling, but the state Supreme Court last week invalidated the 
measure. 
</P>
<P>
	The tribes have until early October to reach an agreement with  
Davis to avoid having thousands of video slot machines shut down by 
federal authorities. Talks were to resume today. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis offered a plan Tuesday aimed at fulfilling some of the  
initiative's purpose. It would double the number of slot machines, 
but tribes would have to share 25 percent of their gross profits 
with other tribes, as well as allow union activity in the gambling 
halls. 
</P>
<P>
	The tribes sought changes in the plan, but a Davis spokesman  
said the governor's negotiators would not budge. 
</P>
<P>
	``After today, it was such a shock that we feel compelled to  
move forward with our initiative,'' said Richard Milanovich, tribal 
chairman of the Agua Caliente Band of Cahuilla Indians. 
</P>
<P>
	That initiative is another version of Proposition 5, the  
initiative approved by voters last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Tribes have been collecting signatures to qualify the plan that  
essentially duplicates Proposition 5 and amends the state 
constitution to exempt tribes from a ban on Nevada-style gambling. 
</P>
<P>
	The tribes' counterproposal was submitted to Davis' negotiating  
team, led by William Norris, a former federal judge. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the Davis plan, tribes now operating about 15,000 slot  
machines -- and non-gambling tribes that want to jump into the 
lucrative business -- could add as many as 15,000 more. Proposition 
5 had no limit on the number of machines. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan also would allow for Nevada-style games, in addition to  
slots, but with a compact limiting future casino expansion. 
</P>
<P>
	While Milanovich said only part of the Davis plan is acceptable,  
Mark Macarro of the Pechanga Band of Luiseno Indians held out hope 
for an agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're still talking,'' he said. ``There's a sense that all the  
possible ingredients for a deal are near at hand.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
