<HEADLINE> Reform Party Picks Convention Spot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- The Reform Party 2000 national convention  
will be held in Long Beach, Calif., and officials say their 
nomination process is the one to watch. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's pretty much a foregone conclusion who the Republican  
nominee will be and who the Democratic nominee will be. The only 
unknown quantity at this point is our nominee,'' Illinois Reform 
Party Chairman Larry Redmond said. 
</P>
<P>
	The convention will be held Aug. 10-13, said Michael Farris, the  
Pacific regional representative to the party's 11-member national 
executive committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The location decision required a two-thirds vote, passing 8-3 in  
a vote Wednesday night. The three members who didn't vote for 
California voted for Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	Farris said California was chosen mainly because of its detailed  
proposal. California officials had already proposed specific hotels 
and gathering places for the convention. Minnesota officials were 
still deciding among four possible cities for a convention. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was discussion about tabling it, but we sort of needed  
to get on with the process,'' Farris said. 
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota Reform Party Chairman Rick McCluhan said he's looking  
into calling a special convention of the delegates from all states 
to try to overturn the executive committee's decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they made the decision for the wrong reasons,''  
McCluhan said. ``We had the (Reform Party founder Ross) Perot 
faction in control of the committee.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jack Gargan, the chairman-elect of the national party, was  
pushing for the event to be held in Minnesota. But Gargan, who was 
backed by Reform Party member and Gov. Jesse Ventura at the annual 
convention last month in Dearborn, Mich., wasn't one of the voting 
members. 
</P>
<P>
	Russell Verney, an ally of Perot who holds the chairmanship  
until Jan. 1, conceded that one of the reasons some committee 
members decided against Minnesota was that ``they didn't want to 
take a chance that Gov. Ventura would overshadow the candidate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said California also had more specifics on where the  
convention would be held and that some members thought Ventura 
would ``be bigger news if he were in California.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
