<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Homeless Samaritan Gets Donations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) -- As Marian Neal prepared to spend her  
second night in a homeless shelter, she pondered her good fortune: 
People inspired by her decision to donate a kidney to a little boy 
had pledged thousands of dollars to help her find a home. 
</P>
<P>
	Neal said in an interview Tuesday it was difficult to fully  
describe how grateful she was. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just so overwhelmed today,'' Neal said. ``I really  
appreciate it from the bottom of my heart.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She moved into a homeless shelter Monday after someone told  
Alexandria housing officials she was living in a friend's public 
housing unit, which is against the rules. 
</P>
<P>
	The former Federal Express employee says she has been unable to  
afford her own place, because a back injury has kept her out of 
work for four years. She was denied Social Security benefits, and 
currently is number 60 on Alexandria's public housing list. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are long waiting lists in city housing,'' Sandy Murphy,  
an aide to Mayor Kerry Donley, said. ``It's not like there is city 
housing lying empty around the city that we could move people 
into.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Local radio station WRQX-FM discussed Neal's predicament  
Tuesday, and listeners pledged more than $5,000 to help her. 
</P>
<P>
	Neal seemed surprised by all the attention.  
</P>
<P>
	``There are other people in more difficult positions,'' she  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But radio listeners said they felt compelled to help Neal  
because of what she did for 7-year-old Terrance Varner. 
</P>
<P>
	Neal met the boy while living in her friend's public housing  
unit. He lived a few doors away with his grandmother. 
</P>
<P>
	The two became fast friends, and Neal began taking Terrance, who  
suffered from kidney disease, to dialysis three days a week so his 
grandmother would not miss work. 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually, Neal learned she was a compatible donor and gave the  
boy one of her kidneys in December. 
</P>
<P>
	``I couldn't believe it. She hardly knew him,'' said a friend  
and former neighbor of Neal's. She chose not to be identified, 
because she said she also has had run-ins with Alexandria housing 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	But she was glad to talk about Neal. ``She's been a great  
friend,'' this woman said, adding that Neal did a lot for the 
residents at the public housing complex. 
</P>
<P>
	Neal and another friend started a program for children at the  
complex that featured Bible classes, homework help and field trips. 
</P>
<P>
	She misses the children, and plans to visit them soon. She seems  
particularly eager to see Terrance again. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's having a difficult time with this -- with not seeing me as  
often,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The two like to go to the playground, which Terrance couldn't do  
before the kidney transplant. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I never do anything else in my life, there's a little boy  
that I've helped,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	It's likely Neal will help others.  
</P>
<P>
	She is attending Northern Virginia Community College with the  
help of a federal Pell Grant for low-income people, and she says 
she thinks she wants to be a social worker when she graduates. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
