<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Makes Pledge to U.S. Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush,  
accepting the endorsement of more than 100 farm activists, pledged 
Wednesday to open up foreign markets to U.S. agriculture. 
</P>
<P>
	``Agriculture is the cornerstone of international economic  
policy,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Returning to Iowa for the first time since his overwhelming  
victory last month in the Ames straw poll, Bush also picked up the 
endorsement of more than half the Republicans in the state 
legislature. 
</P>
<P>
	Donning a green cap, the GOP presidential front-runner stood  
amid hay bales on a farm just outside Des Moines to spell out his 
trade proposals, an important issue in a state where the farm 
economy is sour. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he would pressure European allies to lift a ban imposed  
on genetically altered commodities, and said it was a mistake to 
block China's entry into the World Trade Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Chinese bargainers made ``drastic concessions'' that could have  
lowered tariffs and opened that giant market to foreign goods, Bush 
said. ``We should have taken them up on their offer,'' he said, 
while still acknowledging that he has concerns about China's record 
as a trading partner. 
</P>
<P>
	He blamed President Clinton for not pressuring Congress to  
extend the ability of presidents to negotiate ``fast track'' trade 
deals and said the next president ``must reclaim the authority.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. farmers are expected to export $49 billion worth of  
commodities this year, down from the peak of $59.8 billion three 
years ago. The Agriculture Department is expecting only slight 
improvement in 2000. Economists blame the decline on the Asian 
economic crisis and a worldwide glut of grain. 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas governor said farmers should be allowed to divert farm  
income into tax-free savings accounts, which could be used to 
provide a cushion for notorious unstable farm income. That would 
allow farmers to build a cushion in good years to last through lean 
times. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush also said he would push for reform of a crop insurance  
system that many farmers can't afford, and touted his backing for 
ethanol, alcohol distilled from corn and mixed with gasoline into 
fuel backers say is environmentally friendly. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not only is it good for the farmer, it is good for the quality  
of air all across America,'' said Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Wednesday, Bush was peppered with questions about  
whether he had used drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	Though there's no evidence he has actually used drugs, he  
refuses to flatly declare that he hasn't. The issue has gained 
momentum because Bush has ruled out drug use for only the past 25 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he was a role model for children who might consider  
drug use, he said, ``I consider myself someone to share the wisdom 
of a mature adult. I'd say to children, 'You should not abuse 
drugs, you should not abuse alcohol.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush attended a fund-raising luncheon, where he raised $75,000  
for Republican legislative candidates, and took questions at a news 
conference, where he announced the endorsement of 31 members of the 
state's House of Representatives and 16 members of the Senate, a 
majority of Republicans in both chambers. 
</P>
<P>
	He then headed to a farm just outside Des Moines to accept the  
backing of farm leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush vowed to break open foreign markets, calling them  
``incredibly important in the long-range of the agricultural 
sector.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Exports are an important issue in Iowa because farmers are  
suffering historic low commodity prices and many are near 
bankruptcy. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush told the farmers he would bolster the farm economy by  
expanding trade but also would move to give immediate aid to those 
in financial trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the short run, the issue is hopefully going to be resolved  
by an administration passing, signing and distributing emergency 
aid,'' Bush said. ``Last year Congress passed an aid package that 
got bottled up in a bureaucracy in Washington, D.C.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Collecting a network of farm and legislative backers gives Bush  
an important organizational tool, bringing large numbers of 
community opinion leaders and organizers into his camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Key lawmakers said they were endorsing not only Bush's message  
but his character. 
</P>
<P>
	``We support the governor's message, we support the governor  
personally,'' said Iowa Senate President Mary Kramer, a West Des 
Moines Republican. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
