<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Millionaire' Helps ABC Top Ratings / TV Ratings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- There are no car chases or laugh tracks. Few  
special effects are ever used. And the host just sits around and 
asks questions. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, a prime-time game show has become the most popular  
television program this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	The final night of ABC's two-week ``Who Wants To Be a  
Millionaire'' series drew 22.4 million viewers on Sunday, the most 
people to watch a show since the ``Home Improvement'' finale in 
May. 
</P>
<P>
	The quiz show also virtually swept the top rated shows,  
capturing five of the top six slots. The only competition was from 
``60 Minutes,'' which finished No. 2. 
</P>
<P>
	``Millionaire'' host Regis Philbin jumped the gun when he  
announced on the air that the show would return for another 
two-week run in November, ABC spokeswoman Pat Preblick said. It's 
not clear whether it will return as a weekly series or an almost 
daily, two-week event, as with its first run. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is definitely coming back in November,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	As is often the case with any success, rival networks who  
noticed the show's excellent ratings for the last two weeks are 
already talking about creating more prime-time game shows in the 
future. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS had ordered six episodes of a ``What's My Line'' remake to  
air this summer. But producers weren't able to complete the shows 
in time to make it on the schedule. Look for it next year, network 
spokesman Chris Ender said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The success of `Millionaire' has opened everyone's eyes about  
what game shows can potentially do in the summer,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	And ABC is developing a game show about current events starring  
comedian Norm McDonald called ``Have I Got News For You.'' That 
project would share something else with ``Millionaire'' -- both 
would be remakes of British shows. 
</P>
<P>
	For the week, ABC had a 7.3 rating and 13 share. CBS came in  
second with a 6.5 rating and 13 share, and NBC had a 6.3 rating and 
11 share. Fox had a 5.6 rating and 10 share, Nielsen Media Research 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	UPN, which sought an advantage against its rivals by premiering  
some fall series early, saw it pay off with its first ratings 
victory against the WB since April 1998. UPN saw strong ratings -- 
by its standards -- with the debut of its wrestling show, ``WWF 
Smackdown!'' 
</P>
<P>
	UPN had a 2.3 rating and 4 share, the WB had a 2.2 rating and 4  
share and Pax TV had a 0.9 rating and 2 share. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``NBC Nightly News'' won the evening news ratings race with  
a 7.4 rating and 16 share. ABC's ``World News Tonight'' had a 7.0 
rating and 16 share and the ``CBS Evening News'' was at 6.0 and 13. 
</P>
<P>
	A rating point represents 994,000 households, or 1 percent of  
the nation's estimated 99.4 million TV homes. The share is the 
percentage of in-use televisions tuned to a given show. 
</P>
<P>
	For the week of Aug. 23-29, the top 10 shows, their networks and  
ratings were: ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire-Sunday,'' ABC, 14.0; 
``60 Minutes,'' CBS, 11.0; ``Who Wants To Be a 
Millionaire-Thursday,'' ABC, 10.9; ``Who Wants To Be a 
Millionaire-Tuesday,'' ABC, 10.6; ``Who Wants To Be a 
Millionaire-Wednesday,'' ABC, 10.4; ``Who Wants To Be a 
Millionaire-Friday,'' ABC, 10.1; ``Dateline NBC-Monday,'' NBC, 9.8; 
``Touched By an Angel,'' CBS, 9.5; ``NFL Preseason Football: Denver 
at Green Bay,'' ABC, 9.1; ``CBS Sunday Movie: Ellen Foster,'' CBS, 
8.5; ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' NBC, 8.5. 






  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
