<DOCNO> APW19990901.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 02:50:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                            *Matt Hartl    	
</P>
<P>
	EVANSTON, Ill. (AP) -- Matt Hartl, a key player on the 1995  
Northwestern football team that competed in the Rose Bowl, died 
Monday of Hodgkin's disease. He was 23. 
</P>
<P>
	Hartl, a fullback who played primarily as a blocking back,  
helped the Wildcats become the first Northwestern squad to play in 
the Rose Bowl since 1949. 
</P>
<P>
	Within a few months of the Rose Bowl, doctors discovered a tumor  
in his chest and diagnosed him with Hodgkin's disease, the same 
cancer his mother had beaten more than 20 years earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	After missing the 1996 season while undergoing treatment, he  
returned for the 1997 season, starting in 11 games for the 
Wildcats. 
</P>
<P>
	He planned to play the next season but could not because the  
disease reoccurred. 
</P>
<P>
	Hartl's death came about two years after his mother died at the  
age of 45, her heart fatally weakened by the radiation treatments 
that helped cure her cancer. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Alex Haynes    	
</P>
<P>
	STUART, Fla. (AP) -- Alex Haynes, a pioneering auto industry  
executive who helped adapt seat belts for use by Ford Motor Co., 
died Monday. He was 89. 
</P>
<P>
	Haynes worked as a member of the automaker's design engineering  
department in the 1950s. He was asked by Henry Ford II to look into 
seat belts after both men had heard of recent studies showing 
better crash survival rates if passengers stay in the car. 
</P>
<P>
	Haynes became known as ``Mr. Safety'' for his emphasis on making  
automobiles and trucks safer. But it was not yet a popular cause. 
</P>
<P>
	Haynes, along with a team of international engineers, later  
helped develop the automotive division Hyundai Motor Co. 

</P>
<P>
                          *George Sugarman    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- George Sugarman, a sculptor whose colorful  
geometric aluminum designs were seen in museums around the world, 
died Aug. 25. He was 87. 
</P>
<P>
	In the early 1960s, Sugarman was among the first to make  
large-scale sculptures that sat directly on the floor, not on a 
pedestal. He enjoyed having his artwork directly in the viewer's 
space. 
</P>
<P>
	His pieces were originally made of painted wood but he later  
switched to aluminum. 
</P>
<P>
	He designed his first polychrome sculpture in 1959 and turned to  
large outdoor sculptures in 1970 beginning with one for the Xerox 
Corporation in El Segundo, Calif. Over the next two decades, he 
designed 30 more sculptures in both the United States and abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	Sugarman's most recent exhibition was in 1998 at Hunter College  
in New York where he taught from 1960 to 1970. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Walter O. Wells    	
</P>
<P>
	ELKHART, Ind. (AP) -- Walter O. Wells, a patriarch of the  
manufactured housing industry who helped found Schult Homes Corp., 
died Monday. He was 87. 
</P>
<P>
	Wells had been chairman emeritus of Schult until 1997, a year  
before the Middlebury-based maker of mobile and modular homes 
merged with Oakwood Homes Corp. of Greensboro, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	He went to work at the Wilbur J. Schult Trailer Market in 1934,  
managing the startup of Schult's manufacturing. 
</P>
<P>
	Wells was president of the Mobile Home Manufacturers Association  
in 1952 and 1953. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 23:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bird Stays With Pacers One More Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Larry Bird never promised he would grow old  
with the Indiana Pacers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hall of Fame player, who this week disclosed he has had  
periodic bouts of irregular heartbeats, will remain with the team 
at least one more season as coach, and he could stay with the team 
beyond that, although it might put Donnie Walsh out of a job. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the end of his contract. He hasn't come in and definitely  
told me that, but I've always known it was a three-year deal, and 
at the end of it he was going to make up his mind whether he wanted 
to coach or not,'' Walsh, the team's president, said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 42-year-old Bird is watching his diet and taking medication  
to treat atrial fibrillation, which is not life threatening. He 
first experienced the irregular heartbeats late in his career with 
the Boston Celtics, and Walsh said he knew about the condition when 
he hired Bird in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``In effect, it was a matter of finding the level of the  
medicine in order to have his heart beat regularly. Once they found 
that, it seemed to me it was OK and he didn't have any more 
problems,'' Walsh said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boston Globe reported Wednesday that Bird indicated to Walsh  
the 1999-00 season would be his last as coach. Walsh told The 
Associated Press he never talked to Bird specifically about that, 
although he has been aware of that possibility all along. 
</P>
<P>
	``In dealing with Larry for the last two years, from the very  
beginning, he only committed to coach for three years,'' Walsh 
said. ``But he's going to coach this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've also spoken to him about continuing on as general  
manager, president, whatever you want to call it. So we'll continue 
to talk about that. But we really haven't sat down and had a 
definite discussion about this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bird was not available for comment Wednesday, and it was not  
clear if the possibility of his leaving coaching was tied to his 
heart condition. 
</P>
<P>
	When he came to the Pacers in 1997, he acquired a minority  
ownership of the team and said he didn't expect to coach for long. 
Walsh said he would step aside if Bird wants his job in the front 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd talk to the owners about that, I'd talk to Larry about  
that. If the best thing would be for me to leave the team, I'd 
leave the team. But we haven't really gotten into that yet,'' Walsh 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bird, who had never coached basketball at any level, was the NBA  
coach of the year in his first season with Indiana in 1998, when 
the Pacers were a franchise-record 58-24 and reached the Eastern 
Conference finals. Last season, shortened to 50 games by the league 
lockout, the Pacers were 33-17, won the Central Division 
championship and again reached the conference finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Bird's heart ailment was disclosed in an excerpt in this week's  
Sports Illustrated from his upcoming book, ``Bird Watching: On 
Playing and Coaching the Game I Love.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I always knew there was something wrong with my heart,'' Bird  
wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he would feel sudden exhaustion and his heart would  
start ``jumping around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bird was put on medication and told to exercise, eat healthy and  
drink alcohol only in moderation. But his condition worsened in the 
spring of 1997, right before he became the Pacers' coach. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got a little scared because it didn't seem like it was going  
away,'' Bird wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Walsh said Wednesday he was aware of Bird's heart ailment.  
</P>
<P>
	``When Larry and I were talking about the job originally, he  
told me he was seeing a doctor and he had an irregular heartbeat or 
something like that and that he had to watch his diet, what he 
drank, what he ate, and that he would have to take medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	The disease is not as serious as ventricular fibrillation, which  
doctors believed caused the death of former Celtics teammate Reggie 
Lewis. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 06:50:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Global Coffee Exports Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Global coffee exports fell 4.3 per cent in July,  
compared with the same period a year earlier, the International 
Coffee Organization reported Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency said that preliminary estimates showed that coffee  
shipments in July totaled 6.891 million bags, compared with 7.197 
million bags in July 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Total exports for the year -- August 1998 to July 1999 -- reached  
83.938 million bags, compared with 75.590 million bags in the same 
period a year earlier. One bag equals 132 pounds. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 15:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Long-Term Treasury Bonds Fall Again / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Long-term Treasury bond prices fell for a fifth  
straight session Wednesday as a declining dollar unsettled bond 
traders. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 7/32  
point, or by $2.19 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves 
in the opposite direction, rose to 6.08 percent from 6.06 percent 
late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	A drop of the dollar further below 110 Japanese yen has raised  
worries in the bond market. 
</P>
<P>
	For one thing, a weaker dollar raises the price of imported  
goods, adding to inflationary pressures. If inflation heats up, the 
Federal Reserve may decide to raise interest rates for a third time 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Rising interest rates lower the value of existing fixed-income  
investments, such as bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, if traders are buying yen and selling dollars, they  
may be selling such dollar-denominated assets as U.S. government 
bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were unchanged, and intermediate maturities were unchanged to down 
1/8 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.93 percent as the  
discount fell 0.03 percentage point from Tuesday to 4.80 percent. 
Six-month yields were 5.19 percent, as the discount fell 0.01 
percentage point to 4.99 percent. One-year yields were 5.27 percent 
as the discount held steady at Tuesday's late rate of 5.00 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, fell to 5.44 percent from 5.63 percent late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 3/16 point to 114 5/32. The average 
yield to maturity rose to 5.79 percent from 5.78 percent late 
Tuesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 17:30:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DNA Test Clears Imprisoned Man </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STORMVILLE, N.Y. (AP) -- A 60-year-old man who spent 17 years in  
prison for rape became a free man Wednesday after a DNA test 
cleared him. 
</P>
<P>
	Vincent H. Jenkins, also known by the Muslim name of Warith  
Habib Abdal, was convicted of robbing and raping a 23-year-old 
woman who was attacked in a Buffalo nature preserve in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
	He was sentenced to 20 years to life in prison.  
</P>
<P>
	His lawyer claimed improper police tactics prompted the victim  
to identify Jenkins months after the rape, even though she wasn't 
initially able to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	DNA evidence testing that was completed in April showed  
virtually beyond any doubt that Jenkins was not the rapist. The 
technology was not available when he was charged. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge John T. Elfvin ruled Tuesday that Jenkins  
was wrongly convicted of the rape, opening the way for him to be 
freed. 
</P>
<P>
	After his release, Jenkins said he had shut his feelings away  
for so long that he couldn't find any emotions to describe. ``It's 
hard to tell what grew around my heart and what I'm feeling,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jenkins is the 61st inmate in the United States to be exonerated  
by DNA testing. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 19:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cargill Cleared of Price-Fixing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A federal appeals court cleared Cargill  
Inc. on Wednesday of taking part in an international conspiracy to 
fix the price of citric acid. 
</P>
<P>
	The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals refused to reinstate a  
damage suit by soft drink companies and other buyers of citric acid 
that was dismissed by a federal judge last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The court said there was no evidence Cargill, a leading  
processor and distributor of agricultural, food and industrial 
products, conspired with four other major firms that admitted 
agreeing to divide markets and set prices. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the four, Archer-Daniels Midland, pleaded guilty in 1997  
to conspiring to fix prices of citric acid and lysine, an animal 
food additive, and was fined $100 million, then the largest 
criminal antitrust penalty on record. 
</P>
<P>
	The other three companies, Haarman &AMP; Reimer, Hoffman LaRoche and  
Jungbunzlauer, also pleaded guilty to criminal charges. A number of 
employees have been prosecuted, including three senior ADM 
executives who were sentenced to prison in July. 
</P>
<P>
	All four companies also settled civil suits by bottlers and  
processors. 
</P>
<P>
	But Cargill, based in Minneapolis, insisted it had no part in  
any conspiracy and simply followed a common practice of basing its 
prices on those of its competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	Citric acid, with worldwide sales of $2 billion to $3 billion a  
year, is used to extend the shelf life of soft drinks, canned 
fruits and vegetables, detergents, drugs and cosmetics. 
</P>
<P>
	The four companies admitted agreeing between 1991 and 1995 to  
divide the market and raise prices by limiting sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Cargill entered the market in the late 1980s and gained a 20  
percent U.S. share by the mid-1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit, a class action by Varni Brothers Corp. and the 7-Up  
Bottling Co. of Philadelphia, accused Cargill of joining the 
conspiracy in 1993 when it joined the European Citric Acid 
Manufacturers Association, a group to which the other four 
companies belonged. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit noted that Cargill had announced in early 1992 that it  
planned to double its citric acid production capacity but announced 
in late 1992 that it would increase capacity only 50 percent. The 
suit also cited an FBI report in one of the criminal cases that 
quoted Barrie Cox, an ADM employee, as saying he had frequent 
discussions with Cargill's national sales director about citric 
acid bidding prices in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	But the appeals court largely discounted Cox's statements,  
saying they showed, at most, ``sporadic price discussions'' two 
years after Cargill was alleged to have joined the conspiracy. 
</P>
<P>
	Cargill's scaling back of its expansion plans, and its posting  
of prices that largely mirrored those of its competitors, were not 
evidence of a conspiracy, said Judge Diarmuid O'Scannlain in the 
3-0 ruling. He said Cargill's expansion of its U.S. market share 
came largely at the expense of ADM and Haarman &AMP; Reimer. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the companies that admitted fixing prices, ``none identified  
Cargill as a co-conspirator,'' O'Scannlain said. 
</P>
<P>
	Therese Stewart, a lawyer for the companies that sued Cargill,  
said the court disregarded an earlier antitrust decision and made 
it extremely difficult to get a price-fixing conspiracy case to 
trial. Even ``evidence of actual agreement between an admitted 
conspirator and the defendant on certain bid prices'' isn't enough, 
she said, referring to the FBI's statement from Cox. 
</P>
<P>
	But Richard Favretto, a lawyer for Cargill, said Cox's  
statements were never corroborated and were considered by the 
federal government in a four-year investigation that cleared the 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling is ``a further vindication of our position,'' he  
said. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
