<DOCNO> APW19990901.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 13:20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fla. Gator QB Gets One More Chance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- The injuries, suspensions, demotions  
and dilemmas are behind him. This year, Doug Johnson hopes to tap 
into the awkward lessons of his past to prove himself a worthy 
Florida quarterback. 
</P>
<P>
	He put his pro baseball career on hold, recovered nicely from  
the injuries that hampered him last year and stayed in Gainesville 
all summer to polish up on the offense he'll direct. 
</P>
<P>
	He also got coach Steve Spurrier's vote of confidence, something  
that had been inherently missing during his tumultuous sophomore 
and junior seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	When Johnson takes the field Saturday in No. 4 Florida's opener  
against Western Michigan, he'll take the first step in trying to 
win a title, the way Danny Wuerffel and Shane Matthews did earlier 
in the decade. 
</P>
<P>
	The downside is too painful to imagine. If Johnson fails, he'll  
be the first Florida quarterback not to lead the Gators to at least 
the Southeastern Conference championship since Spurrier arrived as 
coach in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	``That would probably be the worst thing, leaving here without a  
championship,'' Johnson said. ``I don't think anything else could 
happen here that I haven't already gone through.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The tumult started in the summer of 1996, when the Tampa Bay  
Devil Rays drafted Johnson to play third base in their minor league 
system. Thus began a two-year struggle between Johnson, who claimed 
he couldn't be happy without testing his potential in baseball, and 
Spurrier, who appreciated Johnson's talent but questioned his 
commitment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't be happy if I don't play both,'' Johnson said at one  
point, intensifying the disagreement between quarterback and coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the differences, Johnson started on opening day in 1997.  
The early results were scintillating. He threw seven touchdown 
passes in a half against Central Michigan. He threw three more in a 
victory over Tennessee and five against Kentucky, more or less 
outplaying both Peyton Manning and Tim Couch. 
</P>
<P>
	By October, things had changed. A four-interception performance  
against LSU was followed by news that he had missed curfew before 
the game. He was suspended for the next game. His return was 
troubled. 
</P>
<P>
	At season's end, he injured his shoulder in the Citrus Bowl, a  
result of nearly two nonstop years of throwing both baseballs and 
footballs. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet he would not back down from his desire to play baseball.  
That desire, plus the injury, put him behind Jesse Palmer heading 
into last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson eventually worked his way into a rotation system with  
Palmer, then got the job when Palmer broke his collarbone in 
midseason. Johnson threw for 2,346 yards and 19 touchdowns, but 
couldn't engineer a victory over Florida State. Once again, Florida 
settled playing for leftovers instead of titles. 
</P>
<P>
	That brought about a shift in Johnson's outlook.  
</P>
<P>
	He committed to put baseball on hold in 1999. And even though  
Johnson suffered a broken fibula in the Orange Bowl, Spurrier stood 
behind him, taking the rare step of naming him the starter some 
eight months before the next season would begin. 
</P>
<P>
	Healthy again, Johnson kept his promise, stuck around over the  
offseason and proved one of the team's hardest workers. It made an 
impression. 
</P>
<P>
	``You could tell this summer that he was putting a lot of focus  
into it,'' said receiver Darrell Jackson. ``Every day he was in the 
weight room. He was out here throwing every day, even when his leg 
was bothering him. He was hanging out more, laughing with the 
fellas and stuff, growing on them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also became more of a master at the complex Florida offense,  
which is what Spurrier wanted all along. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's a better player,'' Spurrier said. ``He  
understands the game now. He understands how important it is to 
know everything about the offense. He's matured quite a bit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also has a better understanding of his coach, what makes him  
tick and how to handle the sometimes frustrating relationship. 
Spurrier himself used to be the quarterback at Florida. He won a 
Heisman Trophy, but expressed to Johnson that his career didn't 
feel complete. 
</P>
<P>
	``He thinks he could've played even better, but he didn't have  
anyone pushing him like he needed to be pushed,'' Johnson said. 
``He's going to push me as hard as he can push me. He's going to 
get on me because he wants me to play the best I can play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That, he says, is all part of growing up.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a firm believer that people have to fail before they  
succeed,'' Johnson said. ``Things happen for a reason. I can't 
control if I get injured. But I want this year to play out so that 
you can take everything that has happened to me, say I learned from 
it, and here's the final product.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
