<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gas Prices May Drop After Holiday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- As the Labor Day weekend approaches, a series  
of sharp gasoline price spikes that have pinched motorists' 
pocketbooks since March appear to be nearing an end. 
</P>
<P>
	That's because crude oil prices appear to be stable and other  
pressures that helped push gas prices upward, such as refinery 
breakdowns and higher summertime demand, are waning. 
</P>
<P>
	After the holiday weekend, prices will begin to drop, said Bill  
Berman, a petroleum industry analyst and publisher of the Price 
Pump Report. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will drop more quickly on the East Coast because there's  
more price competition. It will drop more slowly as you go west of 
the Mississippi because there are fewer refiners and fewer gasoline 
stations,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Since late June, the average price of gasoline nationwide  
climbed 11.5 cents per gallon to $1.31, according to an Aug. 20 
Lundberg Survey. The increase followed an 8.5-cent jump in March 
and a 14-cent spike in early April. 
</P>
<P>
	California motorists, who use more costly blends reformulated  
fuel to reduce air pollution, were hit even harder. The average 
price rose 14 cents per gallon during the period, according to the 
Lundberg Survey. 
</P>
<P>
	The situation may already be changing. There are signs that  
wholesale prices in some markets have begun to fall in anticipation 
of weaker demand, said analyst Trilby Lundberg. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a substantial downward move,'' she said. ``There's  
more likelihood for weakening pump prices than there is for rises, 
assuming crude oil prices do not rise further.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The earlier increases in the retail market prompted the Federal  
Trade Commission to launch a formal investigation of West Coast 
prices. Attorneys general in California and Nevada are cooperating 
in a separate probe of gas prices in their states. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil companies have blamed the increases on market forces,  
including refinery problems and cuts in world production. 
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest driving force of gas prices increases have been  
crude oil price increases, which have doubled since the first of 
the year,'' said Paul Oves, a spokesman for Tosco Marketing Co., a 
subsidiary of oil refiner Tosco Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	``Outside the West Coast, demand patterns have been pretty  
typical of the driving season,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The explanations haven't placated motorists who are paying  
higher prices. 
</P>
<P>
	At Castaic in north Los Angeles County, Jesus Benavidez of  
Norwalk, Calif., filled two personal watercraft at a Shell station 
where prices for self-serve gas ranged from $1.599 to $1.779. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just going higher and higher, you just can seem to get a  
break,'' Benavidez said. 
</P>
<P>
	But like other holiday travelers, Benavidez was prepared to  
spend more to enjoy his trip. Twenty dollars worth of gas for the 
watercraft would give him four hours of riding time on Lake 
Castaic. 
</P>
<P>
	``The more fun you want to have, the more gas you've got to  
get,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices began to climb after the Organization of Petroleum  
Exporting Countries announced in February that they would reduce 
production by 2.7 percent, or 2.1 million barrels a day. Greater 
demand in Asia, where South Korea, Thailand and other countries are 
emerging from recessions, also has boosted pressure on crude 
prices. 
</P>
<P>
	In California, the problem was made worse by a series of  
accidents that forced four refineries to halt or reduce production, 
cutting supplies by about 15 percent. At the peak of the shortfall 
in April, prices reached $1.99 in parts of San Francisco and Los 
Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	``The California market is just historically, chronically,  
always tighter than the rest of the country,'' said John Cook, an 
oil industry analyst with the Department of Energy. ``Refining 
capacity is just adequate to meet seasonal demand requirements in 
California under normal circumstances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prices fell during May, but began to climb again in late June as  
the July Fourth holiday approached. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices should begin to decline again after Labor Day, analysts  
said. But that depends on crude oil prices remaining stable. OPEC, 
so far, appears unwilling to rock the boat. Following a meeting 
last weekend in Venezuela, oil ministers from that country, Saudi 
Arabia and Mexico reaffirmed pledges to continue with current 
production levels until next March. 
</P>
<P>
	``If driving is declining -- and driving is most likely to  
decline -- then the price of gasoline is going to decline with it,'' 
said Berman. ``Barring unforeseen events, gasoline prices will peak 
Labor Day weekend and probably will drop off after that.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
