<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Williamsburg Program Draws Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILLIAMSBURG, Va. (AP) -- A Colonial Williamsburg program that  
re-creates the harsh treatment of slaves is drawing fire from black 
re-enactors who say they deserve better treatment on the job. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, a group of black employees wrote a letter to the  
Colonial Williamsburg Foundation's education division saying they 
feel typecast as slaves and deprived of the opportunity to advance. 
The employees also said they are underpaid and treated 
insensitively. 
</P>
<P>
	A recent staff shuffling only heightened their unhappiness, they  
told the Daily Press of Newport News in a story published 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems as though with each restructuring, only one black at  
a time is promoted,'' the letter read. ``This leads us to believe 
that those in charge of programming are afraid if they promote too 
many of us, they won't have any 'slaves' to make their programs 
successful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Elliott, Colonial Williamsburg's vice president of  
education, said the foundation is aware of the employees' concerns 
and has been meeting with staff since May to work things out. 
</P>
<P>
	The foundation this year added depictions of the treatment  
blacks received to its re-enactments as part of a program called 
``Enslaving Virginia.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The program placed costumed re-enactors in the role of slaves.  
Black employees portrayed runaways, preachers and slaves, and white 
employees sometimes portrayed slave masters, their treatment of 
blacks often leaving visitors shocked. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
