<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Close Higher / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's benchmark stock average closed 2.1 percent  
higher Wednesday on increasing talk about government intervention 
to stop the dollar's decline. The U.S. dollar continued to fall 
against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed up 365.92  
points, at 17,802.48. On Tuesday, the average closed down 482.41 
points, or 2.69 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 109.22 yen in the late afternoon, down 0.96  
yen from its level of 110.18 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo and also 
below its late New York level of 109.59 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, talk of intervention in the currency market  
helped export issues gain. Bank stocks, hard hit Tuesday, also rose 
sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	A weaker yen would help exporters by making their products less  
expensive abroad, and thus more competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	The higher the yen goes, the stronger the collective market fear  
of intervention becomes, dealers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Concern is mounting in other quarters, too. On Wednesday  
afternoon, Hubert Neiss, director of the International Monetary 
Fund's Asia and Pacific department, said in a speech in Tokyo that 
``a further rapid appreciation of the yen could well put an end to 
the recovery, as has happened before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neiss called this ``an important risk,'' the clearest signal yet  
of growing concern about the surging yen in the international 
community. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 84.85  
points, or 0.8 percent, to close Tuesday at 10,829.28. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section closed up 39.22 points, or 2.69 percent, to 1,496.24. 
The TOPIX closed down 40.92 points, or 2.73 percent, the day 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar edged up in Tokyo from its New  
York level early in the session after some players bought back the 
greenback. 
</P>
<P>
	But currency traders were less optimistic about Bank of Japan  
intervention, and drove the dollar lower after seeing no signs of 
buying by the central bank to support the U.S. currency. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar last traded below 110 yen in Tokyo on Jan. 12.  
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 116.08 yen, up from  
116.06 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 214 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.8650 percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.9150 
percent, driving its price up to 100.29 yen from 99.87 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
