<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge OKs Million Youth March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Million Youth March can return to Harlem  
once again, despite the hate-filled speeches and violence that 
marked the event in its first year, a federal judge has ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Denny Chin overruled city officials who had  
denied organizers of the march a permit. Officials cited the 
anti-white and anti-Semitic slurs of the march's main backer, 
Khallid Abdul Muhammad, and the violence that broke out last year 
as their reasons for blocking the march. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Chin said the city was at least partly to blame for the  
chaos that erupted at the close of the initial rally. Twenty-eight 
people were injured, including 16 police officers, when officers 
moved in to shut down the event moments after the court-ordered 
ending time had passed. 
</P>
<P>
	``The scenes of demonstrators throwing barricades and other  
objects are disturbing, but also disturbing is the spectacle of 
dozens of police officers in riot gear moving in on the stage, with 
a helicopter swooping overhead ... when the rally was indeed about 
to conclude,'' he wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	In his ruling Tuesday, the judge suggested the city show more  
restraint on Saturday. He said the message of hate some rally 
speakers champion was not enough to overcome constitutional 
protections. 
</P>
<P>
	``The right to free speech ... applies not only to politically  
correct statements but also to statements with which we may 
disagree and, indeed, abhor,'' the judge said. 
</P>
<P>
	The city's attorney, Michael Hess, immediately appealed, and a  
hearing was scheduled for this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	If the city loses its fight, it will be the second time  
organizers have won a court battle to hold the event in Harlem. 
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani called Chin's ruling unreasonable and 
unwarranted. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an example of a judge putting his head in the sand,''  
he said, ``and somehow being so overwhelmed with the inability to 
make a distinction between a proper First Amendment demonstration 
and an excuse for violence that he really just can't see the 
difference.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Police estimated last year's crowd at 6,000, while organizers  
claimed a turnout of 300,000. Organizers say they are expecting up 
to 20,000 people this year, although a number of black elected 
officials in Harlem are urging people to stay away from the rally, 
centered at 118th Street and Malcolm X Boulevard. 
</P>
<P>
	``The turnout last year was pathetic,'' said Hess, the city's  
attorney. ``This year's turnout will be even more pathetic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the city was pleased it was not ordered to grant a  
parade permit sought by demonstrators. 
</P>
<P>
	``Victory. Victory. Victory,'' said Malik Z. Shabazz, a lawyer  
and organizer of the rally, who stood outside the federal 
courthouse in Manhattan after the ruling. ``We are coming in peace 
and safety and security.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
