<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 10:40:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kevin Bacon Ready To Be Cut Loose </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Kevin Bacon is an accomplished actor who has  
worked with Oscar winners and top directors. He is also a dedicated 
family man with two children, and sings and writes songs with his 
brother. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet, when you hear his name, does the 1984 film ``Footloose''  
still come to mind? 
</P>
<P>
	That's a typical reaction, said Bacon, who has mixed feelings  
about his breakthrough role as Ren McCormack, a city kid who moves 
to a small town where dancing has been outlawed. (One reviewer 
wrote: ``Bacon's charisma sparks innocuous film.'') 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to be better known for something that I've done in  
the last 15 years. It would have been nice if something had taken 
its place,'' he said during an interview at a Manhattan hotel. 
``But by the same token, I don't want to look a gift horse in the 
mouth. It was an important movie for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since ``Footloose,'' Bacon's two dozen film credits include  
``JFK,'' ``A Few Good Men,'' ``The River Wild'' and ``Apollo 13.'' 
He is most proud of ``Murder in the First,'' a 1995 film that also 
starred Christian Slater, Gary Oldman and William H. Macy. 
</P>
<P>
	His new film is ``Stir of Echoes,'' a psychological thriller  
that follows Bacon on a supernatural journey after he is hypnotized 
at a neighborhood party. 
</P>
<P>
	One thing that attracted Bacon to the role was director David  
Koepp's advice to view the part as a great character instead of a 
classic leading man. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think part of the reason I have not always been as  
successful as a leading man is that the characters just haven't 
been that well written,'' Bacon said. ``A lot of times, people will 
focus more of their energy on bad guys or funny best friends, and 
the hero gets the short end of the stick in character 
development.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unfortunately, Bacon said, he can't always see the flaws of a  
character or a story until it's too late. 
</P>
<P>
	``Seeing a picture for the first time is always a real shock. I  
try to, if I can, get in and see some dailies and cut footage just 
to see bits and pieces.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It is the period leading up to the release of a new film that is  
the most stressful, he said. There are the interviews, the buzz and 
opening weekend box-office numbers to worry about. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Bacon won't read the reviews -- at least not of his own  
work. He stopped about 10 years ago, saying he wasn't getting any 
constructive suggestions. 
</P>
<P>
	Several years ago, Bacon and his brother Michael formed the  
Bacon Brothers. The inspiration for the band's songs are often 
real-life events, explained Bacon, dressed in a black button-down 
shirt with jeans and looking younger than his 41 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since I've been an actor, I have done a million interviews and  
profiles for magazines, and while I try to be honest about my 
feelings about things, I think the most revealing thing I've ever 
done is the lyrics of a song.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Getting There'' is the Bacon Brothers' new CD.  
</P>
<P>
	Bacon said he can't decide whether he prefers acting or music.  
But he likes the team attitude that comes with being in a band. 
Acting in films can be ``oddly isolating,'' he said, while in the 
band, everyone has a necessary and complementary role. 
</P>
<P>
	He particularly likes working with his brother because there is  
a high degree of trust and support. They share lead vocals, and 
sibling rivalry only surfaces when it comes to how many songs each 
has written. Right now, Bacon is ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel blessed that I've been able to bring music into my  
life, even if no one ever heard of the band, it's such a blessing 
to be able to play -- to get together with the guys and play. It's 
kind of a magical experience when it's working right and it's 
grooving.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 16:10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coach Robinson Ready at UNLV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENTON, Texas (AP) -- When John Robinson coached at Southern Cal,  
the annual goal was to win the Rose Bowl. As he prepares for his 
first game with UNLV, school supporters will settle for a victory 
of any kind. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson, out of a job last season after being fired by USC,  
returns to the college sidelines Thursday night when the Rebels 
play North Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	UNLV carries a 16-game losing streak into its opener. It's the  
second-longest skid in Division I-A, two behind Hawaii. 
</P>
<P>
	``The most important thing is that we expect to win,'' Robinson  
said. ``That's necessary to compete. Losing wounds you. If you 
don't shrug it off, you'll always be defeated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Senior receiver Len Ware has felt the sting and heard Robinson's  
soothing words. Now he's curious to see which will be stronger. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just because we have John Robinson, the program isn't going to  
turn around by itself,'' Ware said. ``He's not going to be in the 
uniform out there, but he will put us in a position to win games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 64-year-old coach won four Rose Bowls with the Trojans and  
has a career record of 104-35-4 over 12 seasons. He also coached 
the Los Angeles Rams. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson was lured to the desert by a program long overshadowed  
by the school's basketball team and desperate for an identity. So 
far, it's worked. 
</P>
<P>
	``You hear a lot of football hype around here. `What a great  
team we'll be!' `Coach Robinson's here now!' `You're going to win 
it all!''' Ware said. 
</P>
<P>
	It's all a bit much, Robinson said.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm tired of getting my picture in the paper every day, but we  
need all the help we can get,'' he said. ``We have to sell this 
program to the community over the next five years to get where we 
want to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	North Texas is going through a similar growth process in its  
second year under Darrell Dickey. 
</P>
<P>
	The Eagles won just three games last year after winning four in  
1997 and five in '96. Beating the Rebels would be a good start 
toward reversing the trend. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know each other a lot better than a year ago,'' Dickey  
said. ``As far as the ability to get things done, we'll find out 
Thursday night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	North Texas officials hope for a crowd of at least 17,000 at  
Fouts Field, even though the Dallas Cowboys are playing an 
exhibition game in nearby Irving. 
</P>
<P>
	Dickey understands that much of the interest in this game is  
because of the visiting team and its coach. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it will be much of a factor, but I know there  
has been a lot of hype,'' he said. ``This is a team that has a new 
coach with a great reputation who we know will bring in a football 
team that will play hard and be well prepared.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
