<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hilton Hotels May Buy Promus Corp. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Hilton Hotels Corp. and Promus Hotel Corp.  
said Wednesday they are in discussions about a possible merger. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies said in a brief statement that Hilton had begun  
talks with Promus about ``a possible business combination,'' but 
said there was no assurance a deal would be reached. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past Hilton has expressed interest in buying Promus, but  
executives have said that the company was too pricey. Promus had 
$1.1 billion in revenues in 1998, while Hilton showed $1.8 billion 
for the same period. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wall Street Journal, which first reported the talks  
Wednesday, said a deal could be worth more than $2.4 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	A merger would expand Hilton's stake in the lodging industry.  
Promus' interests include Embassy Suites, Doubletree, Homewood 
Suites and Hampton Inn. If Hilton acquired Promus, it would open 
the limited-service and all-suites segments of the travel market to 
Hilton. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Hilton stockholders would likely have to deal with  
reduced earnings of their shares if a deal were to go through. 
</P>
<P>
	Promus suffered a management shakeup after the company merged  
with Doubletree Corp. in December 1997. The top executives from 
both companies quit in August 1998 because of management strife. 
</P>
<P>
	Norman Blake, the former chief executive officer of insurance  
company USF&AMP;G Corp., said Promus wasn't for sale shortly after 
being named chairman, president and CEO. He said Promus would 
instead be seeking acquisitions. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, Promus reduced its earnings estimates for 1999, citing  
weak market conditions and poor performance at its Red Lion hotels. 
Two brokerages lowered their ratings on Promus and its stock 
dropped by 18 percent in one day. 
</P>
<P>
	The news of talks with Hilton sent Promus stock soaring 10.1  
percent, or by $2.93 3/4, to close at $32 a share on the New York 
Stock Exchange, where Hilton slid 4.1 percent, or by 50 cents, to 
close at $11.68 3/4. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
