<HEADLINE> Disney Set To Sell Angels, Ducks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Walt Disney Co. has reportedly outlined a  
deal to sell the Anaheim Angels and Mighty Ducks to billionaire 
Henry T. Nicholas III for $650 million, a sum millions of dollars 
above industry estimates of the teams' value. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney has ``completed the parameters of a deal'' to sell the  
baseball and hockey club to Nicholas, columnist Peter Gammons wrote 
for ESPN.com on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry analysts have valued the Angels-Ducks package at $375  
million to $425 million, but Nicholas ``stepped up and closed the 
deal,'' the columnist wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	ESPN.com is the online information unit of cable broadcaster  
ESPN, which is owned by Disney. 
</P>
<P>
	Other reports have said Disney and Nicholas were in talks but  
that a deal had yet to be reached. Disney has refused comment on 
reports of talks with Nicholas. 
</P>
<P>
	Any deal would need the approval of Major League Baseball, and  
the Los Angeles Times, quoting an unidentified high-ranking 
baseball source, reported today that Disney has not yet sought 
permission from the commissioner's office to share financial 
information with Nicholas. 
</P>
<P>
	It is possible that Disney and Nicholas could agree on the broad  
outline of a purchase first and adjust the price later, the Times 
said, citing unidentified sources. Disney could raise more than 
$300 million with the sale of the two teams, the Times said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholas is president and chief executive officer of Irvine,  
Calif.-based semiconductor group Broadcom Corp. A message 
requesting comment was left at his office today but there was no 
immediate response. 
</P>
<P>
	Daily Variety, citing unidentified sources, reported that no  
agreement was likely to be announced until later this fall. The 
entertainment industry paper said that securing the deal could take 
much longer. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney signed an agreement three years ago to pay $140 million  
for the Angels. The company also paid a $50 million franchise fee 
for the hockey team. However, both teams have not been money 
makers. 
</P>
<P>
	Just last week, Disney sold Fairchild Publications for a  
reported $650 million. Analysts have said Disney's recent selloff 
efforts have been an attempt to cut costs and boost dropping 
stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Angels entered the season with payroll of $60 million, a  
franchise record. But they have fallen out of contention in the AL 
West in the last month. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mighty Ducks have never made it beyond the second round of  
the playoffs, and were swept by Detroit in the opening series this 
year. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
