<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jim Brown's Wife Denies Threats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Jim Brown's wife took the witness stand  
Wednesday, blaming herself for her stormy marriage and denying the 
football Hall of Famer threatened to break her neck or ever hurt 
her. 
</P>
<P>
	Monique Brown said she lied to a 911 operator and police when  
she claimed the couple had a history of domestic violence and that 
he had threatened to kill her. 
</P>
<P>
	``My husband has never laid a hand on me, and I had no reason to  
believe he ever would,'' she said under cross-examination by 
defense attorney William Graysen. 
</P>
<P>
	``So all this information you gave to the 911 officer was  
false?,'' he asked. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's correct,'' she replied.  
</P>
<P>
	Monique Brown later acknowledged telling a television  
interviewer that premenstrual syndrome led her to call 911. 
</P>
<P>
	When she is premenstrual, ``I become more sensitive, more  
emotional, more irritable,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	She sought treatment and was advised to take vitamins, exercise  
and stay away from salty foods, but was not following the doctor's 
orders at the time, Monique Brown said. 
</P>
<P>
	Toward the end of her daylong account, Monique Brown became  
tearful as she insisted the only people she feared after making the 
emergency call from a neighbor's home the night of June 15 were the 
estimated 18 officers who arrived at her Hollywood Hills home. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt so bad about what I'd done,'' she said. ``It was way,  
way too much. The mistake I'd made was using the 911 operator and 
allowing myself to be led and manipulating to get what I wanted ... 
I didn't realize what I had created and it was way out of 
control.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the end, ``I was just relieved that my husband was alive,''  
she said, explaining she thought they were going to kill him. 
</P>
<P>
	``Did you think they might harm you?'' Graysen asked.  
</P>
<P>
	``Yes,'' she said in a choking voice.  
</P>
<P>
	Brown, 63, is on trial in Hollywood Municipal Court on one count  
of making terrorist threats and one count of vandalism, both 
misdemeanors. He could face 18 months in jail if convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	The city attorney's office is pursuing the case without Monique  
Brown's cooperation. She has urged that charges be dropped. 
</P>
<P>
	At the end of the day Graysen, outside the jury's presence,  
asked Judge Dale S. Fischer to exclude planned prosecution 
testimony from an expert on domestic violence, arguing that Monique 
Brown had recanted her allegations. However, the judge rejected the 
motion and said jurors must decide whether Monique Brown lied to 
police or in court. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, who appeared pained during much of the testimony, emerged  
from court at the lunch hour holding his wife's hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``I sit there and I agonize with her,'' he said. ``She is the  
victim in many, many ways. I'm so happy she's able to stand up and 
present herself and represent us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Monique Brown, 25, portrayed the couple's two-year marriage as  
marred by shouting matches but never violence, although she 
acknowledged that she once had to leave home and stay with friends 
after arguing with Brown. 
</P>
<P>
	She blamed herself for the problems.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was so frustrated,'' she said. ``I had complaints about his  
playing so much golf, giving me so much responsibility. I felt he 
wasn't making the right business decisions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Monique Brown said things came to a head when they argued about  
a trip he was taking to Miami, where she suspected he was having an 
affair. 
</P>
<P>
	``It had been building up over six months,'' she testified.  
</P>
<P>
	``I told him I wasn't going to take this anymore, and I was  
going to leave,'' she testified. ``I knew he was having an 
affair.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I was afraid my marriage was ending,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Brown told her the marriage was over and attacked her car with a  
shovel, smashing the windows and denting the doors. 
</P>
<P>
	She tacitly gave him permission, she added.  
</P>
<P>
	``I said, `Go ahead. ... It's your car, anyway. You're going to  
have to fix it.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Monique Brown said the car was registered to her but it was used  
for Brown's company business. 
</P>
<P>
	She Brown said she was not afraid at any point, even when she  
heard Brown smashing the car windows. 
</P>
<P>
	She acknowledged telling police that Brown once stood over her  
with a metal spear and asked her if she wanted to live. 
</P>
<P>
	``Did you tell the detectives that if you took him to court, he  
said he would kill you?'' Deputy City Attorney Grace Kim Lee asked 
at one point, as Brown sat across the room watching. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes,'' Monique Brown said. ``But it was not true.''  
</P>
<P>
	``Is that why you are changing your story?''  
</P>
<P>
	``Absolutely not,'' Monique Brown said.  
</P>
<P>
	Later in the day, Lee asked her if she thought Brown should  
learn to control her anger. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd have to learn to control my anger before I can speak for  
my husband,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	She also testified about a June 13 argument in which she grabbed  
the TV remote control away from Brown as he lay on their bed. She 
felt he was paying more attention to the TV than to her, she 
testified. 
</P>
<P>
	``Is that when he threatened to kill you by snapping your  
neck?'' Lee asked. 
</P>
<P>
	``He never threatened to kill me by snapping my neck,'' Monique  
Brown replied. 
</P>
<P>
	Police Officer Fernie Montesdeoca testified Tuesday that Monique  
Brown told officers responding to her 911 call that ``the defendant 
had threatened to kill her by snapping her neck.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
