<HEADLINE> Parents Charged in Python Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARLYLE, Ill. (AP) -- The parents of a 3-year-old boy squeezed to  
death by a pet python were charged Wednesday with endangering the 
life of a child and possession of a dangerous animal. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Altom, 26, said Wednesday he didn't know the snake was  
vicious enough to kill his son, Jesse, who was asleep on the living 
room floor of the family's mobile home. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't blame the snake. ... I don't really believe he tried  
to stalk my son down. He might have got out of the cage and he 
cuddled up by him,'' Altom said after his son's funeral Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't have had a snake in my house if I'd thought it was  
going to kill my son. That boy was everything in my world,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The endangerment charge carries a maximum penalty of 10 years in  
prison. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
