<DOCNO> APW19990901.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 23:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Warm Socks As Sleeping Aid? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Instead of counting sheep, the next time you have trouble  
sleeping, try putting socks on your feet. 
</P>
<P>
	A researcher says people with chronically cold feet might drift  
off faster if they warm their feet with socks or a hot water 
bottle. 
</P>
<P>
	That's because the body appears to prepare for sleep by widening  
the blood vessels in the hands and feet to help radiate body heat 
away, according to a study. 
</P>
<P>
	Warming the feet and then removing the socks or water bottle  
would promote this dilation, said the researcher, Anna Wirz-Justice 
of the Psychiatric University Clinic in Basel, Switzerland. Most 
people go through the process naturally and wouldn't need socks or 
a water bottle to help them sleep, she said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	She and colleagues didn't directly test whether socks or water  
bottles promote sleep. But they did analyze data from 18 healthy 
young men who participated in sleep studies. The results suggest 
that blood vessel dilation in the hands and feet in late evening, 
and resulting heat loss, are key to falling asleep. 
</P>
<P>
	The analysis appears in Thursday's issue of the journal Nature.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 10:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Eastwind Airlines Grounding Itself </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) -- As many as 20,000 ticketholders could be  
affected when Eastwind Airlines suspends flights next week, company 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The troubled discount carrier will suspend operations  
indefinitely as it tries to close a deal for its sale. It will 
suspend flights to and from Greensboro, Orlando, Fla. and Trenton, 
N.J., beginning at 12:01 a.m. EDT Sept. 8. 
</P>
<P>
	The company will lay off about 50 of its 145 employees,  
including pilots, flight attendants and some ground personnel. 
</P>
<P>
	Passengers departing before noon Tuesday but not scheduled to  
return until after Sept. 7 will get a return ticket on another 
airline. Anyone else who has paid for a flight on Eastwind 
scheduled after Sept. 7 will get a refund for the unused portion of 
the ticket. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this point, we really don't see ourselves continuing  
Eastwind service, based on the financial performance we have had 
over the last 12 months,'' said Chris Dimitriyadi, the airline's 
executive vice president. 
</P>
<P>
	Dimitriyadi had said just last week that the airline would  
continue operating despite heavy losses. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed purchase agreement involves a European carrier  
looking to establish a U.S. presence and an investment company that 
owns a regional Southeastern carrier. Dimitriyadi declined to name 
the companies but said both are made up of airline veterans. He 
said the deal may be closed by the end of the week. 
</P>
<P>
	Eastwind's owner, New Jersey-based UM Holdings Ltd., is  
continuing talks with about 10 other potential buyers. UM is asking 
at least $10 million for the airline and its leases on two year-old 
Boeing 737-700s. 
</P>
<P>
	If Eastwind is able to find a buyer, the flight suspensions will  
be lifted, Dimitriyadi said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Greensboro-based airline has lost $29 million in the past  
four years and still owes money to airports, passengers and travel 
agencies. It has been the target of scores of customer complaints 
about canceled and delayed flights, double billing and poor 
customer service. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
