</P>
<P>
	Mixed Signals in Economic Reports  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The U.S. economy is continuing the longest  
peacetime expansion in history, although rising interest rates are 
beginning to slow some sectors, including home building. The Index 
of Leading Economic Indicators rose 0.3 percent to 108.0 in July, 
the Conference Board reported today. But construction spending 
unexpectedly fell 0.5 percent in the same month, according to a 
separate government report. The mixed signals may take pressure off 
the Federal Reserve, which already has raised interest rates twice 
this summer in an attempt to slow the economy's growth to a 
noninflationary pace. 

</P>
<P>
	GM, DaimlerChrysler Sales Strong  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- August was a hot month for automakers, as General  
Motors Corp. and DaimlerChrysler AG reported strong U.S. sales 
thanks in part to better rebates and incentives. ``The industry 
continues to run at a spectacular rate, and manufacturers are 
competing fiercely for every sale,'' said John G. Middlebrook, GM 
vice president and general manager of vehicle brand marketing. GM 
said today its sales were up 64 percent over last year -- a 
comparison skewed by United Auto Workers strikes that all but 
halted GM's North American production last year. Truck sales helped 
GM and also pulled sales in DaimlerChrysler's Chrysler unit up 9 
percent over last year. 

</P>
<P>
	Oil Stocks Help European Markets Up  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European stocks closed higher today, as healthy  
crude prices put oil stocks up among the day's best performers. BP 
Amoco, the biggest stock in the Dow Jones Stoxx index, rose 20 
pence, or 1.7 percent, while France's Elf-Aquitaine rose 6.70 euros 
to 172.70 euros, and TotalFina rose 2.80 euros to 124.80 euros. The 
Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 592 European companies rose 1.58 points, 
or 0.5 percent, to close at 310.27. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, 
which tracks 297 companies in countries that joined the single 
currency, closed up 1.89 points at 325.33. 

</P>
<P>
	World Bank Plans Less Asia Lending  
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- The World Bank expects loan disbursements to  
Asian countries to fall dramatically in the fiscal year ending in 
June 2000 because the region is moving toward economic recovery, a 
bank official said today. Jean-Michel Severino, the bank's vice 
president for East Asia and the Pacific region, said the bank lent 
$6.2 billion to Asian governments in fiscal 1999 and expects that 
amount to drop by as much as a third this year. 

</P>
<P>
	Lemieux Takeover of Penguins OK'd  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Mario Lemieux's takeover of the bankrupt  
Pittsburgh Penguins was approved today by the NHL's board of 
governors. Only court approval remains to complete the deal, which 
is expected Friday in Pittsburgh by a bankruptcy judge. The board 
gave its expected approval after the former NHL great made his 
presentation. The NHL has endorsed Lemieux's group all along in a 
determined effort to keep the Penguins in Pittsburgh. 

</P>
<P>
	H&AMP;R Block To Buy Discount Broker  
</P>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Tax preparer H&AMP;R Block, which has been  
buying accounting businesses, now has an agreement to buy the 
nation's fourth-largest discount broker. Block said today it is 
acquiring Olde Financial Corp., the parent company of Olde Discount 
Corp., for $850 million in cash in its largest single acquisition 
yet. The move is one more step in H&AMP;R Block's long-term growth 
strategy of providing a full complement of financial services. 

</P>
<P>
