<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Lemieux Takeover of Penguins OK'd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Now that he's back in the NHL as an owner, Mario  
Lemieux has plenty of ideas about how to make hockey more 
attractive. 
</P>
<P>
	First things first, though. His initial priorities center around  
making the Pittsburgh Penguins more attractive. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other things, that means lower ticket prices and,  
eventually, a new arena. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to make it more (reasonable) for families and young  
kids to come back to the Civic Arena,'' Lemieux said Wednesday 
after the NHL's Board of Governors approved his takeover of the 
team with partners. 
</P>
<P>
	A new arena will be necessary to keep the team in Pittsburgh,  
Lemieux said. The Penguins currently play in the 38-year-old Civic 
Arena, oldest in the NHL. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux, the highest-paid player in the league when he starred  
in Pittsburgh, said he will also turn his attention to keeping his 
players' salaries as low as possible. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a lot of work to do,'' said Lemieux, whose $13 million  
contract one season was higher than the combined total made by the 
next two players on the NHL salary scale. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux, a Hall of Famer who won six scoring titles and led the  
Penguins to Stanley Cup championships in 1991 and 1992, also said 
he would like to see more scoring in the NHL. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what I did best,'' he said. ``Hopefully, we can find a  
way to make the game higher scoring. We have to see what we can do 
to open the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux, of course, was the league's most ardent critic in this  
regard before retiring in 1997. He felt that skill players were 
hampered by suffocating defenses and a lack of effort by the league 
to crack down on pesky holding penalties that didn't allow players 
to skate. 
</P>
<P>
	Scoring has been down dramatically in the NHL in the '90s,  
prompting the league to rethink its rules. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux, without being specific, said he would ``do anything I  
can to improve the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He already has just by his presence, according to NHL  
commissioner Gary Bettman. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can all feel good about the Penguins in Pittsburgh,''  
Bettman said. ``Having (Lemieux) at the board level will be a 
positive, good for the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux's approval came during a Board of Governors meeting that  
was otherwise devoted to general business. Lemieux received a warm 
reception from the owners when he stepped into the room. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a lot of respect for Lemieux as a player,'' Bettman  
said. ``They were delighted that the effort was made, as he had 
done it, to keep hockey in Pittsburgh.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux's takeover climaxed a long struggle by the former hockey  
great and his associates to keep the team in Pittsburgh. Only court 
approval remains to finalize the deal, and that's expected to be 
taken care of by a bankruptcy judge during a hearing Friday in 
Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins went into bankruptcy last season and were only able  
to meet their payroll with the help of a bank loan. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's decision by the board made it just under the wire  
for the Penguins. They're due to open training camp on Saturday and 
will play their first exhibition game on Sept. 11 against the New 
York Islanders. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux said he and his group of investors, numbering more than  
a dozen, have put together $52 million so far and hope to raise 
more money. He said the market value of the Penguins is currently 
$85 million, the price of an expansion team. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux has the largest stake in the team, most of it coming  
from the $25 million in deferred salary the Penguins owed him. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was very important for me to keep the Penguins in  
Pittsburgh,'' Lemieux said. ``That's why I decided to put the group 
together. I have spent more than 15 years of my life in Pittsburgh, 
and I have a good relationship with the fans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux is the first retired player to take over ownership in  
one of the four major North American pro sports leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very excited about the opportunity to come back,'' Lemieux  
said. ``This is a dream come true, after 10 months working on the 
deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had no idea it would be this difficult. I'm glad we were  
finally able to put this together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The arena lease with SMG, a Philadelphia-based company,  
accounted for much of the delay in Lemieux's takeover. Under the 
lease, SMG will continue to control the Civic Arena until 2004, 
when it will revert to Lemieux, with SMG as the arena manager. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins blamed the high cost of their lease with SMG to  
play at the Civic Arena for helping push the franchise into 
bankruptcy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
