<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 22:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Punter Treated for Suspected Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Rookie punter Josh Bidwell underwent  
surgery Wednesday for a suspected case of testicular cancer, Green 
Bay Packers general manager Ron Wolf said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Diagnosis and prognosis will be forthcoming, and we will make  
that information known when it becomes available to us,'' Wolf 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	A source close to the Bidwell family was quoted by the Milwaukee  
Journal Sentinel as saying the surgery went well and the problem 
was caught early, possibly allowing Bidwell to return to the field 
in 2-to-4 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Bidwell noticed something was wrong a couple days ago, reported  
it to a doctor and had an ultrasound exam Wednesday, resulting in 
the decision to do the surgery the same day, the source told the 
newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Bidwell, the Packers' fourth-round draft pick from Oregon and  
the first punter drafted in 1999, was the only punter on Green 
Bay's roster. He also had been the primary holder for placekicker 
Ryan Longwell. 
</P>
<P>
	He practiced with the team Tuesday afternoon, and it wasn't  
immediately clear when the suspected cancer had been found. A 
Packers spokesperson said the surgery took place Wednesday 
afternoon and that doctors would know more about Bidwell's 
condition in the next two days. 
</P>
<P>
	The Packers claimed first-year punter Chris Hanson on waivers  
from the Cleveland Browns to fill in for Bidwell. Green Bay plays 
its final exhibition game against the Miami Dolphins on Thursday 
night at Lambeau Field. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the Packers kept Bidwell as their only punter even  
though he hadn't lived up to expectations in exhibition games. 
</P>
<P>
	He had his best performance last weekend at New Orleans,  
averaging 43.5 yards on six punts. The 6-foot-3 Bidwell's size and 
athleticism, along with his booming 46.0 yards-per-punt averaged 
during his senior season at Oregon, convinced the Packers to spend 
a fourth-round pick on him. 
</P>
<P>
	Bidwell was a second-team All-America at Oregon last season.  
Originally recruited by the Ducks as a receiver, Bidwell signed 
with the Packers the day after training camp began in July. 
</P>
<P>
	The Packers were concerned by Bidwell's inconsistency during  
training camp and exhibition games. He attributed his problems in 
part to the new NFL rule requiring untouched footballs be used in 
kicking situations, which made kicking more difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not anything mechanical with myself,'' Bidwell said last  
week. ``I'm kicking the way I always do. It's just an adjustment I 
have to make to the pro game. I know I've got to make it quickly, 
though.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hanson, who played at Marshall, signed as a free agent with  
Cleveland last April and averaged 43.7 yards on 10 punts in three 
exhibition games for the Browns. 
</P>
<P>
	Defensive end Chris Reed, a first-year player from Abilene  
Christian, was waived to make room for Hanson on the roster. 
</P>
<P>
	Sean Landeta, the Packers' punter in the previous three seasons,  
signed with Philadelphia in the offseason. Bidwell beat out 
journeyman Will Brice for Green Bay's top job last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolf's announcement about Bidwell's surgery came late Wednesday  
afternoon -- only two days after former Packers defensive 
coordinator Fritz Shurmur died from cancer in Green Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just found out this afternoon,'' team president Bob Harlan  
said shortly after the announcement. ``I talked to Ron and he told 
me about the surgery. We're awaiting the results.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
