<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 13:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> ITF Applauds Drug Ruling Vs. Korda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The governing body of tennis says the decision  
to uphold the action against Petr Korda strengthens its stance on 
drugs in sports. 
</P>
<P>
	``This whole case hasn't been about the ITF vs. Petr Korda,''  
Deborah Jevans, executive director for medicine of the 
International Tennis Federation, said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been about the whole integrity of the sport and its  
anti-doping program. If we find ourselves whereby `I don't know' is 
a valid and acceptable excuse for a player to have a banned 
substance in their body, then, to be honest, there's little point 
in testing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That essentially was Korda's explanation when traces of the  
steroid Nadrolone were found in his system after he lost in the 
quarterfinals at Wimbledon in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	When an independent appeals committee, a three-person panel of  
medical, technical and legal experts, accepted the explanation, the 
ITF appealed to the Court of Arbitration for Sport. The appeal was 
upheld Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	ITF lawyer Darren Bailey said the arbitration panel did not  
accept Korda's account that he did not know how the substances got 
into his body. 
</P>
<P>
	``The player couldn't establish the relevant circumstances in  
which the offense occurred, and therefore, he was unable to 
establish the reasonableness of his action,'' Bailey said. ``In 
those circumstances, he was unable to rely on the exceptional 
circumstances provision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bailey said the decision makes the players more responsible for  
their actions. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a key component of the decision,'' he said. ``In the  
future, players will be accountable for having to identify what 
substances entered the body and how it happened. I think that's an 
important lesson because it reinforces the responsibility on all 
players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Young, general counsel for the ATP Tour, said the Korda  
case would lead to some changes in the ITF drug program. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're pleased the decision has helped clarify the  
interpretation of the rule as we always said it should be 
interpreted,'' he said. ``However, we also think it's prudent to 
look at the specifics and make some adjustments in the language to 
help avoid this in the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Korda, winner of the 1998 Australian Open and once No. 2 in the  
world, retired from tennis after failing to qualify at Wimbledon in 
June. His penalty for the drug offense is forfeiture of all his 
ranking points and tennis earnings from the time of the offense. 
That comes to more than $660,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure he's writing the check right now,'' Jevans said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 14:20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Workers Fight English-Only Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Carlos Solero couldn't believe his ears when his  
bosses started reprimanding him for speaking Spanish on the job. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even if I was singing to myself or just mumbling, I would get  
a warning,'' the 31-year-old assembly-line worker says of the 
``English only'' policy his bosses instituted at a suburban Chicago 
manufacturing plant two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said the policy was needed to improve communication  
on its assembly line. Eventually, Solero was asked to sign a work 
agreement that included the policy -- but refused. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told them, 'You cannot shut me up,''' says Solero, who was  
fired three days later. 
</P>
<P>
	Now he and seven other Spanish-speakers -- and the federal Equal  
Employment Opportunity Commission -- have filed lawsuits against 
Watlow Batavia, a metal-casting and assembly plant in Batavia, Ill. 
</P>
<P>
	Legal experts say it's part of a growing movement against  
employers who try to force workers to speak English on the job. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we're going to see more and more of these types of  
lawsuits, especially as the population of immigrants grows and more 
languages are spoken in the workplace,'' says Jose Behar, an EEOC 
attorney handling the agency's lawsuit against Watlow. 
</P>
<P>
	Complaints filed by the EEOC against companies with English-only  
polices have nearly tripled in the last three years, according to 
an agency spokesman. Ninety-one were filed nationwide last year, 
compared with 32 in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not that English-only policies are illegal. Companies can  
have them as long as they can prove they are a ``business 
necessity'' -- say, in an air-traffic control tower. 
</P>
<P>
	Trouble is, say Behar and others, some companies are taking it  
too far -- and instituting policies often because they simply want 
to know what their employees are talking about. 
</P>
<P>
	``When there's some type of health and safety at stake, those  
are situations where English only should be required. But in the 
vast majority of jobs, there really is no justification,'' says 
Donya Fernandez, an attorney with the Language Rights Project, a 
San Francisco-based organization that serves as a resource for 
workers who either can't or sometimes prefer not to speak English. 
</P>
<P>
	This summer, the organization helped work out an agreement at an  
Emeryville, Calif., casino where kitchen cooks were told they had 
to speak English, even though they all spoke Cantonese. 
</P>
<P>
	Human resource officials agree they're having to deal more often  
with candidates who speak other languages as technology companies 
increasingly are recruiting from overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Hawn, a computer industry headhunter for Cleveland-based  
Management Recruiters, says he's often asked to find candidates who 
speak another language -- most recently, a request for a 
Korean-speaking computer systems engineer. 
</P>
<P>
	But he's also seen a language backlash. He says a hiring manager  
at a Fortune 100 company in New York recently asked him not to send 
any more candidates with strong accents for an Internet hardware 
sales position. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was really pushing the envelope of EEOC laws. I was really  
uncomfortable,'' says Hawn, who complained to the manager's 
supervisor. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at Watlow defend their English-only policy, which they  
say was temporary and part of an overall plan to improve an 
assembly department in crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have nothing against speaking any other language as long as  
the customer's needs are being met ... But the department was 
experiencing problems where we thought communication was only one 
of many issues,'' said Diana Rader, the human resources manager for 
the company. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the workers in the assembly department spoke Spanish,  
she concedes. ``(But) when you had supervisors and customers coming 
in and trying to help solve the problems, the common language was 
English,'' she says. 
</P>
<P>
	The cases against Watlow Batavia are expected to be heard in  
U.S. District Court in Chicago early next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Historically, rulings have been mixed. The U.S. Supreme Court  
refused to review a federal appeals court's 1994 decision that 
allowed a South San Francisco, Calif., meatpacker to continue using 
its English-only policy -- a ruling President Clinton opposed. But 
in January, a federal judge in Chicago ruled in favor of 200 
workers who fought an English-only policy at Synchro-Start 
Products, a Niles, Ill., manufacturing company. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, Solero has gotten a job as a line worker at  
another suburban Chicago company, Kraft Foods Inc., where he says 
he's free to speak Spanish. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're in the United States. I understand that,'' says Solero,  
who grew up in Puerto Rico and now lives in Aurora, Ill. ``But when 
I'm talking to another Hispanic person, why shouldn't I be able to 
speak my own language?'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
