<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 14:10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IRS Reviews Cash-Balance Pensions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Critics of a popular new kind of pension plan  
said Wednesday a confidential Internal Revenue Service memo 
bolsters their claims that the plans violate age-discrimination 
laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Bernie Sanders, I-Vt., said the IRS district office in  
Cincinnati raised questions about ``cash-balance'' plans that bear 
out ``what I and others have been saying: If the rate of accrual 
goes down as workers get older, then the plan violates the law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders is among 40 members of Congress who have requested an  
investigation by the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission and 
the Labor Department. 
</P>
<P>
	The memo, dated September 1998 and released this week by  
Sanders, says that the cash-balance plan at an unnamed company 
``does not satisfy the clear and straightforward requirement'' of 
age bias law because the benefit accrual rate ``decreases as a 
participant attains each additional year of age.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A similar plan adopted July 1 by IBM has triggered protests from  
some of the computer giant's workers around the country. About 700 
IBM workers at a microchip plant in Essex Junction, Vt., attended a 
Sanders town meeting on the issue earlier this month. 
</P>
<P>
	``On its face, it seems to me that there is real question about  
the legality of IBM's actions,'' Sanders said. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM spokeswoman Jana Weatherbee said that while some workers  
oppose the new plan it is essential for the company to keep pace 
with benefits packages offered by competitors like Intel and 
Compaq. 
</P>
<P>
	``We still spend the same amount of money on our people, but we  
shifted some money from the pension plan to cash compensation and 
stock options,'' she said. ``The predominant work model today is 
that you don't spend your whole career at one company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More than 300 companies have converted to the cash-balance  
pension plans, which can reduce costs by cutting future benefits to 
middle-aged workers while allowing younger workers to take a larger 
payout if they depart before retiring. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics say the losers in these plans are workers with 15 or  
more years of service. 
</P>
<P>
	Under more traditional defined-benefit pension plans, workers  
receive the maximum amount based on length of service and their 
level of salary in final years before retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRS gets involved in pension plans because corporate  
contributions are tax deductible. The Cincinnati memo involves only 
one unidentified company and asks the IRS to set a national policy, 
but that has not yet been done. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders and others want the IRS to halt all approvals until the  
age bias allegations are reviewed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given the serious and unresolved age discrimination questions  
that exist, the service (the IRS) should not bless these 
arrangements,'' the 40 House members said in their letter. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
