<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 17:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Second Chances for Umps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Rich Garcia didn't want sympathy, not at that moment, anyway. He  
would have settled for a little understanding. 
</P>
<P>
	Garcia stood at a pay phone outside a Philadelphia courtroom,  
waiting to find out whether he and 21 other umpires still had the 
jobs they sweated and sacrificed for, and in his case, labored at 
for 25 years, loving nearly every minute. 
</P>
<P>
	That was Tuesday. Garcia had to wait Wednesday as well after the  
court hearing again failed to produce a decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody has bills. Everybody has kids in school,'' Garcia  
said. ``Anybody who works for a living understands what that's 
like. 
</P>
<P>
	``What they don't understand,'' he added, ``is why we did what  
we did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What Garcia and just about every other umpire in the union did  
was hand in their resignations to major league baseball in 
mid-July. They became effective Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The mass-resignation scheme, hatched by bellicose union boss  
Richie Phillips, might go down as the dumbest negotiating ploy in 
the long and messy history of labor relations. 
</P>
<P>
	With the umpires contract expiring Dec. 31. Phillips feared a  
lockout and was looking for a way around the no-strike provision in 
the existing contract. Why he chose professional suicide is still 
anybody's guess, because by resigning voluntarily, the umps 
surrendered what little protection federal labor law extends. 
</P>
<P>
	When they got the news, the suits running baseball could hardly  
believe their good fortune. Without explaining the rhyme or reason, 
American League president Gene Budig sent letters to nine umps 
accepting their resignations; his NL counterpart, Len Coleman, 
mailed pink slips to an additional 13. Then baseball hired 25 minor 
league umpires to replace them. 
</P>
<P>
	What followed was a lawyer's dream. The umpires filed a lawsuit  
July 26, but withdrew it just ahead of baseball's request to 
dismiss. Their union filed an unfair labor practice charge with the 
National Labor Relations Board, which Daniel Silverman, the NLRB's 
New York agency regional director, said could be decided this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, the umpires went back to court Monday, asking U.S.  
District Judge J. Curtis Joyner to issue an injunction preventing 
baseball from letting the 22 go. Instead of a hearing, seven hours 
of conferences ensued -- with the legal meters running -- while 
Joyner put the matter off until Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The hardest part,'' Garcia said, ``is that people are  
laughing, saying, `Hey, you resign, you lose your job.' Well, all 
we were trying to do was get baseball to the bargaining table. It 
didn't work. But none of us saw what was coming. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love my job,'' he said. ``It's all I've ever wanted to do.  
It's been hard enough on the veterans, but we've got some young 
guys who waited years for their shot, and now their necks are on 
the block, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The complaint argues the integrity of baseball will be harmed  
unless the best and most experienced umpires work the games, but 
the union was not beyond a sympathy plea, either. The legal brief 
before Joyner lists all the umpires scheduled for termination, 
along with their marital status and the number of children and 
grandchildren they have. There are sad stories spilling out behind 
each and every name. 
</P>
<P>
	Some, like 52-year-old Jim Evans and 50-year-old Greg Kosc, are  
probably too old to take up a new line of work. A relative 
youngster, Ed Hickox worked the minors for 17 years before getting 
his callup to the big leagues at the start of this season. His 
payback for all that time away from family, for staying in cheap 
motels and working the far-flung, dimly lighted corners of the 
baseball universe, was just beginning. 
</P>
<P>
	No wonder, then, that Hickox broke into tears the other night  
during an interview with ESPN, trying to explain how much it meant 
to him to work a game close to home with his two small daughters 
looking on proudly from the stands. And then there's perhaps the 
saddest story of all, of umpire Drew Coble, about to lose not just 
his job, but his wife to cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every one of us has a family that's going to be hurt,'' Garcia  
said. ``And every one of us loves baseball. I look back at what got 
us here and I think, `Yeah, we did it, but somebody would have to 
be nuts to take us seriously.''' 
</P>
<P>
	In the cruel way that his business often works, Garcia became  
perhaps the best-known umpire working when he blew a call in right 
field in the AL playoff between the Orioles and Yankees three 
seasons ago. Then, a 13-year-old New Yorker named Jeff Maier leaned 
over the railing and helped turn a warning-track fly ball into a 
hometown home run. 
</P>
<P>
	Garcia regretted it then. But it's no longer the one call he  
wishes he could make all over again. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at jlitke@ap.org. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
