<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Markets Mixed, Tokyo Rallies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed mixed Wednesday, but  
the region's largest exchange, Tokyo, surged ahead amid speculation 
the Japanese government will intervene to stop the yen from rising 
further against the U.S. dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed up  
365.92 points, or 2.1 percent, at 17,802.48. It had fallen 482.41 
points, or 2.69 percent, on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Increasing talk about government intervention to stop the  
Japanese yen's rise boosted export and banking stocks, analysts 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But currency traders were less optimistic and sold the dollar as  
they saw no signs that the Bank of Japan was buying the greenback 
to prop it up. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar traded at its lowest level since January. Late  
Wednesday, the dollar bought 109.22 yen, down 0.96 yen from 110.18 
yen late Tuesday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level of 
109.59 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar last traded below 110 yen in Tokyo on Jan. 12.  
</P>
<P>
	A strong local currency could hurt the country's economy by  
making its exports more expensive abroad, and thus less 
competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, share prices finished moderately higher, although  
bigger early gains were wiped out by heavy selling in companies 
with close ties to mainland China. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue-chip Hang Seng Index closed up 61.42 points, or 0.5  
percent, at 13,544.19. The Hang Seng had fallen 1.5 percent 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Taipei, the key index reached a seven-week high as investors  
continued to snap up semiconductor shares on expectations that 
sector will continue to recover. 
</P>
<P>
	The Weighted Price Index rose 115.60 points, or 1.4 percent, to  
8,273.33, the highest level since July 12, when the index ended at 
8,463.90. 
</P>
<P>
	In South Korea, shares plunged on rumors that some of Hyundai  
Group's executives were arrested for manipulating stock prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kospi index fell 32.36 points, or 3.5 percent, to 905.52.  
</P>
<P>
	The state-run Yonhap News Agency later confirmed that  
prosecutors were planning to arrest Hyundai Securities Co. Chairman 
Lee Ik-chi on stock manipulation charges. 
</P>
<P>
	The prosecutors also are barring nine executive of the  
conglomerate, including Lee, from leaving South Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai stocks fell as the precipitous fall of its  
currency, the baht, against the dollar added to negative sentiment 
on the banking sector. The SET index lost 5.71 points, or 1.3 
percent, to 434.56, 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares rebounded from recent losses, but  
trading was thin amid recent political and economic uncertainties. 
The Jakarta Stock Exchange Composite index rose 0.8 percent, or 
4.750 points, to 571.776. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian shares slumped on selling by foreign  
fund managers. The Composite index fell 14.5 points, or 1.8 
percent, to 752.91 points. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine stocks fell for the fifth straight session on  
concerns over U.S. and domestic interest rates. The PSE index fell 
21.06 points, or 0.9 percent, to 2,152.76. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Singapore shares rose slightly, but sentiment  
remained weak after the 1.6 percent fall Tuesday. The Straits Times 
Index rose 5.17 points, or 0.2 percent, to 2,122.34. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian shares rose, as strengthening base metal  
prices lifted demand for mining stocks. The All Ordinaries Index 
closed at 2,997.4, up 45.5 points, or 1.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand shares closed nearly flat amid a lack of  
clear leads. The NZSE-40 Capital Index fell 2.54 points, or 0.1 
percent, to 2,150.08. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
