<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Construction Spending Falls in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Construction spending fell unexpectedly in  
July, declining 0.5 percent, a sign that one of the economy's 
strongest sectors is beginning to slow. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department said today that spending fell to a  
seasonally adjusted annual rate of $695.7 billion. In June, 
construction spending fell slightly, according to revised figures. 
Previously the government estimated that spending had actually 
increased 0.5 percent in June. 
</P>
<P>
	July's spending decrease was worse than many analysts'  
expectations. They were forecasting that spending would actually go 
up a sizable 0.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Home building and other construction activity -- driven by low  
mortgage rates -- were a key contributing factor to the strong 
economic growth in the early part of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	To slow down the economy and prevent inflation, the Federal  
Reserve last week bumped up interest rates by a quarter of a point, 
making borrowing more expensive. The Fed hinted additional rate 
increases may not be needed this year unless the economy shows 
signs of overheating or inflation flares. 
</P>
<P>
	Higher interest rates are starting to weigh on the minds of more  
Americans. The Conference Board reported Tuesday that its index of 
consumer confidence -- which measures consumers' likeliness to spend 
-- fell for the second straight month in August. 
</P>
<P>
	Rising mortgage rates took a bite out of the housing market in  
July. Existing-home sales fell 3.9 percent, while sales of new 
homes rose a slight 0.1 percent but still reached the 
second-highest level ever. 
</P>
<P>
	The construction report showed that spending on all private  
construction projects fell 0.7 percent in July, following a tiny 
increase in June. In July, Private construction totaled $545 
billion, on a seasonally adjusted annual basis. However, spending 
on hotels and motels, and office buildings showing increases. 
</P>
<P>
	Spending on government projects rose 0.3 percent to a seasonally  
adjusted annual rate of $150.7 billion, after falling slightly in 
June. Government spending on schools and other educational 
facilities, conservation and development systems and water supply 
plants all showed decreases. 
</P>
<P>
	Spending on all residential projects fell 0.8 percent in July to  
a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $319 billion with spending on 
single-family homes down while spending on apartments was up. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 08:30:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> French Check 2 Retail Chains' Stock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- The French stock market watchdog said today it  
would look into a rise in share prices of Carrefour and Promodes 
before the two French retail chains announced their merger earlier 
this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will examine trading in Carrefour and Promodes shares ahead  
of and after the takeover offer,'' the Operations Commission of the 
Bourse said. 
</P>
<P>
	Such surveillance is normal following large mergers and does not  
mean an investigation will be launched. In the past month, the 
watchdog commission has said that it would look into several 
mergers, including the proposed creation of aluminum giant 
Alcan-Pechiney-Algroup, which would be formed by the combination of 
Canadian aluminum giant Alcan Aluminium, French company Pechiney 
and Alusuisse-Lonza (Algroup) of Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	The friendly stock deal between Carrefour and Promodes announced  
Monday -- valued at about $16.3 billion -- would create the world's 
second largest retail group, behind Wal-Mart Stores Inc., in the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Promodes shares rose 6.7 percent Friday in heavy trading volume  
while Carrefour shares rose nearly 2.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Carrefour-Promodes operation will have a market  
capitalization of about $49 billion and expected annual sales of 
more than $50 billion. However, it will still be much smaller than 
Wal-Mart, which had sales of $140 billion last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Both groups are primarily food retailers, with several  
well-known supermarket chains. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts have mentioned both Carrefour and Promodes as potential  
prey for Wal-Mart. The U.S. giant, based in Bentonville, Ark., has 
already made two acquisitions in Germany and most recently, it 
bought the British supermarket chain Asda Group PLC. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
