<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                       *Edward Charles Bassett    	
</P>
<P>
	MILL VALLEY, Calif. (AP) -- Architect Edward Charles Bassett, who  
designed buildings around the world, including San Francisco's 
symphony hall and the U.S. Embassy in Moscow, died Saturday of a 
stroke. He was 77. 
</P>
<P>
	Bassett's San Francisco work includes the Louise M. Davies  
Symphony Hall, the Bank of America headquarters building, the 
Crocker Galleria and the Industrial Indemnity building. 
</P>
<P>
	Bassett was the design partner for Skidmore, Owings &AMP; Merrill in  
San Francisco for 21 years until his retirement in 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	Bassett's designs can be seen all over the United States and in  
a number of foreign countries. They include the Oakland-Alameda 
County Coliseum; the Australian Mutual Provident Society complex in 
Melbourne; and the Royal Dutch Shell headquarters in The Hague. 
</P>
<P>
	Among his awards were the Brunner Prize in Architecture from the  
National Institute of Arts and Letters and the Maybeck Award from 
the California Council of the American Institute of Architects. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Morris Camhi    	
</P>
<P>
	PETALUMA, Calif. (AP) -- Morris Camhi, whose photographs of  
prisoners, farmworkers and Greek Jews were exhibited all over the 
world, died Friday of cancer. He was 71. 
</P>
<P>
	After college, Camhi worked as an advertising photographer. He  
opened his own advertising studio in 1960 but sold it nine years 
later to pursue more artistic aspirations. 
</P>
<P>
	Camhi began teaching photography at San Francisco City College  
in 1972. From the mid-1980s on, his work was exhibited at the San 
Francisco Museum of Modern Art and later in Chicago, New York, 
Japan, Europe and New Zealand. Camhi served as a mentor to numerous 
local photographers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sonoma Museum will run a retrospective of Camhi's work next  
year. 

</P>
<P>
                              *Ed Kea    	
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Former St. Louis Blues defenseman Ed Kea, whose  
hockey career was cut short by a head injury, drowned to death 
Tuesday in an accident at his family's summer cottage in Ontario. 
He was 51. 
</P>
<P>
	Kea played 583 games over 10 seasons in the NHL, scoring 30  
goals and 175 points. He spent his first six seasons with the 
Atlanta Flames, who signed him as a free-agent on Oct. 6, 1972. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blues acquired him along with Don Laurence and a draft pick  
in a trade for center Garry Unger on Oct. 10, 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	He was playing for the Blues' Central Hockey League affiliate in  
Salt Lake City in 1983 when he suffered the injury that ended his 
career. Kea suffered severe head trauma when he fell and hit his 
head on the ice during a game. The injury left him physically and 
mentally disabled. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Willie Mays Sr.    	
</P>
<P>
	REDWOOD CITY, Calif. (AP) -- Willie Mays Sr., the father of the  
Hall of Fame outfielder, died Friday after a brief illness. He was 
89. 
</P>
<P>
	Mays, a retired steelworker and railroad porter, was a versatile  
athlete and passed his love of baseball on to his son, who played 
for the Giants in New York and San Francisco, and later the Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	Mays Sr. was born in the industrial town of Westfield, Ala., and  
played for black baseball teams in the South. He worked on 
passenger trains as a porter and later in a Westfield steel mill. 
At one point, he and his son, then in high school, played together 
on the mill's semiprofessional baseball team. 
</P>
<P>
	Mays attended many of his son's games with the Giants before he  
lost his sight because of glaucoma. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
