<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Canucks' Top Scorer Gets $7.2M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- Markus Naslund, the Vancouver  
Canucks' leading scorer last year, was rewarded for his 
breakthrough season by signing a three-year contract on Wednesday 
worth $7.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think Markus' season last year was the first of several  
quality seasons to come,'' assistant general manager Dave Nonis 
said. ``We don't mind paying at all for guys that put out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 26-year-old left wing will earn $2.25 million this season,  
$2.35 million next season and $2.6 million in 2001-02. He earned 
$800,000 last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Naslund, a restricted free agent this summer, had career highs  
of 36 goals and 66 points last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nice to get a little stability with a three-year deal,  
after taking one-year deals the last three years,'' Naslund said 
from his home in Sweden. 
</P>
<P>
	Saying he found ``the joy'' for playing hockey again for the  
first time in many years last season, Naslund is confident he can 
continue to be a consistent offensive threat. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know there's going to be pressure, but I honestly like  
pressure,'' said Naslund, who before last year had managed a 
combined 63 goals in his first five seasons in the league. 
</P>
<P>
	``Years before, they really didn't count on me, they really  
didn't care if I was dressed or not, and I really didn't like 
that,'' he said. ``Last year I felt the pressure that I needed to 
score to help the team win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Drafted 16th overall by Pittsburgh in 1991, Naslund broke into  
the league in the 1993-94 season with the Penguins. The Canucks 
acquired him in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The Canucks, who open training camp Monday, have five remaining  
restricted free agents yet to sign, including defenseman Ed 
Jovanovski and left wing Todd Bertuzzi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
