<HEADLINE> Oil Stocks Help European Markets Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European stocks closed higher today, as healthy  
crude prices put oil stocks up among the day's best performers. 
</P>
<P>
	BP Amoco, the biggest stock in the Dow Jones Stoxx index, rose  
20 pence, or 1.7 percent, while France's Elf-Aquitaine rose 6.70 
euros to 172.70 euros, and TotalFina rose 2.80 euros to 124.80 
euros. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 592 European companies rose 1.58  
points, or 0.5 percent, to close at 310.27. The energy index closed 
with a gain of 1.6 percent, the conglomerate index rose 1.5 
percent, and the auto index rose 0.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks 297 companies in  
countries that joined the single currency, closed up 1.89 points at 
325.33. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index rose 26.48 points to 3,795.62,  
while the DJ Stoxx 50 Index closed up 25.06 points at 3,724.82. 
</P>
<P>
	In domestic markets, the Paris bourse was one of the strongest  
performers on the day, with the CAC-40 index gaining 1.0 percent to 
4,633.38. Carmakers Peugeot and Renault were boosted by 
better-than-expected numbers for new car registrations in August. 
</P>
<P>
	Peugeot showed the strongest growth in the month, with total  
vehicles registered up 51 percent, as French auto makers held their 
55 percent share of the domestic market. Peugeot shares rose 7.60 
euros to 181.60 euros Wednesday, and Renault rose 1.05 euros to 
52.05 euros. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the expanding auto market comes amid forecasts of  
a pickup in French economic growth in the second half of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, Frankfurt's Xetra DAX index rose 0.9 percent to  
5,317.12, and London's FTSE 100 was up 0.5 percent to 6,276.20. 
Amsterdam's AEX index fell 0.02 percent to 572.33. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
