<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pete Rose's Ex-Bookie Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEBANON, Ohio (AP) -- The man who said he was Pete Rose's  
bookmaker has been arrested on charges that include assaulting a 
police officer, a jail official said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ron Peters, 42, was scheduled to appear at a preliminary hearing  
Thursday afternoon in Warren County Court, according to the county 
jail in Lebanon. 
</P>
<P>
	Peters is accused of assaulting a Springboro police officer  
about 3 a.m. Tuesday, the Dayton Daily News reported in its 
Thursday editions. 
</P>
<P>
	A police report said the officer stopped Peters' car because it  
was weaving. The officer was injured when Peters elbowed him. 
</P>
<P>
	Peters drove from the scene, but was arrested about five hours  
later by a Warren County sheriff's deputy and taken to the jail, 
about 25 miles northeast of Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond was set at $50,000 for Peters, charged with driving under  
suspension, resisting arrest, falsification and the assault charge, 
said a jail official who would not give his name. 
</P>
<P>
	Peters helped authorities build their case against baseball's  
career hit leader, saying Rose placed bets on baseball, including 
the team he managed, the Cincinnati Reds. 
</P>
<P>
	Rose admitted betting through bookies, but denied placing bets  
on baseball. He later pleaded guilty to two felony counts of 
failing to report income from autograph appearances, baseball 
memorabilia sales and gambling. 
</P>
<P>
	Rose was banned from baseball in August 1989.  
</P>
<P>
	Peters served concurrent two-year sentences at a federal prison  
in Terre Haute, Ind., for tax and drug trafficking convictions. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
