<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans, Up a Bit / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain futures prices drifted marginally higher  
and soybean futures prices advanced in early trading today on the 
Chicago Board of trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures were unchanged to slightly higher as yesterday's  
strong close carried over into the day's trading. However, weak 
cash prices are draining the market of some strength. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures were unchanged to slightly higher as forecasts call  
for dry weather in the Midwest. There also is concern over crop 
quality. 
</P>
<P>
	Dry conditions is giving a boost to soybean futures prices. The  
distressed condition of large portions of the soybean crop is also 
boosting prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Department of Agriculture is reporting that only 47  
percent of all U.S. soybeans were in good to excellent condition -- 
a decline of 1 percentage point from a week ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures for September delivery were unchanged at $2.64 3/4 a  
bushel; September corn futures were unchanged at $2.05 1/4 a bushel; 
September oats were a 1/2 cent higher at $1.09 a bushel; September 
soybeans were a 1/2 cent higher at $4.79 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Cattle futures prices were lower, and hog and pork belly futures  
higher in trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle were .20 cent lower at 66.35 cents a pound;  
September feeder cattle were .10 cent lower at 78.02 cents a pound; 
October lean hogs were .55 cent higher at 46.35 cents a pound; 
February pork bellies were .30 cent higher at 59.05 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
