<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MIT Student Dies From Laughing Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- On the eve of a new semester another MIT student  
has died from substance abuse, despite efforts by the school to 
prevent such a tragedy. 
</P>
<P>
	After the 1997 drinking death of a freshman, Massachusetts  
Institute of Technology mandated alcohol education for all 
students. They established sanctions and will soon require all 
freshmen to live in campus dorms. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet on Tuesday, a 22-year-old physics major seeking a laughing  
gas high was found dead in his dorm room. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Guy, 22, of Mission Viejo, Calif., had apparently used a  
plastic bag to inhale the nitrous oxide. The bag was found on his 
head, a campus spokesman said 
</P>
<P>
	The medical examiner ruled the MIT junior died from asphyxiation  
as a result of nitrous oxide intoxication. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're treating it like an accident and that's because we have  
no evidence of a suicide,'' Ken Campbell, a university spokesman, 
said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In September 1997, Scott Krueger, an 18-year-old freshman, died  
three days after lapsing into an alcohol-induced coma on the floor 
of a fraternity. The incident drove campus officials to require all 
freshmen to live on campus beginning in fall 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the shock of Scott Krueger has penetrated a great deal  
and this will have a similar effect,'' Campbell said. 
</P>
<P>
	MIT is known among college administrators as having some of the  
best drug prevention programs anywhere. The school even provides 
literature about inhalants like nitrous oxide to students. 
</P>
<P>
	``Having the right program is no guarantee that you're not going  
to have a sensational incident like this,'' said Kevin Kruger, 
associate executive director of the National Association of Student 
Personnel Administrators, an organization for campus 
administrators. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
