<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Gov't Knocks Western Media </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia's government tried Wednesday to contain the  
damage from allegations of Russian mob involvement in money 
laundering through the Bank of New York, claiming that the case has 
been overblown by Western media and politicians. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said Western reports on the scandal  
were part of a deliberate policy by ``certain circles who don't 
want Russia to reassert its role as a great power.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ivanov, in a speech at the Moscow State Institute for  
International Relations, called the media reports ``an attempt to 
manipulate unconfirmed facts in order to cast a cloud on our 
nation. Russia will not tolerate that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ivanov also said the reports reflected a ``political struggle''  
in the United States, though he did not blame any specific 
politicians. Other Russian leaders have also suggested the news 
leaks in the scandal are rooted in U.S. election campaign battles. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators reportedly believe that up to $10 billion was  
laundered through the Bank of New York. Some reports claim that the 
money included International Monetary Fund aid to Russia -- an 
allegation Russian officials have angrily denied. 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Minister Vladimir Putin said his Cabinet has been on top  
of the case and was in close contact with the FBI and other U.S. 
agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	``If someone wants to blow up these issues because of political  
motives, he is free to do that, but this isn't going to either 
speed up or slow down investigators' work,'' he told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Putin had been asked about a statement by U.S. Treasury  
Secretary Lawrence Summers, who said in an interview with USA Today 
published Wednesday that Washington wouldn't support new IMF loans 
to Russia until there is an adequate account of previous IMF aid to 
the country. 
</P>
<P>
	A U.S. Treasury official, however, said in Washington Wednesday  
that the Clinton administration hasn't come to a decision on 
whether Russia should receive any additional loans from the IMF. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's central bank chairman, Viktor Gerashchenko, insisted  
Wednesday that ``the money which was received from the IMF was used 
properly to support budgetary revenues.'' He was speaking to Dow 
Jones Newswires during a trip to Zurich, Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian government was initially silent about the scandal,  
which was first reported last month. It could be the among the 
largest money laundering schemes ever uncovered in the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	Money laundering is the process of moving criminal gains through  
a series of bank accounts to make them look like legitimate 
business proceeds. 
</P>
<P>
	No one has been charged with any crime in the case.  
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of New York case is just one of several that allegedly  
link prominent Russian political or business figures to corruption 
and money laundering. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian prosecutor Nikolai Volkov was in Switzerland this week  
to examine documents and consult with his Swiss counterparts on a 
case involving a Swiss construction company suspected of bribing 
its way into the Kremlin to get lucrative renovation contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	Kremlin officials and the head of the company, Mabetex, have  
denied any wrongdoing. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
