<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GM, DaimlerChrysler Sales Strong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Pickups, sport utility vehicles and minivans  
continued to pull buyers onto car lots in August, setting high 
marks for sales at General Motors Corp., DaimlerChrysler AG and 
several foreign automakers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's one of the strongest months ever for vehicle sales,''  
said David Healy, a Burnham Securities Inc. analyst. ``If anything, 
the pace of sales seems to be strengthening rather than dropping 
month to month.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Experts said the results were in line with expectations that the  
industry's yearly sales total would shatter the record of 16.1 
million vehicles, set in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	GM said Wednesday its sales were up 64 percent over last year --  
a comparison skewed by United Auto Workers strikes that all but 
halted GM's North American production last year. 
</P>
<P>
	GM also said it set an August record for truck sales behind its  
sport utility vehicles, including the Chevrolet/GMC Suburban, Chevy 
Tahoe and GMC Yukon. The company recently has added rebates of up 
to $1,000 on slow-selling models in its full-size pickup line -- the 
first since redesigned versions were introduced this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The industry continues to run at a spectacular rate, and  
manufacturers are competing fiercely for every sale,'' said John G. 
Middlebrook, GM vice president and general manager of vehicle brand 
marketing. 
</P>
<P>
	Trucks also pulled sales in DaimlerChrysler's Chrysler unit up 9  
percent over last year. Chrysler's cars were up less than 1 
percent, but trucks were up 13 percent behind sales of the Jeep 
Grand Cherokee, which set a record for its sales in any month. 
</P>
<P>
	Like GM, DaimlerChrysler offered a wide range of rebates,  
discount leases and finance rates on many of its models. Automakers 
have traditionally used incentives in August to push last year's 
models off car lots, but this year there appeared to be better 
deals for car buyers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ironic thing in this period of very strong sales is that  
incentives are really driving the market,'' said Alan Baum, an 
analyst with IRN Inc. ``The reason is that auto companies want to 
maintain their market share.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign automakers also reported record August sales. Toyota  
said sales were up 3 percent, beating the record set for the month 
last year. While Toyota's car sales were down slightly, sales of 
its Lexus SUVs and its new Tundra full-size pickup more than made 
up for the difference. 
</P>
<P>
	Honda said sales were up 10.5 percent last month, breaking the  
record for the month set in 1997. Honda's redesigned Odyssey 
minivan and Accord sedan powered the increase. 
</P>
<P>
	Volkswagen said its sales were up 34 percent, while Mitsubishi  
said sales were up 48 percent. Mercedes-Benz and Subaru also 
reported higher sales. One exception to the trend was Nissan, whose 
sales were down 8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford Motor Co. was scheduled to release its sales today.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
