<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 09:56:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Venice Film Festival Opens Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VENICE, Italy (AP) -- The grande dame of film festivals opened  
today with a flurry of self-doubt and high-minded pledges about 
cinema as art. It was, in other words, business as usual on the 
Lido. 
</P>
<P>
	The Venice Film Festival, now in its 56th edition, is the  
world's oldest film festival and it has suffered in recent years 
from a mid-life crisis. The festival's last director floundered for 
two years, then stunned everyone by quitting on the last day and 
declaring festivals obsolete. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe there is something wrong with film festivals as such,''  
the new director, Alberto Barbera, admitted today. But, he added, 
``none of us has an innovative model to counter it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That said, Barbera has put together a program that seems to have  
something for everyone, including enough high-wattage star power to 
send spectators scrambling for their sunscreen and ample portions 
of both sex and violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Barbera brings a fresh eye and a taste for young directors to  
the festival, where established talent will be competing against 
relative newcomers. He also displays his love for masters of the 
medium such as Stanley Kubrick, Alfred Hitchcock and Akira 
Kurosawa. 
</P>
<P>
	The festival also features two of the most talked-about American  
movies of the year, neither showing in competition. 
</P>
<P>
	The festival opens with the European premiere of Kubrick's final  
work, ``Eyes Wide Shut.'' Stars Nicole Kidman and Tom Cruise are on 
hand, as is Kubrick's widow. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fight Club,'' starring Brad Pitt and Edward Norton, will also  
be shown. 
</P>
<P>
	As a special tribute to Kubrick, ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' is showing  
on all three of the festival's main screens tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	The movies are, of course, also about commerce and Venice is an  
important European launching pad for Hollywood films. In addition 
to ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' it boasts several other intriguing premieres 
out of competition, including Woody Allen's ``Sweet and Lowdown,'' 
starring Sean Penn and Uma Thurman, and horror king Wes Craven's 
first conventional movie, ``Music of the Heart,'' with Meryl 
Streep, Aiden Quinn, Angela Bassett and Gloria Estefan. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the competitors are ``Holy Smoke'' from the Oscar-winning  
director of ``The Piano,'' Jane Campion, ``Topsy-Turvy'' from Mike 
Leigh, director of the acclaimed ``Secrets and Lies,'' ``The Cider 
House Rules,'' an adaptation of John Irving's best-selling novel, 
and ``Mask of Zorro'' star Antonio Banderas' directorial debut, 
``Crazy in Alabama,'' starring his wife, Melanie Griffith. 
</P>
<P>
	The festival wraps up on Sept. 11 with a career achievement  
award for comedian Jerry Lewis. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 09:56:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Venice Film Festival Opens Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VENICE, Italy (AP) -- The grande dame of film festivals opened  
today with a flurry of self-doubt and high-minded pledges about 
cinema as art. It was, in other words, business as usual on the 
Lido. 
</P>
<P>
	The Venice Film Festival, now in its 56th edition, is the  
world's oldest film festival and it has suffered in recent years 
from a mid-life crisis. The festival's last director floundered for 
two years, then stunned everyone by quitting on the last day and 
declaring festivals obsolete. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe there is something wrong with film festivals as such,''  
the new director, Alberto Barbera, admitted today. But, he added, 
``none of us has an innovative model to counter it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That said, Barbera has put together a program that seems to have  
something for everyone, including enough high-wattage star power to 
send spectators scrambling for their sunscreen and ample portions 
of both sex and violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Barbera brings a fresh eye and a taste for young directors to  
the festival, where established talent will be competing against 
relative newcomers. He also displays his love for masters of the 
medium such as Stanley Kubrick, Alfred Hitchcock and Akira 
Kurosawa. 
</P>
<P>
	The festival also features two of the most talked-about American  
movies of the year, neither showing in competition. 
</P>
<P>
	The festival opens with the European premiere of Kubrick's final  
work, ``Eyes Wide Shut.'' Stars Nicole Kidman and Tom Cruise are on 
hand, as is Kubrick's widow. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fight Club,'' starring Brad Pitt and Edward Norton, will also  
be shown. 
</P>
<P>
	As a special tribute to Kubrick, ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' is showing  
on all three of the festival's main screens tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	The movies are, of course, also about commerce and Venice is an  
important European launching pad for Hollywood films. In addition 
to ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' it boasts several other intriguing premieres 
out of competition, including Woody Allen's ``Sweet and Lowdown,'' 
starring Sean Penn and Uma Thurman, and horror king Wes Craven's 
first conventional movie, ``Music of the Heart,'' with Meryl 
Streep, Aiden Quinn, Angela Bassett and Gloria Estefan. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the competitors are ``Holy Smoke'' from the Oscar-winning  
director of ``The Piano,'' Jane Campion, ``Topsy-Turvy'' from Mike 
Leigh, director of the acclaimed ``Secrets and Lies,'' ``The Cider 
House Rules,'' an adaptation of John Irving's best-selling novel, 
and ``Mask of Zorro'' star Antonio Banderas' directorial debut, 
``Crazy in Alabama,'' starring his wife, Melanie Griffith. 
</P>
<P>
	The festival wraps up on Sept. 11 with a career achievement  
award for comedian Jerry Lewis. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 20:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Carson, Calif. Pitches NFL Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARSON, Calif. (AP) -- Carson made its pitch for a football team  
again to the NFL on Wednesday, with officials in this suburban city 
seemingly just as unclear on their prospects as other groups trying 
to lure a team to the Los Angeles area. 
</P>
<P>
	Roger Goodell, an NFL vice president who is the league's point  
man on stadiums, made City Hall here the last of his four stops 
during a whirlwind visit to Southern California. His itinerary had 
him holding separate meetings earlier in the day with backers of 
the Coliseum, Hollywood Park in Inglewood, and Anaheim as possible 
homes for an NFL team. 
</P>
<P>
	After talking for about an hour with Carson City Manager Jerry  
Groomes and attorney Darold Pieper, Goodell rushed off to catch a 
flight without speaking to reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were aware they were visiting us as well as three other  
locations, and essentially we understand that their goal was to get 
a current assessment of these sites and the options that are 
available so that they can present them to the team owners, or at 
least to the (expansion) committee,'' Groomes said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We felt the conversations were productive, at least in our  
view that Carson is a great location for this and we think that 
there are many possibilities that could be put together to make 
this a feasible deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Los Angeles Councilman Mark Ridley-Thomas said the same thing  
Wednesday about the Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	``With literally two weeks to go'' before the NFL's Sept. 15  
deadline, ``we remain committed to returning NFL football to Los 
Angeles in a new Coliseum,'' Ridley-Thomas said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that this can be accomplished in a way that is  
acceptable to the NFL, to all necessary governing bodies, to 
prospective owners and to Los Angeles football fans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ridley-Thomas hopes to convince the NFL of the feasibility of a  
new approach to providing money for the Coliseum remodeling and 
adjacent parking. The funds would come from taxes on revenue 
generated by a new team. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL has imposed a Sept. 15 deadline on Los Angeles for  
coming up with an acceptable proposal for the league's 32nd 
franchise. As that deadline approaches, it appears more likely that 
Houston instead will be promised a team. 
</P>
<P>
	Groomes said it seems impossible to predict what the 31 team  
owners might decide. 
</P>
<P>
	``We understand the position of Roger (Goodell), and for that  
matter, ... (NFL commissioner Paul) Tagliabue. It's hard for them 
to predict where 31 people are going to come from, especially this 
group of 31,'' Groomes said. 
</P>
<P>
	The league's expansion committee is scheduled to meet Sept. 9 in  
Washington, D.C., and representatives from Los Angeles and Houston 
are slated to meet with NFL officials in New York on Sept. 13. A 
full meeting of the league's team owners isn't scheduled until Oct. 
6 in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	Carson was one of three sites, along with the LA Coliseum and  
Houston, originally considered by the league for the expansion 
team. The NFL narrowed that list down to the Coliseum, then opened 
the door for other proposals again after talks with the Coliseum 
backers hit snags over what the league considered a lack of public 
funding and insufficient parking. 
</P>
<P>
	Groomes said Carson is by no means desperate to have an NFL  
stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't see ourselves as a desperate community trying to find  
a life raft in this NFL franchise. Frankly speaking, without 
suggesting that we're not interested, we can take it or leave it,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not interested in spinning wheels in this process or  
being used as leverage for something else.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 10:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Excerpts From Bradley Film </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Excerpts from ``Old Young Man,'' a 1968 documentary on Bill  
Bradley produced for the United States Information Agency: 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a fantastic sensation, you know, when you work on  
something for hours, and maybe weeks even, and nothing goes. Then 
on about the ten thousandth time, you finally do the shot right. 
And you know it's right because it feels right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Bradley, on basketball  

</P>
<P>
	``It's the nature of sport that it creates people like Bill  
Bradley who are famous far beyond reason, really. And he has got to 
live with this the rest of his life. He may become a public figure, 
but my point is that he already is one, and the sport made him 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--John McPhee, author of a magazine profile of Bradley in 1965  

</P>
<P>
	``He's sort of a loner, kind of. I don't know what he's done,  
you know, other than being a scholar and basketball star, but he 
also seems to have a concern about people. But he takes it so much 
to heart. I think that's half the reason he's so quiet. It's not a 
relaxed kind of quiet at all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Unidentified woman accompanying Bradley  

</P>
<P>
	``The essential component of the program is the street worker.  
Most important is his concern that something be done for the 
teenage kids in the ghetto. So what he does is, he tries to reach 
these kids, and in effect transform their lives by giving them the 
hope that college is possible, by giving them the confidence that 
is absent in so many of their lives simply because no one has ever 
put his hand on the kid's shoulder and told him he was with him all 
the way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Bradley, on his work with a youth outreach program in Harlem  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 16:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Saints' Williams Cleared To Play </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- New Orleans rookie running back Ricky  
Williams, sidelined with an ankle injury since the first preseason 
game, has been cleared to play in the season opener. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams, injured after just nine carries in the Saints first  
exhibition game of the year, was given the go-ahead to play in the 
Sept. 12 opener against the Carolina Panthers, Saints trainer Dean 
Kleinschmidt said. 
</P>
<P>
	A second MRI of Williams injury, a high ankle strain, cleared  
the former Heisman Trophy winner to return to the field. 
</P>
<P>
	``The repeat MRI on Ricky Williams showed exactly what we  
expected,'' Kleinschmidt said. ``It shows that the ankle is stable 
and that there is no widening of the ankle mortise joint and that 
it is in the process of healing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team expected Williams to return for the opener all along,  
and had repeatedly denied reports that he would miss the first two 
games of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams will sit out the final preseason game against the  
Tennessee Titans on Thursday night. He has not practiced or played 
since Aug. 13, but began limited drills on the injured ankle this 
week, under the supervision of Saints trainers. 
</P>
<P>
	There will be no problem putting the injury behind him, Williams  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not that big of a deal,'' Williams said Wednesday. ``You  
just go along, go along, start playing and you play. It's not like 
it's traumatized me or anything to not be ready. It's just a 
progression and when I'm ready, I'll be on the field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams said he had numerous injuries while playing in college  
at Texas, including a similar ankle sprain. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was worse, but it was on the other ankle,'' Williams said.  
</P>
<P>
	Although he won't have taken a hit in a month by the time he  
plays again, Williams doesn't anticipate any problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's only been a couple of weeks,'' he said. ``I don't think  
you lose it that fast.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 08:21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Apple Unveils 'Desktop Supercomputer' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Calling it ``the world's first desktop  
supercomputer,'' Apple Computer Inc.'s charismatic leader Steven 
Jobs unveiled his company's latest workstation, designed to further 
extend the company's technological and financial rebound. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the most powerful personal computer ever brought to  
market,'' Jobs, Apple's interim CEO, told more than 1,000 cheering 
spectators attending the Seybold publishing conference here 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Then he pulled a brown cloth cover off the sleek, glistening  
computer, and took a small bow. 
</P>
<P>
	The new computers, powered by chips made by Apple, Motorola Inc.  
and IBM, cost between $1,600 and $3,500 and mark Apple's continuing 
efforts to sell to business users such as architects, publishers 
and graphic designers. 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street investors appeared to signal their enthusiasm today  
for the new machine, pushing Apple's stock price up 3 percent, or 
$2.12 1/2 at $67.37 1/2, in early trading on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 
</P>
<P>
	The G4 chip incorporates a new execution unit named the Velocity  
Engine, which is the heart of a supercomputer miniaturized onto a 
sliver of silicon. 
</P>
<P>
	Jobs also unveiled a new 22-inch flat-panel display monitor,  
dubbed the Apple Cinema Display, which together with the top G4 
model will sell for $6,500 in October. The display monitor is twice 
as bright, twice as sharp and has three times the contrast of 
traditional monitors, Apple said. 
</P>
<P>
	Software developers on hand gushed over the new machine.  
</P>
<P>
	``The new G4 is an unbelievable machine for creating compelling  
content that adds life to the web,'' said Rob Burgess, CEO of 
Macromedia. 
</P>
<P>
	Adobe Systems CEO John Warnock said the G4 runs his company's  
image editing software Photoshop -- significantly faster than any 
other platform. 
</P>
<P>
	During the unveiling, Jobs held a head-to-head race against an  
Intel Pentium III system, rendering a scene with Buzz Lightyear 
from the movie ``Toy Story.'' Jobs claimed that the G4 was more 
than twice as fast as the Pentium machine, which was running at a 
speed of 600 Mhz. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel didn't let the thrown gauntlet go unchallenged.  
</P>
<P>
	At about the same time, at an Intel developers conference in  
Palm Springs, Intel CEO Craig Barrett announced that the 
``Coppermine'' Pentium III processor, an enhanced version of its 
high-end chip, will be released in October. It will operate at a 
speed of at least 700 Mhz -- more powerful, but not necessarily 
faster, than Apple's 500 Mhz G4. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 08:21:35 </DATE_TIME>
