<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Sues Disney for Portrayal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SELMA, Ala. (AP) -- A woman is seeking $8 million in damages over  
a Disney TV movie that she contends inaccurately portrays her as a 
``black Mammy'' during the civil rights era. 
</P>
<P>
	Amelia Boynton Robinson was heavily involved in the Selma civil  
rights movement during the 1960s and was an identified character in 
the movie ``Selma, Lord, Selma.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She was depicted as a stereotypical ``black Mammy'' whose main  
function was to make religious utterances and to participate in 
singing spirituals and protest songs, said Bruce Boynton, her son 
and an attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	``My mother's depiction in the movie was drastically wrong,''  
the son said. ``It doesn't bespeak the type of character my mother 
actually had at all -- not only had but continues to have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The movie, which aired in January, was based on a book by the  
same name. 
</P>
<P>
	A Disney executive, Jack Yellen, did not immediately return a  
telephone call. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 10:09:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Depardieu, Huppert: Enduring Icons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- It's been 25 years since Gerard Depardieu and  
Isabelle Huppert burst into prominence in a whimsical road movie 
about three scruffy hippies seeking sexual adventure. 
</P>
<P>
	In ``Les Valseuses'' (``Going Places''), Bertrand Blier's 1974  
cult hit, he was a long-haired, big-nosed unknown, and she was a 
waifish ingenue. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, at the height of their careers, Huppert and Depardieu are  
icons of French cinema who have fans throughout the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Depardieu, or ``Gege,'' the nickname by which he's known, has  
more than 100 films to his credit. He's whispered love sonnets in 
``Cyrano de Bergerac'' and hurled Gallic insults as the rotund 
Obelisk in the recent blockbuster ``Asterix and Obelix Versus 
Caesar.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the man who battled neglect and poverty and overcame a  
severe speech impediment to star in ``Green Card'' and ``The Return 
of Martin Guerre'' took on another challenge this year: He made his 
directing debut with ``Un Pont Entre Deux Rives'' (``A Bridge 
Between Two Banks''), a poignant story about a small-town cleaning 
woman who gets her emotional thrills from watching movies. 
</P>
<P>
	Depardieu co-directed his off-screen companion, Carole Bouquet,  
in what French critics deemed her best performance ever. 
</P>
<P>
	The 52-year-old actor also shined in the role of the husband she  
leaves -- a potbellied worker forced to spend weekdays away from 
home, laying pipes for the Tancarville bridge going up over the 
Seine near Le Havre in the early 1960s. 
</P>
<P>
	Some say Depardieu single-handedly carries the French cinema on  
his broad shoulders -- not only as its most prolific actor, but also 
as producer and promoter of young talent. 
</P>
<P>
	He recently helped establish ``Emergence,'' the French  
equivalent of Robert Redford's Sundance Institute. It raises funds 
to finance seminars for budding directors. 
</P>
<P>
	He also has offered his talent -- at minimal cost -- to any young  
director with a good idea. Which is why his name figured among the 
production credits of ``Mirka,'' a low-budget Algerian film 
released last summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Actor and Business Man: Depardieu and Co.,'' headlined the  
weekly news magazine, Le Point, in a cover story earlier this year 
that spoke about his oil venture in Cuba and sales of his Chateau 
de Tigne wine to Eastern Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Depardieu has said he doesn't like being labeled  
``businessman,'' but wants control of his affairs so he can live 
his life the way he sees fit. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have the soul of a businessman,'' he says. ``I don't  
even have a secretary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His failed oil venture cost him more than $1 million, and he  
called his winery ``practically nonprofit.'' But he added that 
recent negotiations were on to sell nearly a third of the chateau's 
yearly output of 350,000 bottles as kosher wine. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, he still manages to dominate stage and screen. This  
winter he played a 16th-century emperor in a four-month stage 
production and finished filming a miniseries on Balzac to air on 
French TV in the fall. 
</P>
<P>
	This summer he's been filming ``Vatel,'' a period movie in  
English about the Duke of Conde's valet. 
</P>
<P>
	Huppert also cuts a unique figure among French movie stars.  
</P>
<P>
	She may be no match for Catherine Deneuve's classic blond beauty  
or Isabelle Adjani's beguiling, dark exoticism. But with her face 
of a million facets, she is widely regarded as France's most 
versatile actress. 
</P>
<P>
	Which is why, at 44, she may be the nation's most enduring  
female star, a box-office heavyweight who makes almost as many 
films a year as the prolific Depardieu. 
</P>
<P>
	In a career that spans nearly three decades, she has worked with  
every major French director: Jean-Luc Godard, Claude Chabrol, 
Bertrand Blier and Bertrand Tavernier among them. 
</P>
<P>
	Huppert has made four movies in the past year, including  
``L'Ecole de la Chair'' (``The School of Flesh''), the tale of a 
fortysomething fashion designer who falls for a bisexual gigolo 20 
years her junior. 
</P>
<P>
	The film fared better in the United States than in France, but  
still earned Huppert a nomination for best actress at this year's 
Cesar ceremonies -- the French equivalent of the Academy Awards -- 
over which she presided. 
</P>
<P>
	``It'll touch you or it won't,'' she said during a recent  
interview at her Left Bank apartment. ``You'll either love it or 
hate it, but it won't leave you indifferent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Director Benoit Jacquot said he wanted Huppert, and only Huppert  
-- with her signature impassivity -- to play the role of Dominique, 
an established divorcee who buys sex and finds love in the arms of 
a low-life Arab prostitute. 
</P>
<P>
	```It's love at first sight,'' Huppert said. ``Dominique is  
wildly attracted to this man, and experiences intense physical 
passion she can't explain. When things get too painful, she pulls 
out. She's a survivor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Huppert has been a mainstay of French cinema since her debut 25  
years ago as the teen-age ingenue deflowered by Depardieu and 
Patrick Dewaere in ``Going Places.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, she has incarnated 53 roles, including: a  
19th-century tubercular courtesan, a wartime abortionist and a 
simple postal worker-turned-killer in ``La Ceremonie'' (``Judgment 
in Stone''). 
</P>
<P>
	That performance won her a Cesar for best actress in 1995 and  
had critics comparing her relationship with Chabrol to that between 
Grace Kelly and Alfred Hitchcock. 
</P>
<P>
	Colleagues say Huppert chooses her films carefully, on the basis  
of a director's style and themes that matter to her. 
</P>
<P>
	In the early 1990s, for example, she sought out independent  
filmmaker Hal Hartley and asked him for a part. He cast her as a 
pornography-writing ex-nun in his 1993 ``Amateur.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Huppert has evolved over the years, the adolescent curves  
melting away to reveal a girl-next-door appeal enhanced by her 
delicate auburn looks and diaphanous skin. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike many French actresses of her generation, she also has  
triumphed on stage: as Joan of Arc at the Bastille-Opera in a 
three-hour, one-woman show directed by U.S. director Robert Wilson, 
and in London, as Mary Stuart -- speaking English. 
</P>
<P>
	Another English-language role, in Michael Cimino's 1979  
big-budget ``Heaven's Gate,'' could have been a ticket to 
Hollywood, but it flopped, and Huppert hasn't worked there since. 
</P>
<P>
	She is an intensely private person. Lush greenery on her  
balconies keeps prying photographers at bay, and she has 
successfully sued more than one celebrity glossy for invasion of 
privacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Playing with her child at a nearby public park, the waifish  
Huppert -- in dusty black pants and no makeup -- looks more like a 
baby-sitter than a movie star who regularly earns superlatives from 
France's notoriously harsh critics. 
</P>
<P>
	In the daily Liberation, Gerard Lefort deemed her performance in  
``The School of Flesh'' ``grandiose,'' saying it destroyed any 
notion that Huppert might be ``over the hill.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 08:36:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Kosovo Kids Go Back to School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Thousands of Kosovo students  
returned to school today, the first time pupils in the province 
have been able to attend class since NATO launched its war against 
Yugoslavia five months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Most schools in Pristina, the provincial capital, were cleaned  
up and ready for students who will spend the next month in makeup 
classes because school was suspended after NATO's bombing campaign 
began March 24. 
</P>
<P>
	Some rural schools have been shut down since February 1998, when  
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic launched a bloody crackdown 
on ethnic Albanian separatists. The crackdown ended in June when 
Milosevic accepted a peace plan that included 40,000 NATO-led 
troops. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Hasan Pristina school in the provincial capital, excited  
11-year-olds raced up to their classrooms on the third floor, 
marveling at the absence of a grill that formerly separated them 
from Serb children, most of whom have fled the province. 
</P>
<P>
	``I came up here yesterday just to see where my class would be,  
and I couldn't believe it,'' said Arjjir Rexha as he waited for his 
teacher. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. officials were uncertain how many students -- ethnic  
Albanians and Serbs -- would show up for class. The United Nations 
estimates nearly half of Kosovo's schools were damaged or destroyed 
in 18 months of ethnic warfare. 
</P>
<P>
	Most Albanian children have not officially attended school since  
1989, when Milosevic revoked the province's autonomy. 
</P>
<P>
	Many ethnic Albanians responded by establishing their own,  
unofficial schools, financed by contributions from Albanians 
abroad. Most Serb pupils fled Kosovo with their parents to escape 
reprisal attacks by ethnic Albanians after Yugoslav troops withdrew 
from the province under the peace agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	In areas where Serb children remain, they will share school  
buildings with the Albanians. To avoid trouble, one group will 
attend classes in the morning and the other in the afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. officials hope the resumption of classes will represent an  
important step toward rebuilding the province after years of ethnic 
unrest and war. 
</P>
<P>
	The next major step will come Sept. 19, when the Kosovo  
Liberation Army is to disarm and disband under a June agreement 
with NATO. On Tuesday, the NATO commander in Kosovo, Lt. Gen. Mike 
Jackson, met with KLA leader Hashim Thaci to discuss the rebel 
commitment. 
</P>
<P>
	The meeting took place behind closed doors. But sources close to  
Thaci who spoke on condition of anonymity said the two also 
discussed terms to end an eight-day stalemate between local ethnic 
Albanians and Russian soldiers in the southern city of Orahovac. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of ethnic Albanians have been blocking roads to the  
town for more than a week, refusing to allow Russian peacekeepers 
to enter. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the unrecognized Kosovo parliament held its first  
session since the end of the Kosovo fighting. The parliament was 
elected in March 1998 in balloting which was not recognized by the 
Serb-led Yugoslav government. 
</P>
<P>
	Moderate Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova, whose Democratic League  
of Kosovo dominates the assembly, said parliament must cooperate 
with U.N. and NATO-led forces to draft new laws to replace the 
Serbian legal code. 
</P>
<P>
	The parliament's influence within the Kosovo Albanian community  
has been eclipsed by the Kosovo Liberation Army which did not take 
part in the 1998 balloting. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Tuesday, the top U.N. official in Kosovo, Bernard Kouchner,  
swore in seven new judges and two prosecutors in the divided 
northern town of Kosovska Mitrovica. 
</P>
<P>
	The judges will be part of a new legal system being set up by  
the United Nations to replace the Serbian law that previously ruled 
the province. 
</P>
<P>
	International officials are eager to have a judiciary system up  
and running in the province. The peacekeepers, who started arriving 
on June 12, have not been able to prevent revenge attacks and 
criminal acts from taking place. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 08:36:59 </DATE_TIME>
