<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Georgian President Visiting Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SKANEATELES, N.Y. (AP) -- The president of the republic of  
Georgia, Eduard Shevardnadze, will meet with President Clinton in 
Washington this month, the White House announced Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Shevardnadze will also speak before the United Nations in New  
York before traveling to Washington for the Sept. 23 White House 
meeting, said a statement from White House spokesman Joe Lockhart. 
The statement was issued from the Clinton family vacation spot in 
upstate New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``The United States strongly supports the sovereignty, stability  
and territorial integrity of Georgia,'' the statement said. It went 
on to praise Shevardnadze's role ``in promoting prosperity and 
democratic development for all the people of Georgia.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two leaders will discuss current U.S.-Georgia cooperation,  
and ways to broaden the relationship, the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgia is a former Soviet republic, and its leader was once a  
prominent Soviet politician. 
</P>
<P>
	Shevardnadze has remained in power in Georgia through years of  
political upheaval, including an assassination attempt last year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
