<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soybeans Soar on Crop Worries / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean futures raced to their highest level in  
three weeks Wednesday in a second straight day of strong advances 
reflecting crop concerns. Grain futures also were mostly higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean prices pushed higher as crop time nears with both the  
size and condition in question. The U.S. Department of Agriculture 
said earlier this week that less than half the crop was in good to 
excellent condition -- way under last year's rating at the same 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasts for dry, warmer weather through most of the soybean  
belt this week also boosted prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans helped carry corn prices higher for the third straight  
day. Investors also reacted to reports of low yields and light test 
weights in the eastern corn belt. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat prices also were buoyed by the soybean market activity.  
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 1 1/2 cents to $2.83 3/4 a bushel;  
December corn rose 1 3/4 cents to $2.21 a bushel; December oats were 
unchanged at $1.16 1/2 a bushel; November soybeans rose 5 3/4 cents to 
$4.88 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures were mixed and pork futures advanced on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle fell .18 cent to 66.37 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle rose .17 cent to 79.02 cents a pound; October 
lean hogs rose 1.07 cents to 46.87 a pound; February pork bellies 
rose .85 cent to 59.60 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
