<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 12:40:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Liberty's Rookies Show the Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Tamika Whitmore and Crystal Robinson weren't in  
the league when the New York Liberty played in the inaugural 1997 
WNBA championship against the Houston Comets. 
</P>
<P>
	They didn't experience the disappointment of a 14-point loss  
when the Comets held New York to 38 percent shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the rookies are reveling in better moments, like the  
69-54 victory over the Charlotte Sting on Monday that sent the 
Liberty to the WNBA Finals against the Comets for the second time 
in three seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Houston, the two-time defending champions, advanced with a 72-62  
victory over Los Angeles in the Western Conference final. 
</P>
<P>
	The best-of-3 championship series begins Thursday night at  
Madison Square Garden. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitmore, a 6-foot-2 center who led the nation in scoring her  
senior year at Memphis, scored 10 points off the bench against the 
Sting. 
</P>
<P>
	``For me, as a rookie, it feels great,'' Whitmore said. ``Not  
many rookies get this opportunity in their first year in the 
league. It just shows how much charisma and talent we have on this 
New York team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson is a rookie only in the sense that she's a newcomer to  
the league. The 5-foot-10 forward led the now-defunct ABL in 
3-point shooting (.466) and made 4-of-5 from behind the arc to 
finish with 18 points against the Sting. 
</P>
<P>
	``We fought hard this season and had a lot of ups and downs,''  
Robinson said. ``A lot of people doubted us. We didn't have any 
superstars, but we are a good team. '' 
</P>
<P>
	When Rebecca Lobo went down with a season-ending knee injury 42  
seconds into the opener, the Liberty's future looked bleak. But Sue 
Wicks and Whitmore went to work on the boards and Robinson, the 
Liberty's first-round pick, shot .437 from behind the arc. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't say enough about Crystal Robinson,'' New York coach  
Richie Adubato said. ``They double-team her and triple-team her and 
(Charlotte) even threw a little diamond-and-one on her. But she 
continues to show what a marvelous shooter she is. She has that 
quick release.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Liberty, a strong defensive team, is playing especially well  
on offense. 
</P>
<P>
	New York shot a WNBA playoff-record 55 percent in Game 2 against  
the Sting and followed with a 54-percent performance on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Liberty got a big boost from their reserves, who outscored  
the Sting's bench 20-0. Sophia Witherspoon matched Whitmore's 10 
points off the bench. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sophia has been instant offense for us,'' Adubato said. ``When  
she comes in, we try to run because she has a tremendous ability to 
get to the basket in transition. Both of them came in and obviously 
8-for-12 shooting is pretty good off the bench.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Whitmore has contributed consistently in the last two weeks  
after recovering from a midseason ankle sprain. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now that Tamika is back, we know she is a terrific offensive  
player,'' Adubato said. ``She can play inside or out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New York will have to contain Cynthia Cooper, who is averaging  
17 points in the playoffs, five points off her average. 
</P>
<P>
	Cooper is still grieving the loss of teammate Kim Perrot, who  
died of lung and brain cancer Aug. 19. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even at the beginning of the season, we wanted to dedicate our  
season to Kim,'' Sheryl Swoopes said. ``There was no way they were 
going to come out and beat us on our own court.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both teams are winners at home. The Comets went 15-1 at the  
Compaq Center during the regular season. The Liberty had a 12-4 
record at home. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know it's going to be a dogfight,'' Witherspoon said.  
``Because, hey, everybody wants that ring and everybody wants that 
trophy.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
