<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Amtrak Delays High-Speed Train </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Premature wheel wear discovered during testing  
of Amtrak's new high-speed Acela train prompted the railroad to 
announce Wednesday it is delaying the launch of the service until 
next spring at the earliest. 
</P>
<P>
	While an embarrassment for the railroad, Amtrak President George  
Warrington offered one consolation for Northeast passengers 
expecting the 150 mph trains to start running later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Warrington said that a project to straighten curves and run  
electricity along tracks between Boston and New York was on 
schedule, which will allow Amtrak to cut travel times by up to one 
hour, 40 minutes using its existing locomotives. 
</P>
<P>
	Trip times should also improve slightly on New  
York-to-Washington runs, which will compose the second half of the 
Acela high-speed route. 
</P>
<P>
	``The infrastructure and electrification program will enable us  
to take advantage of those investments in advance of introducing 
the actual (high-speed) train sets themselves in the spring,'' 
Warrington told reporters in a telephone news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Acela has been hampered in testing by ``wheel hunting''  
problems. At speeds of 130 mph to 145 mph, the wheels began shaking 
from side to side. 
</P>
<P>
	Jacques Lapare, the North American head of the Canadian firm  
Bombardier Inc., which is building the train with Paris-based 
Alstom, said engineers found ``excessive wheel wear'' on passenger 
coaches in the two eight-car test trains. 
</P>
<P>
	``This delay is unfortunate but not unusual when new technology,  
although proven, is being introduced in a new environment,'' Lapare 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lapare said engineers are trying to build a smaller suspension  
to help remove ``some of the rigidity of the truck ... to make the 
going through curves a little bit easier.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Warrington also defended the delayed introduction.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is about taking the time to make this train right,'' he  
said. ``It is as a practical matter not a toughest choice because 
we have no interest in cutting corners and accepting a train that 
does not meet performance standards or the standards of excellence 
that Amtrak has set.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Acela is the cornerstone of a $2 billion plan to revive Amtrak  
and promote high-speed rail as one means of addressing highway and 
air traffic congestion in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The railroad is spending $710 million to buy 20 eight-car train  
sets from Bombardier-Alstom. The trains were set to be fully 
operational by the fall of 2000, allowing Amtrak cut the trip 
between New York and Boston from 4 1/2 hours to just over three hours, 
and the trip from New York to Washington from nearly three hours to 
2 1/2 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Warrington acknowledged Wednesday that the company will see  
revenues drop because of the delay. 
</P>
<P>
	``That slippage is one-time, and it is short-term, and it is in  
no way consequential to our long-term revenue or our absolute 
commitment to operational self-sufficiency by 2003,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
