<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls Despite Wall St. Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar slipped further against most major  
currencies Wednesday, approaching its lowest level of the year 
against the Japanese yen, as it failed to get a lift from a rebound 
in U.S. stock markets. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 109.05  
Japanese yen, down from 109.59. It last was this low on Jan. 11, 
when it closed at 108.22 yen. The dollar also lost ground to the 
euro, which rose to $1.0594 from $1.0578 late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The persistent weakness in the dollar against the yen is  
fostering weakness in the U.S. currency's trading against other 
major denominations, said Robert Lynch, currency strategist at 
Paribas in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Lynch said the dollar's rapid approach of its 1999 low ``raises  
the threat of intervention by the Bank of Japan. It's becoming a 
bit more critical at these levels,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders have been predicting for days that the Japanese  
government will intervene to prop up the dollar against the yen. 
Such a policy would prevent the yen from getting too strong, which 
would lower Japan's export profits and hurt the country's resurging 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	A weak dollar would make U.S. exporters stronger competitors in  
world markets, but it also would raise the price of imported goods 
and make overseas travel more costly for Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.5127 Swiss francs, down from  
1.5136, and 1.4896 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4925. 
</P>
<P>
	But the British pound fell to $1.6062 from $1.6064.  
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Wednesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8453 German 
marks, down from 1.8507; 6.1889 French francs, down from 6.2071; 
and 1,828 Italian lire, down from 1,832. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
