<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cardinals To Call Up Right-Hander </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- The St. Louis Cardinals' second group of  
minor-league callups will include pitcher Chad Hutchinson, a 
second-round draft pick last year who made his Triple-A debut 
Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Hutchinson, a right-hander, struck out 11 and walked five in six  
innings for Triple-A Memphis and got a victory at Vancouver. He 
will join the team after the Pacific Coast League season ends Sept. 
6 to work with pitching coach Dave Duncan and get some major league 
experience. 
</P>
<P>
	Cardinals manager Tony La Russa doesn't plan to give Hutchinson  
any starts, however. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dunc's anxious to get a look at him,'' La Russa said. ``He's  
had some promising outings, but there's indications he still has 
some work to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duncan said Hutchinson, who was 7-11 with an 4.72 ERA at  
Double-A Arkansas, has had a dominating breaking ball all season 
but has struggled to control his fastball. In 141 innings at 
Arkansas, he struck out 150 and walked 85. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that's something they'd like to see improved upon,''  
Duncan said. ``All in all, I think he's had a decent year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hutchinson, 22, was a two-year starter at quarterback at  
Stanford before deciding to concentrate on baseball. He signed a 
$3.5 million deal last June that included a $2.4 million signing 
bonus and $1.1 million for a four-year guaranteed contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Right-hander Alan Benes, out more than two years with shoulder  
woes, will also join the bullpen after making one more rehab start 
at Memphis. On Monday night, Benes lasted three innings and gave up 
one run and walked three while striking out two. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the Cardinals called up first baseman Eduardo Perez,  
catcher Marcus Jensen and right-hander Mark Thompson. None of the 
players were expected to report until after Wednesday's game 
against the Florida Marlins had begun. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cardinals also plan to recall right-hander Jose Jimenez, who  
had a no-hitter and two-hitter against Arizona's Randy Johnson but 
was 5-12 with a 5.81 ERA overall. Jimenez, who was demoted Aug. 18, 
was 1-1 with a 2.92 ERA at Memphis. 
</P>
<P>
	St. Louis also plans to call up infielders Placido Polanco and  
Luis Ordaz. 
</P>
<P>
	In another move Wednesday, right-handed reliever Curtis King was  
recalled from a rehab assignment and optioned to Memphis. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
