<HEADLINE> Fading Blue Jays Lose Hamilton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- The Toronto Blue Jays playoff hopes are fading  
and the news got worse as starting pitcher Joey Hamilton is out for 
the season with a sore shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton, who has pitched with pain for most of the season, will  
see Dr. James Andrews in Birmingham, Alabama on Monday. Hamilton 
may undergo exploratory surgery next week. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a long struggle throughout the year,'' Hamilton  
said. ``I've definitely strengthened my tolerance for pain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After being acquired from San Diego in an offseason trade,  
Hamilton signed a three-year, $18 million deal. He started the 
season with muscle impingement and after two bad starts was placed 
on the disabled list for six weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	After allowing five runs in two-plus innings on Tuesday,  
Hamilton said his shoulder felt worse. He is 7-8 with a 6.52 ERA. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blue Jays are also without starter Chris Carpenter, who will  
miss at least one start with elbow problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Toronto manager Jim Fregosi and General Manager Gord  
Ash held a meeting with the player's before Toronto's game against 
Minnesota Wednesday night. The Blue Jays entered the day five games 
back in the AL wild card race. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just didn't want anybody to think that Gord and myself have  
given up,'' Fregosi said. ``I don't want anybody feeling sorry for 
themselves. Whatever games we have left I expect them to do their 
job.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
