<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> German Utility Firms Discuss Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MUNICH, Germany (AP) -- The chairmen of German utility giants  
Viag AG and Veba AG discussed a possible merger Wednesday with 
Bavarian Gov. Edmond Stoiber, whose state is a major shareholder in 
Viag, but no decision was reached, participants said. 
</P>
<P>
	Veba chairman Ulrich Hartmann said the talks were ``constructive  
and (had) a good atmosphere,'' but that more talks were necessary 
given the scale of the merger under discussion. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, a Viag spokeswoman confirmed that the cornerstone of a  
merger had been worked out, but said many questions remained, 
including possible antitrust concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Cartel Office chief Dieter Wolf told reporters Wednesday  
that the two groups had approached his office to gauge how the 
merger would be received, but that nothing had been formally 
submitted. 
</P>
<P>
	He said if approval were sought, his office would focus on the  
energy and chemicals divisions of the two groups and any potential 
monopoly operations. Both are also involved in mobile telephones, 
but Wolf said that would not necessarily be a problem. 
</P>
<P>
	The state of Bavaria, which owns 25.1 percent of Viag, must also  
approve the proposal. The Bavarian government has stated that it 
intends to sell its stake by 2003, but also wants to protect the 
20,000 jobs Viag has in Bavaria. 
</P>
<P>
	Veba and Viag are the second- and third-largest German energy  
companies, respectively, in sales terms. Combined, they move into 
the top spot in the country, with combined sales of $10.9 billion 
in 1998, but still trail Electricite de France, which holds the No. 
1 spot in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	The French utility, which has used its protected home market as  
a launching pad for expansion beyond its borders, is aggressively 
bidding for a 25 percent stake in Germany's fourth-largest power 
producer Energie Baden-Wuerttemberg AG. 
</P>
<P>
	Electricite de France's looming presence is seen as one of the  
drivers for regional industry consolidation, and the German 
government seems to be pushing for German energy companies to 
become major European players. 
</P>
<P>
	A Veba-Viag ``merger doesn't automatically make them a huge  
international player,'' said Simon Allen, a European utilities 
analyst at PricewaterhouseCoopers. But a linkup does give the 
companies leverage and breathing space to position themselves for 
the future. 
</P>
<P>
	``EdF is still seen as the big potential threat,'' said Nicola  
Mann, a utilities analyst at Merrill Lynch. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
