<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Machinists Vote on Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Thousands of Machinists union members who work  
for The Boeing Co. weighed in today on a new three-year contract 
that union leaders called the best in the business. 
</P>
<P>
	The current contract, affecting 44,000 members of the  
International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers, was 
set to expire at 12:01 a.m. tomorrow. The Machinists have struck 
over two of the last three contracts, most recently for 69 days in 
1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The pact was not exactly what the union wanted -- dissident  
members made sure their co-workers were aware of its flaws -- but 
many interviewed on their way to union-hall polls appeared ready to 
accept it as the best they were likely to get. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a small percentage that plans to vote no but I can't  
really understand why. I think they just wanted to be militant,'' 
said Mark Dodds, 42, a 16-year Boeing worker who is a painter in 
the company's Auburn plant. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is really nothing worth going out on strike over,''  
Dodds said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been here 25 years and I've seen three strikes and this  
is one of the best contracts I've seen,'' said Larry Shively, who 
works for Boeing in Wichita, Kan. 
</P>
<P>
	The opposition to the agreement focused on retirement benefits  
and job security. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing offered a 25 percent increase in pensions, to $50 a month  
per year of service -- well below the 300 percent increase sought by 
the union. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract offer also guaranteed ``no layoffs as the direct  
result of subcontracting or offloading,'' but dissidents noted 
other language exempted ``commercial airplane strategic work 
placement requirements.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leadership at the company and the union said the exemption  
concerns work allocated to foreign workers as a condition of 
winning aircraft orders. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a good contract and the members are going to buy it,''  
predicted Bill Johnson, president of the union's Seattle-based 
District Lodge 751. 
</P>
<P>
	One in five Boeing workers is a Machinist -- 44,000 out of  
210,000 worldwide. Boeing, the nation's No. 1 exporter, plans to 
deliver a record 620 commercial planes this year, but a fierce 
rivalry with the European consortium Airbus Industrie has prompted 
an intensive effort to streamline operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The pressure to keep producing helped bring negotiators  
together. The company dropped its demands for a seven-day work week 
and more worker contributions to health-insurance premiums. It 
offered two annual wage increases of 4 percent and a third-year 3 
percent raise, as well as a 10 percent signing bonus worth $4,400 
to the average machinists. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll say it again: That's the best contract in aerospace,  
period. By far. Talk to anyone around the country,'' Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing ran double full-page ads this week -- outlining contract  
basics and urging union members to vote -- in newspapers serving 
cities with substantial Boeing work forces, including Seattle, 
Spokane, Everett, Tacoma, Bellevue and Kent in Washington; 
Portland, Ore.; and Wichita, Kan. The company also ran radio and TV 
ads. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just not taking this for granted,'' said Boeing chairman  
and CEO Phil Condit, who stepped in personally to end a prickly 
bargaining stalemate last weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract ``offers unprecedented job security, the best wages  
and retirement plan in the industry, and world-class benefits. It's 
the right thing for employees and the company,'' Condit said. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 10:09:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> George Buck: Celebrating Jazz </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- George Buck began collecting jazz records in  
high school. Now his collection fills two warehouses and nine 
record labels. 
</P>
<P>
	And those are just the records he has for sale.  
</P>
<P>
	Buck produced his first jazz record on Aug. 16, 1949, during  
summer break from college. The Jazzology label he created then is 
still going strong, with worldwide sales of traditional jazz -- the 
music Buck sometimes calls ``my jazz.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ten years ago, worried that a major label might buy the company  
after his death just for his Al Hirt and Pete Fountain masters, he 
created a nonprofit foundation to keep it all going after he is 
gone. 
</P>
<P>
	The GHB Jazz Foundation usually releases 80 to 100 CDs a year.  
But last month, it had 50 new CDs to celebrate Buck's 50th 
anniversary in recording. Some were all new, others reissues and 
added new and additional tracks to old LPs that had been released 
on vinyl. 
</P>
<P>
	The musicians who recorded Buck's first album all are dead, but  
his current favorites played at his recent 50th anniversary party: 
Clive Wilson on trumpet, Tom Fischer on clarinet, Steve Pistorious 
on piano, Tom Bartlett on trombone, Hal Smith on drums and Tom 
Saunders on bass. 
</P>
<P>
	``In a way, he's like a patron of the arts,'' said Dan  
Morgenstern, director of the Institute of Jazz Studies at Rutgers 
University's Newark campus. The only way to keep such a deep and 
lavish catalog is to ignore the bottom line, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Or, as Buck sees it, ``The recording business is not a business  
-- not in jazz. You do it because you love the music.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buck's office overlooks the French Quarter Flea Market. His  
battered desk faces away from the window, toward row upon row of 
wooden box shelves filled with records and CDs. These are for mail 
order; another office sends CDs to the distributor. 
</P>
<P>
	The desk seems at least as old as his high-bodied typewriter  
with its stair-step keyboard. He has a brand-new computer but has 
not yet learned how to use it, though dictation and text-reading 
software have definite appeal for a man who knows the world through 
touch and hearing because of his failed eyesight. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't really think it could work, but my phone book made me  
a convert,'' he said. He pulls a slim black gizmo from a drawer to 
show it off. ``All I have to do is say the name and hold it up to 
the phone, and it dials the number.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buck's love of traditional jazz goes way back, to when he was  
about 15 and heard Muggsy Spanier on the radio. A year or two 
later, he found a single at his record store. He bought it, and was 
hooked. 
</P>
<P>
	This was the swing era. He bought some drums -- he still has the  
set, in the third-floor warehouse apartment where he also keeps 
most of his personal record collection -- but couldn't find anyone 
to play with in Elizabeth, N.J., where he lived. He did find one 
other fan, though, and they'd get together on weekends to listen to 
records and talk. 
</P>
<P>
	He decided while he was still at Lynchburg College in Virginia  
that he wanted to keep this music alive by recording it. So he 
cashed the war bonds he'd bought hawking newspapers as a kid in 
Washington, D.C., got together his favorite musicians -- clarinetist 
Tony Parenti, cornet player Wild Bill Davison, Jimmy Archey on 
trombone, Art Hodes on piano, Pops Foster on bass and Arthur 
Trappier on drums -- and rented a New York studio. 
</P>
<P>
	The record cost well over $1,000. He made little of it back.  
</P>
<P>
	``I had no idea what the market was for jazz,'' Buck said.  
</P>
<P>
	He figured the big record stores with a name for jazz would buy  
a total of 500 copies, and he could sell another 500 by mail. The 
big stores bought five to 15 each. 
</P>
<P>
	He still has some of the original two-record sets: a 10-inch set  
with one song on each side, and two 12-inch records -- RCA had 
introduced LPs only a year earlier -- with a total of nine songs. 
Each take went directly to vinyl. A 10-inch record held only three 
minutes per side. 
</P>
<P>
	``On the first day, everything ran too long. ... I said, `It's  
so good I'll put out 12-inch disks,' so they wouldn't have to do 
retakes,'' Buck said. 
</P>
<P>
	He never put out singles, only albums with heavy-duty covers and  
liner notes: ``I thought there should be written material with it. 
It should be educational,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, in 1952, he got a deal with a national distributor. The  
profits it yielded two years later paid for his next recording 
sessions. But he couldn't turn those sessions into records until 
the early 1960s, when a radio station he had bought at bankruptcy 
sale in 1958 became the lead station in Columbia, S.C. As a top 40 
station, it got him back into the record business. 
</P>
<P>
	His earlier contracts with distributors had been so disastrous  
that he decided to stick entirely to mail order. He now has one 
distributor contract, and has added some of his lines, such as 
modern jazz, to make the ensemble more attractive to distributors. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1960s, Buck purchased the Creole label. Like many other  
independent labels, it had been forced out of business by bootleg 
companies that sold their music for much less. 
</P>
<P>
	Radio, though, has remained in his blood. He now owns a  
half-dozen stations, and broadcasts a jazz show each Sunday. The 
money he makes from radio pays for his records and the jazz history 
books that the GHB Jazz Foundation also publishes. 
</P>
<P>
	Morgenstern has a hard time singling out one or two of the  
company's most important achievements. There is the almost 
unheard-of longevity and the fact that Buck keeps everything in the 
catalog instead eliminating poor sellers. Then there's his issues 
of the previously unreleased Eddie Condon Town Hall concerts from 
the 1940s, and the transcriptions -- jam sessions recorded for radio 
use, but available only on bootleg albums before Buck bought World 
Transcriptions. 
</P>
<P>
	Buck figures he has about 2,000 titles available across his nine  
labels. And he's still recording more. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you have that much material, not all of it is immortal  
music,'' Morgenstern said. ``But a goodly percentage of it is. And 
all of it is worthwhile.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The GHB Jazz Foundation's nine record labels and a few  
representative musicians: 
</P>
<P>
	-- JAZZOLOGY RECORDS: Chicago style traditional jazz.  
</P>
<P>
	Artists include: Wild Bill Davison, Pud Brown, Marty Grosz,  
Lawson-Haggart Jazz Band, Tim Laughlin, Pete Fountain, Bob Wilber, 
Doc Cheatham, Eddie Condon Town Hall Concerts. 
</P>
<P>
	-- GHB RECORDS: New Orleans style jazz.  
</P>
<P>
	Artists include: George Lewis, John Handy, Turk Murphy, Lu  
Watters, Basin Street Six, Louis Nelson, Claude Luter, Kid Thomas, 
Sammy Rimmington, Pete Fountain, Percy Humphery. 
</P>
<P>
	-- AMERICAN MUSIC RECORDS: Pioneers of New Orleans jazz.  
</P>
<P>
	Artists include: Bunk Johnson, George Lewis, Jim Robinson, Kid  
Ory, Baby Dodds, Leadbelly, Raymond Burke, Kid Thomas, Kid Howard, 
Alvin Alcorn, Punch Miller, Kid Sheik, Billie &AMP; De De Pierce. 
</P>
<P>
	-- BLACK SWAN RECORDS: Reissue of Paramount blues and jazz  
recordings of the 1920's. Black Swan was the first black-owned 
record label. It later became a subsidiary of Parmount, which GHB 
bought in 1972. 
</P>
<P>
	Artists include: Ma Rainey, Charley Patton, Paramount Piano  
Blues. 
</P>
<P>
	-- SOLO ART RECORDS: Piano jazz, including ragtime, barrelhouse,  
stride, boogie woogie and seven other styles, played by early and 
contemporary musicians. 
</P>
<P>
	Artists include: Jimmy Yancey, Lucky Roberts, Jelly Roll Morton,  
Don Ewell, Wally Rose, Joe Turner, Max Morath, Butch Thompson, 
David Thomas Roberts, Marin Litton, David Paquette. 
</P>
<P>
	-- AUDIOPHILE RECORDS: Vocalists.  
</P>
<P>
	Artists include: Lee Wiley, Helen Forrest, Dick Haymes, Bobby  
Troup, Claire Austin, Margaret Whiting, Sandra King, Dolly Dawn, 
Ronny White, Maxine Sullivan, Chris Connor, Dorothy Donegan. 
</P>
<P>
	-- CIRCLE RECORDS: Big bands, both from the swing era and  
contemporary groups. 
</P>
<P>
	Artists include: Bob Crosby, Red Norvo, Harry James, Jimmie  
Lunceford, John Kirby, Charlie Spivak, Claude Thornhill, Dorsey 
Brothers, Jimmy Dorsey, Hal Kemp, Glen Gray, Frankie Carle, Louis 
Jordan, Count Basie, Les Brown, Woody Herman, Duke Ellington. 
</P>
<P>
	-- SOUTHLAND RECORDS: Blues, both rural and urban.  
</P>
<P>
	Artists include: Sunnyland Slim, Big Bill Broonzy, Lorenzo  
Holden, Eddie ``Cleanhead'' Vinson, Montana Taylor, Sister Rosetta 
Tharpe, Jimmy Ballero, Big Miller, Little Brother Montgomery. 
</P>
<P>
	-- PROGRESSIVE RECORDS: Modern jazz.  
</P>
<P>
	Artists include: Ben Webster, Derek Smit, Lee Konitz, Hank  
Jones, Buddy DeFranco, Milt Buckner, Buddy Tate, Arnett Cobb, Hal 
Stein, Ronny White, Milt Hinton, Harry Allen, Keith Ingham. 
  	   	
