<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 11:10:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Are Faster Lanes an Illusion? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The urge to change lanes while driving may be caused by an  
optical illusion that convinces people the cars in the other lane 
are going faster, according to a study. 
</P>
<P>
	The basic problem is that cars spread out when they're going  
quickly and bunch up when they slow down, said Dr. Donald 
Redelmeier, a professor of medicine at the University of Toronto. 
So when you pass a bunch of slower cars in the other lane, it 
happens fairly quickly. But if you are passed by the same cars 
while your lane slows temporarily, they go by one by one. 
</P>
<P>
	That leads to the illusion that the other lane is moving faster.  
</P>
<P>
	Redelmeier's advice: ``Resist small temptations to change  
lanes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Thursday's issue of the journal Nature, Redelmeier and a  
Stanford University statistician reported the results of computer 
simulations of traffic. 
</P>
<P>
	They showed that a driver can spend more time being overtaken by  
cars in the other lane than in passing them, even though both lanes 
travel at the same average speed. 
</P>
<P>
	``So you're going to have many more moments of frustration to  
balance the relatively few moments of pleasure,'' Redelmeier said. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers also showed 120 driving students a videotape of  
an adjacent lane of real traffic, depicting a side view from the 
back seat of a car. Seventy percent believed the traffic they saw 
was going faster than the car with the camera, when in fact it was 
going slightly slower on average. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Ervin, head of the engineering research division at the  
University of Michigan Transportation Research Institute, said the 
study offers ``a great hypothesis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It is an important and interesting issue that deserves more  
attention,'' especially with experiments that follow real drivers 
in their vehicles, he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 15:50:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Ex-Lions Coach Denied Compensation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Former Detroit Lions coach Wayne Fontes' claim  
that he suffered injuries while coaching wasn't credible, a 
magistrate wrote in denying Fontes worker disability compensation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fontes has failed to prove by a preponderance of the evidence  
that he has a disability, which arose out of, and in the course of, 
his employment with the Detroit Lions,'' Magistrate John Hurbis 
wrote in the decision dated Aug. 6 and released Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Fontes' lawyer, Gary Busch, said he would appeal the decision,  
calling Hurbis' ruling ``political.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It was like the magistrate was intent on denying benefits  
throughout the whole case,'' Busch said. ``Wayne isn't the most 
sympathetic plaintiff, but legally and factually, this should have 
been winnable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Messages left for the Detroit Lions seeking comment weren't  
returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Fontes, 60, spent 11 years with the Lions as a defensive  
backfield coach and eventually as coach, taking over from the fired 
Darryl Rogers late in the 1988 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Fontes, fired after the 1996 season by Lions owner William Clay  
Ford, last year filed a claim for disability benefits, saying he 
has been unable to resume coaching. 
</P>
<P>
	He insisted he was hurt first during a game in 1989 and again  
Nov. 12, 1995, during a game against Tampa Bay. While he was 
talking to his defensive squad on the sidelines, the Lions' offense 
turned the ball over, and the defense rushed onto the field, he 
said. Two players hit his shoulders, and a third knocked him to the 
ground, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He got up and continued coaching but was hurting badly by the  
time he got home, Fontes testified during a hearing in June on his 
compensation claim against the Lions. 
</P>
<P>
	Hurbis questioned Fontes' claims that he was injured while  
employed by the Lions and that those injuries were serious enough 
to prevent him from working again. 
</P>
<P>
	``This court finds as less than candid the testimony of the  
plaintiff and his witnesses,'' Hurbis wrote, suggesting Fontes' 
injuries could have stemmed from a 1990 automobile wreck, for which 
he was treated at Henry Ford Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Twice in the decision, Hurbis questioned how Fontes can continue  
playing golf despite his alleged suffering. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why would a man subject himself to the rigors of playing golf,  
when to endure pain thereafter, would require him to spend the next 
three days on the floor,'' Hurbis wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	During the June hearing, the Lions presented no witnesses and  
the only evidence the medical records of Fontes' treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	Busch said that since the Lions had no witnesses testify, the  
evidence should have weighed in Fontes' favor, ``but the magistrate 
said he didn't believe him anyway.'' 
</P>
<P>
	John Fontes, Wayne's brother and a former assistant coach for  
the Lions, testified that he had to help his brother get off the 
floor, where Fontes often rested after practices because of his 
injured back. 
</P>
<P>
	Hurbis found the need for such assistance ``inconceivable.''  
</P>
<P>
	``It seems incongruous to the court that the nature of the  
plaintiff's medical problems would render him unable to arise from 
the floor, considering the medical testimony of either doctor,'' he 
wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	At his June hearing, Fontes acknowledged that he swims and  
continues to play golf despite the injury. His attorney said Fontes 
often agrees to play in charity golf events. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's not playing good golf, he's out there trying to lend his  
name to a good cause,'' Busch said. ``There have been times he goes 
and plays two or three holes and then he can't play any more.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 22:50:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schools Work To Subdue Bullies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PEORIA, Ill. (AP) -- Brianna Thomas' mood shifts suddenly from  
bubbly to thoughtful as she recalls years of being teased about her 
weight. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I was little I would cry,'' said the 16-year-old, who is  
a junior at Woodruff High School. ``When I got older I'd say, 
'That's just you being ignorant' and walk away. But some kids in 
school tend to be pushed to the edge and they could snap.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As students across the country return to schools newly fortified  
with metal detectors, hall cameras and security guards, experts and 
students say the most important deterrent to violence is often 
overlooked: Teaching students to respect one another. 
</P>
<P>
	``Security issues are a necessary knee-jerk reaction, but what  
goes on every day in every school and every hallway is more 
important to the solution than locking up our schools,'' said 
George Batsche, a school psychology professor at the University of 
South Florida and co-director of the university's Institute for 
School Reform. 
</P>
<P>
	The two students who killed 15 people, including themselves, at  
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., reportedly felt 
alienated and harassed by other students. Students' alienation and 
anger also were cited in the wake of other school shootings, 
including those in Paducah, Ky.; Springfield, Ore. and Jonesboro, 
Ark. 
</P>
<P>
	``Each of the situations is so unique, but the anger that came  
out is pretty common and anger can come from a lot of things,'' 
said Susan Gorin, executive director of the National Association of 
School Psychologists. 
</P>
<P>
	Such issues are quite real to students such as Ashayla Scott, a  
16-year-old junior at Woodruff who says she's dreamed about 
classmates shooting up her school. 
</P>
<P>
	``You always think about those who are known to be bullies as  
being violent,'' she said. ``But now it's those who are quiet and 
always picked on that you have to wonder about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No matter what the cause, anger and alienation can be  
exacerbated by being bullied or taunted, psychologists say. In 
fact, those who are bullied, not the bullies, usually commit the 
most violent acts, Batsche said. 
</P>
<P>
	Psychologists say television violence, the Internet and easy  
access to weapons can make the consequences of bullying more dire 
than in the past, when many students suffered in silence. 
</P>
<P>
	The Internet allows kids to interact with others who share  
similar feelings, and can make them feel it's OK to seek revenge, 
Batsche said. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the past, there were individuals in schools considered  
weird or different, but they didn't have anybody to talk to; they 
had no peer group to activate them,'' he said. ``Now they find kids 
a thousand miles away who feel the same way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sometimes, victims of teasing do not act out in violence against  
other students, but inward, at themselves. On Wednesday, in 
southern Illinois, administrators at Freeburg High School said they 
were investigating whether the bullying of a freshman by fellow 
students led the 14-year-old to commit suicide last week. His 
father said the boy shot himself after four days of relentless 
tormenting. 
</P>
<P>
	How children deal with bullying depends on their personality,  
but experts say it's how schools deal with bullies and victims that 
will make a difference. 
</P>
<P>
	Batsche said schools should include social skills training in  
the curriculum and adopt a zero tolerance policy for bullying -- 
including intolerance for bullying by teachers and other adults. 
</P>
<P>
	When students returned to Taft Elementary School in Lockport,  
Ill. last week, they were told that bullying won't be tolerated and 
will be met with tougher penalties, Principal Trish Carlson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I truly believe harassing and bullying behavior is at the core  
of the violence,'' she said. ``Usually the reason kids get teased 
is because they look different or dress different or their 
mannerisms are different. We want kids to know that just because 
someone is different doesn't mean they're bad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But how can schools distinguish between normal teasing and  
harmful bullying? 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had parents say 'That's just normal boy behavior,'''  
Carlson said. ``But it's not normal boy behavior when someone's in 
tears on a daily basis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, school administrators say it's difficult to make  
anti-bullying efforts a priority because of pressure to implement 
more visible and immediate security measures. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel awareness programs impact more kids than putting in  
hundreds of thousands of dollars in cameras, but we have to do some 
security to satisfy parents and the community,'' said Galesburg, 
Ill. superintendent Ronald Cope. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 15:50:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
