<DOCNO> APW19990901.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 10:10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Show Obsesses on Collectibles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Who woulda thunk it: a letter from George  
Washington sharing air time with Speedy Gonzalez jelly glasses. A 
Beanie Baby collection competing for attention with a 19th-century 
Bible. A Civil War officer's pocket journal alongside, yes, a 
miniature model of the General Lee, the car from ``The Dukes of 
Hazzard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's all on your TV screen to see, and -- if you so desire in  
this age of boundless synergy -- on the Internet to buy and to have 
and to hold. 
</P>
<P>
	Eras, niches and tastes meld -- collapse, some might argue -- into  
one aggrandized, commodified pile of Very Significant Stuff in 
``Treasures in Your Home,'' a curious example of what might happen 
if someone put eBay, QVC and ``The Price Is Right'' into a blender 
and pressed frappe. 
</P>
<P>
	PAX TV's ``Treasures'' (7-8 p.m. Eastern and Pacific, 6-7 p.m.  
Central and Mountain, Monday-Friday), which made its debut last 
month, resembles in some ways PBS's ``The Antiques Road Show,'' 
another haven for garage-sale gurus. But ``Treasures'' takes the 
concept even further, offering a live, simultaneous auction online 
through its Web site, www.treasuresinyourhome.com, which also 
simulcasts the show. 
</P>
<P>
	``Television's changing, and we're at the forefront of where  
television's migrating to,'' says PAX TV President Jeff Sagansky. 
``It's going to be this multimedia experience where you create 
something for TV, but it lives all day long in other forms.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The format is heavy on regular-guy participation -- average Joe  
meets Independent Appraiser to see what that old family Bible or 
mama's childhood doll is really worth: 
</P>
<P>
	--Ron has what he believes to be a Confederate Civil War compass.  
Does he? No! It's a replica made in the 1920s, probably in India. 
But it's still worth a C-note! 
</P>
<P>
	--Rachel thinks she has a World War I chocolate tin embossed with  
presidential profiles. Does she? Yes! More than $100! 
</P>
<P>
	--Edgar has restored an antique oil can for a locomotive and  
thinks it might have some value. Does it? Beautiful restoration 
job, says the appraiser, but not worth a lot of moola. 
</P>
<P>
	And if they want to put their item up for bids, it goes up on  
the Web site in an instant. Synergy! (An interesting note: Fewer 
people than you might think are willing to put their coveted stuff 
up, even if the chance of profit is good.) 
</P>
<P>
	On the surface, ``Treasures'' is cheerful and harmless, exuding  
middle-of-the-road bonhomie and trafficking in stuff you might see 
on walls and shelves at TGI Fridays or The Ground Round -- old 
advertising accouterments, antique lamps, books with very 
serious-looking bindings. 
</P>
<P>
	But look a little deeper. It's a bit disconcerting how each item  
is presented as a cultural fetish object. Sure, ``stuff'' is the 
show's stock-in-trade, but ``Treasures,'' a joint production of PAX 
TV and ChannelSpace Entertainment's Collectingchannel.com Web site, 
elevates collecting to an obsession. The consumptive message: 
Collect what you want, but for goodness' sake collect SOMETHING. 
</P>
<P>
	Viewers are invited on the live telecast to tell about ``a  
collectible that changed your life.'' A parade of stuff-bearing 
hopefuls wait with expectant faces as their goods are appraised. 
Host John Burke's booster-like enthusiasm, while charming, only 
accentuates this feeling. 
</P>
<P>
	``Is there one thing you've learned this week that you didn't  
know?'' he asks guest co-host Shelley Taylor Morgan of ``General 
Hospital.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes,'' replies Morgan. ``I want more stuff.'' (Morgan later  
reveals she collects man-in-the-moon items, and shows a video of 
some of the more than 1,500 in her home.) 
</P>
<P>
	Consider Frank Holsinger, a Union officer in the Civil War who  
faithfully kept his diary through Gettysburg, through Antietam, 
through a visit to President Lincoln in Washington. Today it's part 
of a show that also features an on-the-spot report from a Barbie 
40th-anniversary convention. And here's the great part: It's worth 
hundreds of dollars! 
</P>
<P>
	Another segment features a letter written by Anne Frank's  
father, Otto, a few weeks after he was freed from a concentration 
camp. Shortly afterward, the topic is a ``Star Wars'' poster -- 
rarity or reproduction? Not that there's anything wrong with 
pop-culture collectibles, but such juxtaposition risks trivializing 
the important and elevating the irrelevant. The chaff becomes the 
wheat, and the wheat is forgotten in the clutter. 
</P>
<P>
	But this isn't really the fault of the program, which is  
entertaining and informative. In today's marketplace, everything is 
a commodity. See it on TV, desire it and, now, bid for it online, 
all in just moments. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you look hard enough and long enough, you can find just  
about everything,'' independent appraiser Dave Maloney says on the 
show. 
</P>
<P>
	He may be right. But behind ``Treasures in Your Home'' lurks a  
question any collector will -- or should -- eventually face: 
Ultimately, is everything really worth finding? 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ...  
</P>
<P>
	MARLEY TRIBUTE: The late Bob Marley's music will be the subject  
of a special all-star tribute on TNT. Previous tributes to Burt 
Bacharach and Johnny Cash have been successes both critically and 
commercially for the network. Erykah Badu, Sheryl Crow, Lauryn 
Hill, Queen Latifah, Sarah McLachlan, Busta Rhymes and Seal have 
already agreed to join the Marley family for the special, which 
will be taped in Jamaica on December 4. The network will air the 
special on Dec. 19, making it a Marley Christmas. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 13:50:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FB Coach June Jones Goes to Hawaii </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONOLULU (AP) -- Everybody keeps asking June Jones the same  
question. 
</P>
<P>
	Why would a football coach turn down a fat NFL contract for a  
much-lower paying job at a university that is hurting financially 
and riding an 18-game losing streak? 
</P>
<P>
	For June Jones, the new coach at the University of Hawaii, the  
answer is easy. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is something I've always wanted to do,'' he told the  
latest questioner at a recent booster club rally. ``I played here 
(in 1974) and I coached here (as an assistant in 1983), so it 
wasn't a difficult decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically, it's something I wanted for a long time. If it  
wasn't Hawaii, I wouldn't have done it. It wasn't something that 
just transpired in a couple of months. I wanted to do this for a 
number of years, but the timing wasn't right until now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The San Diego Chargers certainly wanted him back as coach. They  
were willing to remove the ``interim'' designation from his job 
description after he replaced Kevin Gilbride in midseason. 
</P>
<P>
	No thanks.  
</P>
<P>
	They offered him a tidy sum.  
</P>
<P>
	Thanks again, but no.  
</P>
<P>
	And, in a last effort to sway him, the Chargers emphasized  
Hawaii's budget problems and dismal record. 
</P>
<P>
	``They tried very hard to talk me into staying, but I have had  
no second thoughts about my decision to leave,'' said Jones, who 
went 3-7 with the Chargers after a 19-29 record as coach of the 
Atlanta Falcons. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't get me wrong, I love the NFL,'' he said. ``I was a  
player or a coach for 20 years. But I enjoy being part of the 
situation here. It's do or die. My alma mater is in dire straits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Hawaii, Jones inherits a team trying to dig its way out of  
the nation's longest losing streak, which dates to 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones will get a sense of where the Rainbows stand on Saturday  
night. Hawaii opens the season at home against No. 21 Southern 
California. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this point, we're not very deep,'' he said. ``We recruited  
players to fill the holes. But a lot of JC players haven't 
practiced and we can't rely on them the first game. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, we're kind of thin. We haven't been able to  
practice the way we want for fear of injuries.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No sooner had he said those words when he was informed that one  
of his starting defensive backs had gone down. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what I mean,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Jones wasn't trying to tip his hand as he talked about the  
Hawaii run-and-shoot offense. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a lot of things we did in San Diego and Atlanta,'' he  
said. ``We're trying to find a niche as to what we can do. A lot of 
times the talent has to dictate it, so we need to get in place to 
be fully efficient.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The challenge doesn't faze him.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm really excited about what we have to get done,'' Jones  
said. ``We know we're backed into a corner. I knew that when I took 
the job. We've known about the deficit and know what we have to do. 
</P>
<P>
	``On the field, we've got a lot of work ahead of us. I'm looking  
forward to the task of making this a winning program again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Only seven years ago, Hawaii was looking up, going 10-2 and  
upsetting Illinois in the Holiday Bowl. There's been nothing but 
trouble since, culminating with an 0-12 record last season and the 
firing of Fred vonAppen. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a firm believer that history and tradition do matter and  
the players need to understand that there is a tradition here,'' 
Jones said. 
</P>
<P>
	His returning players endured a 5-31 record during vonAppen's  
three seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``They haven't won a football game in a while, but they need to  
understand that not too long ago they were Holiday Bowl 
champions,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Jones acknowledges it will take time to get things right.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's going to be some growing pains,'' he said. ``But as we  
get the players in place, work through all the repetitions and 
learn to do things correctly, we'll get better as time progresses. 
But it's not going to happen overnight.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 20:19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Zedillo Faces Cat Calls During Talk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo faced  
catcalls Wednesday from opposition lawmakers attacking his record 
on poverty as he delivered his state-of-the-nation address to 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	The reception Zedillo got in Congress contrasted sharply with  
his strength in polls. A survey published Wednesday in the 
newspaper Reforma found two-thirds of Mexicans approve of how 
Zedillo is governing the country. 
</P>
<P>
	In his fifth state-of-the-nation address, Zedillo steered clear  
of controversial subjects, concentrating on gains in education and 
pledging fairness in July 2000 presidential elections. 
</P>
<P>
	Zedillo said his administration was meeting its economic goals,  
but conceded poverty was a huge problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all know that we need to go faster, and deeper, in  
attacking poverty,'' Zedillo said. ``For this we need a strong 
economy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But applause was sparse, and he was interrupted several times by  
catcalls and sarcastic signs held up by members of the 
opposition-dominated legislature. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're doing well ... with 60 million in poverty,'' read a sign  
held up by congressman Antonio Prats of the left-center Democratic 
Revolution Party during the speech. 
</P>
<P>
	Another held up a sign referring to a $65 billion plan to use  
taxpayer money to bail out failed private banks. Some of the bad 
loans being paid off in that program were actually campaign 
donations to Zedillo's party. 
</P>
<P>
	Zedillo pledged that there would be ``no political use of public  
funds in 2000, as there never has been any such use in any year of 
this administration,'' -- drawing a roar of disbelief from the 
floor. 
</P>
<P>
	He drew his biggest applause when he said, ``This government  
will continue to handle the conflicts that have caused so much 
concern using legality, never authoritarianism, and tolerance, 
never violent confrontation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The last time Zedillo delivered a state-of-the-nation address,  
the peso had plummeted, the government was chopping its budget and 
lawmakers were screaming about a mammoth bank bailout plan. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, the economy is sound and, according to a new poll,  
Zedillo's popularity is at an all-time high. 
</P>
<P>
	The peso is trading stronger than it was a year ago, the stock  
market's IPC index has risen from under 3,000 points to over 5,000, 
and inflation is in line with a 13 percent goal for the year. 
</P>
<P>
	The budget, slashed four times last year because of diminishing  
oil revenues, contains an $840 million surplus in the first half of 
1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet the Reforma poll also suggests Zedillo's support has more to  
do with his character than his performance. Forty-seven percent 
gave him high marks for honesty, compared with 14 percent 
describing him as ``bad'' or ``very bad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But in regard to the economy -- which Mexicans identify as the  
greatest problem facing their country -- approval and disapproval 
for Zedillo's policies was about even at 30 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Two-thirds of those surveyed say they believe that after  
Zedillo's term ends next year, the country will have an economic 
crisis like those that have frequently followed presidential 
transitions. The poll of 1,550 people has a margin of error of 2.5 
percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	Zedillo has faced criticism that the growth -- gross domestic  
product rose a healthy 2.6 percent in the first half of the year -- 
hasn't yet filtered down to most Mexicans. 
</P>
<P>
	In what his supporters is an attempt to encourage greater  
democracy, Zedillo has declined to name a successor for the first 
time since his party took power 70 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	That opens the way for the ruling party's first primary.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
