<DOCNO> APW19990901.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 20:19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Zedillo Faces Cat Calls During Talk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo faced  
catcalls Wednesday from opposition lawmakers attacking his record 
on poverty as he delivered his state-of-the-nation address to 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	The reception Zedillo got in Congress contrasted sharply with  
his strength in polls. A survey published Wednesday in the 
newspaper Reforma found two-thirds of Mexicans approve of how 
Zedillo is governing the country. 
</P>
<P>
	In his fifth state-of-the-nation address, Zedillo steered clear  
of controversial subjects, concentrating on gains in education and 
pledging fairness in July 2000 presidential elections. 
</P>
<P>
	Zedillo said his administration was meeting its economic goals,  
but conceded poverty was a huge problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all know that we need to go faster, and deeper, in  
attacking poverty,'' Zedillo said. ``For this we need a strong 
economy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But applause was sparse, and he was interrupted several times by  
catcalls and sarcastic signs held up by members of the 
opposition-dominated legislature. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're doing well ... with 60 million in poverty,'' read a sign  
held up by congressman Antonio Prats of the left-center Democratic 
Revolution Party during the speech. 
</P>
<P>
	Another held up a sign referring to a $65 billion plan to use  
taxpayer money to bail out failed private banks. Some of the bad 
loans being paid off in that program were actually campaign 
donations to Zedillo's party. 
</P>
<P>
	Zedillo pledged that there would be ``no political use of public  
funds in 2000, as there never has been any such use in any year of 
this administration,'' -- drawing a roar of disbelief from the 
floor. 
</P>
<P>
	He drew his biggest applause when he said, ``This government  
will continue to handle the conflicts that have caused so much 
concern using legality, never authoritarianism, and tolerance, 
never violent confrontation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The last time Zedillo delivered a state-of-the-nation address,  
the peso had plummeted, the government was chopping its budget and 
lawmakers were screaming about a mammoth bank bailout plan. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, the economy is sound and, according to a new poll,  
Zedillo's popularity is at an all-time high. 
</P>
<P>
	The peso is trading stronger than it was a year ago, the stock  
market's IPC index has risen from under 3,000 points to over 5,000, 
and inflation is in line with a 13 percent goal for the year. 
</P>
<P>
	The budget, slashed four times last year because of diminishing  
oil revenues, contains an $840 million surplus in the first half of 
1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet the Reforma poll also suggests Zedillo's support has more to  
do with his character than his performance. Forty-seven percent 
gave him high marks for honesty, compared with 14 percent 
describing him as ``bad'' or ``very bad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But in regard to the economy -- which Mexicans identify as the  
greatest problem facing their country -- approval and disapproval 
for Zedillo's policies was about even at 30 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Two-thirds of those surveyed say they believe that after  
Zedillo's term ends next year, the country will have an economic 
crisis like those that have frequently followed presidential 
transitions. The poll of 1,550 people has a margin of error of 2.5 
percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	Zedillo has faced criticism that the growth -- gross domestic  
product rose a healthy 2.6 percent in the first half of the year -- 
hasn't yet filtered down to most Mexicans. 
</P>
<P>
	In what his supporters is an attempt to encourage greater  
democracy, Zedillo has declined to name a successor for the first 
time since his party took power 70 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	That opens the way for the ruling party's first primary.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
