<HEADLINE> Man Executed in Texas Hacking Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) -- A high school dropout was executed  
Wednesday for beating and hacking to death a Vietnamese immigrant 
so he could have his stereo. 
</P>
<P>
	Raymond James Jones, 39, used a meat cleaver to murder Su Van  
Dang, 51, in a 1988 attack. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones told police Dang tried to run from the house, but he  
dragged him back inside. Dang's body was set on fire in a closet. 
</P>
<P>
	The attack came three years after Jones was released from prison  
for holding up a convenience store. He was the 22nd Texas inmate to 
be executed this year and the 100th to go to the Texas death 
chamber during Gov. George W. Bush's 4 1/2 years in office. 
</P>
<P>
	In appeals rejected by the courts, Jones said he killed the  
victim in self-defense while resisting a homosexual advance, that 
he was mentally retarded and that the theft of the stereo was an 
afterthought, meaning he should not have been charged with capital 
murder, which specifies a slaying be committed as part of another 
felony. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
