<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Willie Mays Sr. Dies at 89 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	REDWOOD CITY, Calif. (AP) -- Willie Mays Sr., the father of the  
Hall of Fame outfielder, died after a brief illness. He was 89. 
</P>
<P>
	Mays, a retired steelworker and railroad porter, died Friday at  
Sequoia Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Mays was a versatile athlete and passed his love of  
baseball on to his son, who played for the Giants in New York and 
San Francisco, and later the Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	Mays Sr. was born in the industrial town of Westfield, Ala., and  
played for black baseball teams in the South. He worked on 
passenger trains as a porter and later in a Westfield steel mill. 
At one point, he and his son, then in high school, played together 
on the mill's semiprofessional baseball team. 
</P>
<P>
	``My father ... made a very good living there,'' Mays said. ``I  
really didn't have a hard time eating like other people around me 
did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mays attended many of his son's games with the Giants before he  
lost his sight because of glaucoma. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to his son, Mays is survived by a grandson.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
