<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alltel Buying Southern Data Systems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK (AP) -- Alltel Corp. is acquiring a privately held  
company that produces software systems for the community bank 
market, company officials said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal between Alltel and Atlanta-based Southern Data Systems  
is expected to close before the end of this year's third quarter. 
Alltel would not disclose details of the acquisition. 
</P>
<P>
	When combined with its existing banking system, Alltel officials  
said the company will have an integrated front and back office 
system for the community bank market. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bankers want to be able to focus on banking,'' said Gary  
Norcross, senior vice president and general manager of Alltel's 
community banking business based in Florida. ``They need help 
managing the technology pieces needed to maintain their 
competitiveness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Southern Data Systems produces products used in loan  
origination, collection management and new account creation. The 
company has 60 employees and has more than 300 clients with more 
than 800 applications installed across the country. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 10:40:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Five Questions With David Ball </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The urban cowboys and honky-tonk girls  
sucked on beers at a country music bar called The Bullpen, and 
cheered on David Ball as he sang his two-stepping anthems. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bullpen, in an industrial area just north of downtown  
Nashville, has returned to its country roots after lasting just two 
weeks as Club Manhattan's, an upscale discotheque. 
</P>
<P>
	Now it's back to being a place where David Ball music feels  
right. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bullpen could be the set of a 1970s Burt Reynolds or Clint  
Eastwood ``good ole boy'' comedy film. The hostess has enormous 
blond permed hair and wears black hot pants and knee-high boots. 
Men who apparently pump some serious iron strut around in tight 
Wranglers, enormous belt buckles, boots, Western shirts and cowboy 
hats. 
</P>
<P>
	Honky-tonks like this still thrive, in a time when there are  
several singers with major label recording contracts who are too 
young to even be admitted through the front door. And Ball, who has 
been crowded off the radio by the pop-leaning sounds of just such 
youngsters, still has an enthusiastic audience there. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, I be-LIEVE,'' Ball begins his biggest hit by drawing out  
the second syllable of the word ``believe'' for dramatic effect. 
``I got a thinkin' problem/seems you're always on my mind/the 
memories go round and round/I've tried to quit a thousand times.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ball, 46, acknowledges he's feeling a little out of place these  
days in Nashville. But like the guy in ``Thinkin' Problem,'' 
quitting isn't an option. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of got me thinking that I need to go find a place to  
go do what I do,'' he said. ``It's still alive. It's still out 
there somewhere. It's too discouraging to look at what's going on, 
and try to fit into that. Good God! 
</P>
<P>
	``One thing that I used to think about country music is that it  
didn't chase the fad. It had an integrity to it that was maybe 
above that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ball was born in Rock Hill, S.C., the son of a Baptist minister.  
With boyhood friends Walter Hyatt and Champ Hood, Ball played 
stand-up bass and sang as part of Uncle Walt's Band, an eclectic 
trio that relocated to Austin, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	In Austin, Ball fell in love with the country music he heard in  
the dance halls, and has played it ever since. He avoided Nashville 
until the mid-1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't like it until Randy Travis,'' Ball said of  
contemporary country music. ``Heck, Ricky Skaggs started having 
hits on the songs that I was doing. And I thought, `This is really 
interesting.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Thinking the time was right, Ball moved to Nashville and was  
signed by RCA. That didn't work out, but a few years later, Warner 
Bros. gave him a second chance. ``Thinkin' Problem'' was a No. 2 
hit in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then his singles haven't done as well, though he makes  
consistently great country music records like the new ``Play.'' But 
in honky-tonks like The Bullpen, he's a superstar every night. 
</P>
<P>
	1. You're having trouble getting radio play. Do you feel out of  
step with what's happening in country music? 
</P>
<P>
	Ball: I do feel a little bit out of touch. To try and chase it,  
and cut my music to where it fits in with what's going on at a 
certain time, I'm not interested in doing that. I'm more interested 
in pursuing my own vision. 
</P>
<P>
	2. It's funny that you're now a standard-bearer for traditional  
country music. It's not like you were born in a log cabin in the 
hills and sang it when you were a kid. 
</P>
<P>
	Ball: But I'm all the more locked into it because of that. I  
grew up in a real heavy folk thing in high school -- which is the 
beginning of country music. And of course I grew up in church, so 
there was also gospel, and radio was playing Roger Miller. 
</P>
<P>
	From my listening, I got into country music at the beginning --  
Jimmie Rodgers. From Jimmie Rodgers I just took it all the way up 
to Merle Haggard and George Strait. 
</P>
<P>
	For the last 10 or 15 years, I really haven't had any  
influences. I never got into contemporary country music. I was not 
a fan of '70s pop, '80s pop, '70s country, '80s country. 
</P>
<P>
	3. Does good country music have to be depressing?  
</P>
<P>
	Ball: Right after I finished my first album, I'd kind of used up  
all of my brokenhearted songs. The second album was more positive. 
But even when I write a positive song, it's an idea like `It's 
Looking Like a Bad Day for the Blues.' That's a big part of country 
music, to me. I think there's a lonesome sound to it that I like, 
that I'm drawn to. 
</P>
<P>
	4. ``Thinkin' Problem'' is your calling card, your biggest hit  
and a song you have to play every time you perform. Do you ever get 
tired of singing it? 
</P>
<P>
	Ball: Doesn't bother me a bit. It's pretty straightforward and  
simple and to the point. And those are the ingredients of a 
classic. That's why I tend to write that way. ... I just like it. I 
like it. 
</P>
<P>
	5. Would you quit if you lost your record deal in Nashville?  
</P>
<P>
	Ball: Gosh, I don't think so. I really like to play and sing.  
The reason I really got into this was to have a great band. I'd 
like to do more or less what Willie Nelson was able to do. Just get 
it to the people. Because they're out there. They want it. They 
want to hear it. And my job is to take it to them. If I can't do it 
through radio, then I've got to put it on the road and bust it 
there. I believe that's how Willie did it, in Austin. That was 
pretty cool, to pull something like that together. He followed his 
music and chased it, went and got it. That would be the way I'd 
like to do it. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 16:10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Blues Defenseman Ed Kea Drowns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Former St. Louis Blues defenseman Ed Kea, whose  
hockey career was cut short by a head injury, has died. He was 51. 
</P>
<P>
	Kea drowned Tuesday in an accident at his family's summer  
cottage in Ontario. 
</P>
<P>
	Kea played 583 games over 10 seasons in the NHL, scoring 30  
goals and 175 points. He spent his first six seasons with the 
Atlanta Flames, who signed him as a free-agent on Oct. 6, 1972. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blues acquired him along with Don Laurence and a draft pick  
in a trade for center Garry Unger on Oct. 10, 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	He was playing for the Blues' Central Hockey League affiliate in  
Salt Lake City in 1983 when he suffered the injury that ended his 
career. Kea suffered severe head trauma when he fell and hit his 
head on the ice during a game. The injury left him physically and 
mentally disabled. 
</P>
<P>
	Kea and his family remained in St. Louis after the injury. He is  
survived by his wife, Jennifer, and four children. Funeral services 
were pending. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 15:02:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Dennis Cuts Hatteras Island in Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NAGS HEAD, N.C. (AP) -- Tropical storm Dennis weakened today and  
began drifting back toward North Carolina's Outer Banks, where its 
first pass had sliced Hatteras Island in half and isolated 
residents of three towns. 
</P>
<P>
	After stalling this morning, the storm began plodding westward  
again early this afternoon at 5 mph, forecasters said. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of rough surf and rip currents, beaches were closed to  
swimmers as far north as Massachusetts' Cape Cod. 
</P>
<P>
	The storm's top sustained wind had slowed to 60 mph today.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's starting to spin down,'' said James Franklin of the  
National Hurricane Center in Miami. ``There's no thunderstorm 
activity keeping it going. Once that happens, it slowly spins 
down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said it was likely to downgraded from a tropical storm before  
the end of the day, but cautioned that it could still strengthen 
again. 
</P>
<P>
	As Dennis approached the first time, vacationers and residents  
were ordered to evacuate the Outer Banks on Sunday. By Monday night 
they began returning when Dennis headed into the Atlantic, only to 
have to leave again Tuesday night when the storm began 
backtracking. 
</P>
<P>
	For those who stayed behind, mostly residents, provisions were  
begging to get scarce today. A convoy of National Guard vehicles 
carrying diesel fuel, water and ready-to-eat packaged meals left at 
dawn today to push as far south as possible along Hatteras Island's 
only highway, N.C. 12. 
</P>
<P>
	The convoy got two-thirds of the way down the island before  
discovering that days of gale-force wind and 14-foot waves had 
severed the 50-mile-long island, cutting an 8-foot-deep channel at 
a point where the island was just a quarter-mile wide. 
</P>
<P>
	``Between Avon and Buxton, it's completely washed out,'' Sgt.  
Joe Baker said by satellite phone as the convoy rushed to get off 
the island before high tide. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were going to get to Buxton, but we couldn't get that  
far,'' Baker said. 
</P>
<P>
	That meant hundreds of people were isolated in Buxton, Hatteras  
and Frisco, and the washout also had cut off their water, phone 
service and electricity serving about 5,000 customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker said the convoy, which included a Humvee, a 5,000-gallon  
fuel truck, a wrecker and a cargo truck, also found as much as 4 
feet of sand from the island's dunes had washed onto parts of the 
highway. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ocean has come in and knocked the dunes down,'' Baker  
said. ``I didn't see any houses down, but we did see some damage, 
some roofs, decks and walkways.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The convoy delivered 3,700 meals to three fire stations north of  
Avon. Helicopters were waiting for calmer weather to deliver 
hundreds more meals to Hatteras. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's our water line, our power line, our telephone line and  
our kids' access to the school,'' motel owner John Hooper said 
earlier. ``It's our whole way of life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In spite of rain and 55 mph wind that kept other aircraft on the  
ground, the Coast Guard sent a helicopter to Hatteras Island today 
to pick up a woman in labor. Amber Simerly, 19, was taken to 
Albemarle Hospital in Elizabeth City, the Coast Guard said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mandatory evacuations were ordered Tuesday in the communities of  
Nags Head, Kitty Hawk and Kill Devil Hills, along with the mainland 
side of Pamlico Sound. 
</P>
<P>
	While a hurricane watch was lifted this morning, a tropical  
storm warning was still in effect for most of the North Carolina 
and Virginia coast. 
</P>
<P>
	A heavy surf advisory was posted for the whole New Jersey coast,  
and most beaches banned swimming. Along the south shore of New 
York's Long Island, no swimming was allowed at state park beaches 
and it was up to lifeguards to decide whether to let people wade 
along the shore. Two beaches on Cape Cod, at Westport and Eastham, 
were closed to swimmers because of rip currents, officials said 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	At 2 p.m. today, Dennis was centered about 100 miles east of  
Cape Hatteras, 65 miles closer than it was Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Maximum sustained winds were near 60 mph, with tropical storm  
force winds extending outward up to 175 miles from the center. Wind 
blowing onto the shore in the warning area was producing storm 
surges 2 to 4 feet above normal tide, the weather service said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the washout and road damage on Hatteras, waves  
had destroyed five condemned houses on the beach at Rodanthe. 
</P>
<P>
	Derek Pietro of Collegeville, Pa., and his family packed up and  
left their rented Kitty Hawk beachfront house Tuesday as water 
washed under it at high tide. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always come down here this week,'' Pietro said. ``This is  
the first time I've gotten nailed. If it's stalled, it's going to 
be miserable.'' 







  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990901.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 15:02:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
