<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Prison Makes Drake Appreciate Chance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- Two months ago, Jerry Drake sat in a prison  
cell, wondering if his football career had come to an end. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, with Mark Smith still a holdout and Eric Swann still not  
recovered from knee surgery, Drake will start for the second 
straight game when the Arizona Cardinals play their final 
exhibition game Friday night against Oakland. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jerry certainly has overcome a lot of things,'' coach Vince  
Tobin said. ``He's been injured the last two years and, of course, 
he had the scrape with the law. I think he realizes that this is 
his last chance, and he's working very, very hard to make the most 
of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When he completed his six-month drunken driving sentence on July  
3, Drake had no illusions about where he stood in the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	He was 30 years old on the last year of his contract. The  
Cardinals had made him available to Cleveland in the expansion 
draft, and the Browns had passed on him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a guy who got injured two years back to back and had some  
problems off the field,'' Drake said. ``Not too many people would 
give me a chance. But I'm still having fun. I'm not looking at what 
I've done in the past. I'm looking at right now. You get a chance, 
you come in and you do your best and see what happens. That's all 
I'm doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Drake was an NFL long shot from the start. He played at Hastings  
College in Nebraska, an NCAA Division II school, and signed with 
the Cardinals as a free agent in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	He made the practice squad that season, and appeared in 14 games  
the following year. He earned a three-year contract, but injured 
his neck in the 1997 training camp, underwent surgery and 
eventually missed the entire season. 
</P>
<P>
	Back with the team in 1998, Drake started at defensive end in  
the season opener against Dallas, but he was diagnosed with a lower 
back injury, and eventually underwent more surgery and missed the 
rest of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	The medical problems were compounded by his off-field woes.  
</P>
<P>
	Last February, Drake entered an Arizona prison to serve a  
six-month sentence for two counts of aggravated driving under the 
influence of alcohol. In November 1997, while he was injured, he 
was stopped and arrested in the Phoenix suburb of Gilbert, where he 
lives. A month later, he was arrested again by police in Tempe when 
he drove away from a bar. 
</P>
<P>
	Last December, he pleaded no contest to the charges and was  
sentenced to concurrent prison terms of six and four months. 
</P>
<P>
	During his time in jail, he missed the birth of his son Jerry  
Jr. in April. He worked out rigorously in prison and came to camp, 
at 6-foot-5 and 315 pounds in the best shape of his life. Alcohol, 
he said, wasn't worth what it had cost him. 
</P>
<P>
	Now he relishes just being able to play football again.  
</P>
<P>
	``It makes you appreciate life,'' he said. ``It's hard to get  
second chances. I'm just thankful that I am getting a chance to 
help the organization and hopefully make the club.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Drake found himself valuable to a Cardinals organization that  
had earlier indicated it was losing patience with him. Swann, one 
of the NFL's fiercest defensive linemen, seems nowhere near ready 
to play after extensive knee surgery last season. Smith, graded 
Arizona's top defensive lineman last season, is locked in a 
contract dispute that shows no sign of being resolved. 
</P>
<P>
	Then there were injuries to several other defensive linemen in  
training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Drake has gotten his shot, and while he's no all-pro, he's done  
well enough to earn the starting job. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's played pretty well,'' Tobin said. ``He gives us an anchor  
point that you need in the type of defense that we play. Jerry does 
a good job of holding his space and making them run somewhere else, 
and that's certainly a starting point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Drake said he wants Swann and Smith to return because of what it  
would mean for the team. He figures there still would be room for 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	``If those guys were here, I'd still play,'' he said. ``Nobody's  
going to play all the time. I'd still get a few snaps here and 
there. It's great man. It's beautiful. I can't complain. I'm just 
happy, you know.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
